<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Census     06-23 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Census,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Researchers Find Census Thought Destroyed by Stalin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet demographer was quoted as saying
Wednesday that researchers have found the results of a 1937 census
thought to have been destroyed by Josef V. Stalin to hide millions
of deaths caused by his policies.
   Demographer Mark Tolts said the census showed a population of
162 million, the official Tass news agency said.
   The weekly magazine Ogonyok, in a story about the census
published in December, said Stalin claimed a population in 1937 of
170 million even though statistics could not confirm it.
   Tolts did not say where the census results were found, and said
it was too early to use its figures to estimate how many people
died in the purges, collectivization of agriculture and forced
industrialization Stalin imposed in the 1930s.
   Current Soviet reference books put the population at 163 million
for 1917, the year of the revolution that brought the Bolsheviks to
power. The current population is 284 million.
   Ogonyok blamed many of the deaths on a famine forced upon rural
residents by government grain requisitions, but Tolts said Stalin's
repressive policies also apparently were to blame.
   He said the population of the Saratov region on the Volga River
southeast of Moscow declined by 20 percent between 1927 and 1937,
and the population of the Kursk region south of Moscow declined by
14 percent in the same period.
   Stalin told a Communist Party congress in 1934 that the Soviet
population the previous year was 168 million, although census
officials put the figure at 165.7 million and one scientist put it
as low as 158 million.
</TEXT>
