<1ST_LINE>r i PM-ScotchWhisky     06-23 0171</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotch Whisky,0173</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>``Scotch'' to Become Protected Trademark like ``Champagne''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament has passed a law that will ensure the
integrity of spirits labeled ``Scotch'' by making the appellation a
protected trademark.
   Under the law, no whisky can be called Scotch unless it conforms
to standards set by the Scotch Whisky Association: matured for at
least three years, in oak casks with charred insides, and using
only Scottish ingredients like Highland water.
   The law passed the House of Lords Tuesday and now awaits the
formality of the queen's signature, said Bill Walker, a Scottish
lawmaker for the ruling Conservative Party and sponsor of the bill.
   Walker said Wednesday that the new law would empower whisky
distillers to prosecute anyone violating Scotch standards. He said
it was modeled on a law that prevents drinks being called champagne
unless they come from the province of Champagne in France and
conform to its standards.
   Walker said more than 90 percent of Scotch is exported, and
earns Scotland $1.8 billion a year.
</TEXT>
