<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PrisonEscape 1stLd-Writethru a0833 06-23 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prison Escape, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0833,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Capture Two Escapees in Taylor County</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with details of capture; ADDS 2
grafs on further investigation.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CAMPBELLSVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two escaped murderers from the
Kentucky State Penitentiary were captured in a rural field
Wednesday night after a brief exchange of gunfire with state police.
   State police Sgt. Mike Sapp said nobody was injured during the
exchange.
   He said Ronnie Hudson, 29, and Joseph Montgomery, 27, were taken
into custody about 8:21 p.m. in a cornfield about 300 feet from a
temporary command post that state police had set up in a church
parking lot.
   The two were seen crawling through the field by several children
playing kickball behind the church before Wednesday night prayer
meeting.
   The two surrendered after their escape from the field was halted
by a barbed wire fence. Both men were armed, Sapp said.
   Sapp said Hudson had died his hair red, and Montgomery had cut
his hair.
   State police said neighborhood children had found two tote bags
Tuesday night that were believed to have been dropped by the
escapees. The bags contained bullets, clothing and hair dye.
   The escapees, both from Louisville, were among eight who fled
the Kentucky State Penitentiary at Eddyville in western Kentucky
last Thursday. Three others have been captured.
   State police said they believed the two men had been staying
with friends or relatives of Hudson's since arriving in the area
Sunday.
   ``I anticipate some charges against local people for aiding
these fugitives,'' said state police Sgt. Mike Sapp.
   Those still at large include another murderer, James Blanton,
29, of Farler; Billy Hall, 25, of Paducah, serving 23 years for
burglary and assault, and Derek Quintero, 26, of Clarksville,
Tenn., serving 37 years for kidnapping and robbery.
   The eight sawed their way to freedom from an upper level of
Cellhouse 3. The breakout was apparently well-planned, with inmates
on the cellhouse's lower level setting small, diversionary fires to
distract guards.
   Officials in Dover, Tenn., were investigating Wednesday whether
the murder of an elderly couple in rural Leatherwood, a resort
community on Kentucky Lake about 50 miles south of the prison, was
linked to the escapes.
   Stewart County Sheriff's dispatcher Tina Hicks said
investigators from the Tennessee Bureau of Investigation and a
laboratory team from the Tennessee Highway Patrol linked the
slayings to the fugitives, but had no details.
</TEXT>
