<2ND_LINE>PM-Rainbow Family,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Forest Service To Bring In More Officers For Rainbow Gathering</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ZAVALLA, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A plan by a back-to-nature group to hold a
gathering of thousands of people in a national forest has prompted
the U.S. Forest Service to place 24 additional officers on patrol.
   Between 12,000 and 20,000 people are expected to attend the
annual ``gathering of the tribes'' held by the Rainbow Family
during the Fourth of July weekend, officials said.
   The Forest Service blocked roads to the site where many are
camped after the U.S. 5th Circuit Court of Appeals last week
reinstated a temporary restraining order forbidding more than 25
Rainbow Family members from meeting in one place without a Forest
Service permit.
   An appeals panel has not announced if it will continue the
restraining order while considering an appeal of a ruling by U.S.
District Judge William Wayne Justice that the group doesn't need a
permit.
   About 400 ``family'' members are now camped in the forest,
officials said Tuesday. One forest service agent is usually
assigned to the area.
