<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Australia 1stLd-Writethru a0706 06-23 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Australia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0706,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hawke Arrives With Messages for Reagan, Congress, Candidates</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after pvs 2nd graf bgng ``The prime ...'' to
include information and quotes from dinner hosted by Shultz; picks
up pvs 3rd graf bgng ``Hawke told ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Australian Prime Minister Bob Hawke arrived in
the U.S. capital Wednesday for meetings with President Reagan and
the leading presidential candidates and to speak to both houses of
Congress.
   The prime minister and his wife, Hazel Masterson Hawke, were in
Chicago and New York this week. Secretary of State George P. Shultz
and Mrs. Shultz met their helicopter near the Washington monument
and escorted them to their hotel.
   Shultz hosted a dinner for the Hawkes at the State Department
Wednesday night and praised Australia's strong ties with the United
States.
   He said the Soviet Union was posing new challenges in Asia and
the two allies must face the question ``how do we meet the
challenge.''
   On Cambodia, where the Soviet-backed Vietnam is withdrawing some
of its forces, Shultz said ``we must keep up the pressure now that
we see things are going our way.''
   Hawke paid tribute to Shultz as a good friend of Australia and
joined him in calling for an end to agricultural subsidies. ``It's
insane to spend $200 billion on them,'' Hawke said.
   Hawke told a television interviewer his message to Congress and
other U.S. leaders will be Australia's familiar appeal against U.S.
farm subsidies that Australia says are unfair competition and cause
economic harm to ``a first class ally of America, the best ally
you've got.''
   In trade, ``that first class relationship isn't reflected. We
don't like our farmers and our economy being hurt by action here
which is against your own interests. ... That's my message,'' Hawke
said on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning America.''
   ``It's against the self-interest of the United States to be
spending the billions of dollars it is on farm supports and
subsidies,'' Hawke said. ``It doesn't get into the right hands. It
increases the cost and price structure of this country.''
   But Australians, with unsubsidized wheat and meat to export, are
``the innocent people in the middle who get caught by the subsidies
cross fire between the Europeans and the Americans,'' Hawke added.
   The prime minister also branded as ``nonsense'' the New Zealand
anti-nuclear restrictions that barred American warships from
visiting New Zealand and led to New Zealand's ouster from the
three-cornered ANZUS alliance between the two South Pacific
countries and the United States.
   Seventy-four U.S. warships visited Australia last year with ``no
restrictions,'' Hawke said. ``We've got an alliance relationship
with the United States, and we don't buy the New Zealand
proposition that you can have an alliance relationship and say to
your ally, `We're allies, but I'm sorry, boys, your ships can't
come.''
   Hawke will address a meeting of the two houses of Congress on
Thursday and then lunch with Reagan. An afternoon meeting was
planned with Vice President George Bush, probable Republican
candidate in the November presidential election, and the Hawkes'
host at dinner later Thursday.
   The Australian Embassy said Hawke also would meet Massachusetts
Gov. Michael Dukakis, the probable Democratic Party candidate for
president.
   Hawke planned to fly Friday to a speaking engagement at Austin,
Texas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
