<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Taxes     06-23 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Taxes,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panel Wants Two Special Tax Breaks Back in Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House tax-writers want to renew two targeted
benefits of the type that were supposed to be wiped out when the
tax law was overhauled in 1986.
   The House Ways and Means Committee agreed Wednesday to renew for
three years a tax benefit for employees who receive educational
assistance from their bosses, and to extend for one year a special
credit for owners of low-income rental housing.
   The panel, working on a package of miscellaneous tax items
proposed by Chairman Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., is considering
extension of a third special benefit: tax-exempt mortgage bonds
used to help low-income people buying their first home.
   That exemption is a favorite of state and local government
officials, who administer the mortgage assistance. The General
Accounting Office, the auditing arm of Congress, says the program
``does little to increase home ownership opportunities.''
   About $50 billion of such bonds were issued between 1982 and
1986, at a cost to the federal government of about $7.5 billion,
GAO estimated. About two-thirds of the homebuyers who benefited
could have bought their homes without assistance, the agency said.
   Congress wiped out several such special-interest benefits when
it revised the tax law two years ago, contending that the tax
system should not be used to provide subsidies when federal
appropriations could do the job better. But several still remain.
   The committee hopes to complete work next week on this year's
tax bill, which is designed mainly to correct hundreds of errors
that found their way into the 1986 law. The ``technical
corrections'' bill is being used as the vehicle for a few
substantive tax amendments, including those proposed by
Rostenkowski.
   The committee, meeting behind closed doors, voted Wednesday to:
   _Tighten and renew through 1990 an expired law under which
employees could avoid tax on up to $5,250 a year worth of
educational assistance provided by their employers. The benefit was
designed to help lower-income workers prepare for better jobs.
   Under the new version, the exclusion would be reduced as income
rises above a level that is yet to be determined, and upper-income
workers would receive no benefit. No benefit would be available for
post-graduate work. The Reagan administration opposes renewal of
the exclusion, which would cost the government about $540 million.
   _Extend for one year the credit for owners of low-income rental
housing, which is due to expire at the end of 1989. This would cost
$543 million.
   _Write into law an Internal Revenue Service decision that sick
pay, accumulated vacation leave and similar compensation received
by employees of state and local governments and non-profit
organizations should not be taxed when earned.
   _Exempt from Social Security taxes the wages of members of Amish
and other religious sects that have religious objections to such
programs. Committee aides estimated this would affect about 10,000
workers; about 750 self-employed people _ most of them Amish _
already are exempt.
   _Deny Social Security benefits to any person who in the future
is ordered deported as a Nazi war criminal.
   _Exempt from taxation a $10-million trust fund created in 1985
to finance rehabilitation of Enjebi Island in the Enewetak Atoll,
which the United States used as a target for testing nuclear
weapons in the 1940s and 1950s. A similar exemption was voted in
1982 for the benefit of Bikini Island.
   The biggest portion of the tax increase required to pay for the
benefits in the bill would come from corporations that own shares
of other corporations and from owners of single-premium life
insurance.
</TEXT>
