<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ScotusRdp     06-23 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus Rdp,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Blocks Billions in Pension Payments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State and local governments and other private
employers have received some welcome news from the Supreme Court in
a decision that could save them billions of dollars in pension
benefits.
   The court on Wednesday used a case from Florida to limit the
application of two previous rulings, which bar sex discrimination,
in determining retirement benefits.
   ``We're very happy and very pleased,'' said Andy McMullian,
director of Florida's division of retirement. ``We really thought
they would rule in our favor all along and that's why we took it to
the Supreme Court.''
   By a 5-4 vote, the justices said Florida taxpayers do not have
to pay $43.6 million to male state workers who retired between
March 24, 1972, and Aug. 1, 1983.
   The court said that it would be unfair to retroactively apply
the anti-discrimination principles the court first established in a
1978 ruling and greatly expanded in 1983.
   Imposing such extra costs on pension plans would threaten their
existence and, therefore, the rights of other workers to collect
benefits, the court said.
   A U.S. Labor Department study estimates that the ruling will
save public and private employers nationwide from $817 million to
$1.26 billion a year well into the next century.
   The court in 1978 barred employers from requiring women to make
higher contributions to pension plans based on their generally
longer lifespans, even though as a group they receive more
retirement benefits as a result.
   In 1983, the court made it illegal for women to receive smaller
monthly retirement pay than men based on life expectancy when
employees of both sexes contributed equal amounts. That ruling took
effect Aug. 1, 1983.
   Both pension benefit rulings were based on the Civil Rights Act
of 1964 banning sex discrimination in the work place.
   Until Wednesday, the court had not said whether the sex-neutral
principles it established in the pension cases apply to a vast
number of workers who retired sometime between 1964 and 1983.
   The justices said Wednesday that employers, such as the Florida
government, should not be penalized for failing to eliminate all
sex-based pension options after the court's 1978 ruling.
   That decision failed to place employers on notice that all
pension options taking gender into account were illegal, the court
said.
   Some options in the Florida state retirement plan continued to
use sex-based mortality rates until 1983.
   The state was sued by male workers on behalf of themselves and
their wives, who also were beneficiaries of the pension plan. They
said their benefits were reduced illegally because of the use of
the sex-based life expectancy figures.
   Lower courts ruled in their favor and ordered the state to pay
an additional $43.6 million in benefits to them.
   In other decisions, the court:
   _Upheld by a 6-3 vote the way Texas courts administer that
state's death penalty law, dashing the hopes of about 260 death row
inmates.
   _Split 5-4 in upholding an Oklahoma man's murder conviction and
death sentence even though the presiding judge wrongly refused to
exclude one potential juror. The juror was disqualified when the
defendant's lawyer used one of the defense's limited number of
automatic challenges.
   _Ruled, 8-1, in a case from Denver that federal judges may not
throw out an indictment because of a prosecutor's misconduct unless
the defendant can show there would have been no indictment without
such misconduct.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
