<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 0259EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Aldicarb     06-23 0699</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Aldicarb,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EPA Asks 10 States To Develop Aldicarb Management Plans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Under a new proposal, 10 states in the upper
Midwest, Northeast and Southeast are going to have to tell the
Environmental Protection Agency how they will protect ground water
from contamination with the highly toxic pesticide aldicarb.
   In its first action under a draft strategy aimed at protecting
ground water from pesticides, the EPA said Wednesday that it was
considering an alternative that would require ``pesticide
management plans'' from as many as 24 states.
   Only the 10 states in the main proposal, chosen on the basis of
their crops and the general vulnerability of ground water, were
identified: Pennsylvania, Michigan, North Dakota, Georgia, Alabama,
Maine, New York, Wisconsin, Minnesota and Florida.
   In the first five, aldicarb has not been found in ground water;
in the second five, it has been found in concentrations above 10
parts per billion, which is the amount the EPA considers safe.
   Ground water, which supplies drinking water to half the nation's
population, was once thought safe from pollution. But evidence to
the contrary has accumulated in recent years. The EPA has found 63
pesticides in ground water.
   The agency reported that one-third of about 35,000 ground water
samples it tested contained some aldicarb.
   Aldicarb, sold under the trade name Temik by Rhone-Poulenc Ag
Co. of Research Triangle Park, N.C., is used on potatoes, citrus,
peanuts, cotton and other crops to protect them against scores of
insects, root worms and mites. As much as 5.7 million pounds of the
pesticide are used each year.
   Its use already is restricted, and it is banned in a few areas
like Suffolk County on New York's Long Island, where 3,100 homes
must use expensive charcoal filtration to remove it from their well
water.
   In humans, aldicarb can interfere with the transmission of nerve
impulses. High concentrations can cause digestive upset,
dehydration, blurred vision, disorientation, seizures,
unconsciousness and death.
   More than 1,000 poisonings and two stillbirths were reported in
Western states and Canada in 1985 from California-grown watermelons
contaminated with aldicarb.
   The EPA has been studying the pesticide for four years, and
still is investigating how much might be in typical diets. The
manufacturer said Wednesday its latest survey showed ``residues
were rarely present.''
   The agency's draft strategy leaves many key decisions to the
states, like banning aldicarb's use in certain areas and limiting
frequency of application. John A. Moore, assistant EPA
administrator for pesticides, told reporters Wednesday that the
agency probably would ban use of aldicarb in states that refuse to
submit plans.
   States might win EPA approval to permit contamination of ground
water that wouldn't be used for drinking water, he said, as long as
residents of the state have had a chance to comment on the plan.
   Moore said the EPA also is proposing to ban aldicarb use within
300 feet of any well and to require state training programs for
applicators to teach about ground water effects.
   Rhone-Poulenc said in a statement that the EPA's proposal
reflects ``sound principles for drinking water protection,'' and
said it would cooperate.
   A company spokesman, Steve Schmotzer, said, ``We are going to
manage this product even more stringently than required, as we are
doing in some instances now.''
   In some counties in Florida, he said, the company requires
1,000-foot well protection zones. Elsewhere, though, 50 feet might
suffice, and Rhone-Poulenc might seek a variable zone in comments
to the EPA, Schmotzer said.
   Jay Feldman, coordinator of the National Campaign Against the
Misuse of Pesticides, criticized the EPA for not considering
non-chemical strategies, such as crop rotations, in calculating the
costs and benefits of aldicarb use.
   In addition to the five states from which EPA wants management
plans, aldicarb also has been found in California, Massachusetts,
North Carolina, New Jersey, Rhode Island and Virgina in
concentrations above 10 ppb, and in Arizona, Arkansas, Oregon,
Texas and Washington in concentrations below that.
   The EPA's proposal also would require Rhone-Poulenc to monitor
ground water the agency considers highly vulnerable in Connecticut,
Hawaii, Idaho, Illinois, Indiana, Kansas, Massachusetts, Missouri,
Montana, Nebraska, New Hampshire, Ohio, Rhode Island, South
Carolina, South Dakota and Vermont.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
