<DOCNO> AP880623-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 0302EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DefenseProbe-Weinberger     06-23 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defense Probe-Weinberger,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Weinberger Fears Overreaction to Pentagon Fraud Disclosures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Defense Probe Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Defense Secretary Caspar W. Weinberger
says he's afraid there will be a dangerous overreaction by Congress
and the public to disclosures of a massive Pentagon fraud and
bribery investigation.
   ``You don't close a bank because there's been a bank robbery,''
Weinberger said in an interview Wednesday.
   ``And you don't conclude that we don't need a strong defense
because of the actions of some faithless employees. It's important
to bear in mind that the needs of defense haven't changed at all as
a result of these stories.''
   Weinberger also said that he had no apologies to make for his
management style while serving as secretary of defense. He said he
didn't know about the federal investigation until it was revealed
last week. Nor, he said, did he have any suspicions of wrongdoing
before he left office last November.
   ``I think the (contract) procedures in effect are proper,'' the
former defense chief and presidential confidant said.
   ``We needed to regain military strength quickly and we did. But
I didn't exercise any hands-off management technique. I had
briefings regularly, once a week or every two weeks, on the major
weapons programs.
   ``But no matter how careful you are, you're not going to be able
to eliminate dishonesty.''
   Weinberger served almost seven years as secretary of defense
before stepping down because of the ill health of his wife.
According to the Justice Department, the ongoing fraud and bribery
probe began during his tenure and involved, at least to some
extent, contracting actions that occurred before his departure.
   Justice Department officials say the inquiry centers on
allegations that Pentagon executives took bribes from private
military consultants who were seeking classified contract
information for their clients.
   Weinberger insisted he had seen nothing in news reports about
the FBI investigation to call into question the contracting rules
and regulations used by the Pentagon. He also complained that talk
of scandal was prompting lawmakers to twist facts about the
administration's performance.
   ``We need to keep a sense of proportion without jumping to
conclusions,'' he said. ``The Pentagon awards 52,000 contracts
every single day, and inevitably there may be some faithless or
dishonest people.
   ``Now, a lot of totally incorrect statements are being made in
the heat of battle. Sen. (Charles) Grassley (R-Iowa) said 6 percent
of defense contracts are awarded competitively. It's really 60
percent. Sixty percent of the contracts by dollar value. It's 82
percent by number of contract actions.''
   Weinberger's defense of the Pentagon came just one day after
President Reagan offered similar observations, saying bribery and
fraud were ``understandable'' within the huge bureaucracy of the
Pentagon and that no one could keep track of all defense employees
and military contractors.
   While echoing those views, Weinberger made clear he did not
condone the misconduct.
   ``I don't have any hesitancy in saying anyone found guilty of
bribing or receiving bribes or giving out classified information
ought to be administered full punishment,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
