<2ND_LINE>AM-Train Derailment, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0437,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Train Derailment Ignites Fire In Ky.; 2,500 Evacuated; Flights
Banned</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 1st graf and ADD one graf to UPDATE with comment from
CSX CORRECTING that 36 cars of 121-car train derailed, sted 32-car
train derailed; include route of train.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CROFTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty-six cars of train derailed and one
car filled with phosphorus burst into flames Wednesday night,
forcing 2,500 people to evacuate and bans on flights over four
counties, officials said.
   No injuries were reported, said Don Armstrong, spokesman for the
state Disaster and Emergency Services in Frankfort.
   He said a phosphorus fire cannot be quenched and must burn
itself out. Smoke from the fire could explode when temperatures
reach 90 degrees, he said.
   ``You're talking about big, big, big trouble,'' Armstrong said.
``Water makes it burn hotter.''
   The evacuation was ordered for residents of Nortonville, Graham
and White Plains downwind to the east of the burning car, which
derailed in Christian County near the Hopkin County line.
   The Federal Aviation Administration early Thursday restricted
all air travel over those counties and over Muhlenberg and McLean
counties. Two highways also were closed, officials said.
   The CSX train derailed at 7:55 p.m., 3{ miles north of Crofton,
a community of 800 in western Kentucky, state police said.
Armstrong said smoke from the fire could be seen up to 30 miles
away.
   No one in Crofton, population 800, was evacuated, said Novi
Mainire of the Crofton police department.
   Officials were unable to determine if other chemicals were being
transported on the train, but Armstrong said only one car was on
fire.
   CSX spokesman Ripley Watson said the 36 cars that derailed were
roughly in the middle of the 121-car train, which was traveling
from Nashville, Tenn., to Chicago.
</TEXT>
