<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Biden-Dukakis     06-23 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biden-Dukakis,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Campaign Hails Biden Endorsement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One-time Democratic presidential contender
Joseph Biden has endorsed likely Democratic nominee Michael
Dukakis, nine months after a Dukakis aide circulated an ``attack
video'' that helped push Biden out of the race.
   Biden, a U.S. senator from Delaware, telephoned Dukakis from his
home, Biden's office said Wednesday. Dukakis has a mathematical
lock on the nomination.
   The Dukakis campaign reacted to the call with satisfaction.
   ``Obviously we are delighted,'' said campaign spokesman Mark
Gearan, who praised the Delaware senator as ``someone who has
national stature and has gained a reputation in the Senate as a
leader and a fighter.''
   ``His reputation as an effective and forceful leader on foreign
policy, on education and other domestic issues is something that we
feel can be a tremendous help to our campaign,'' Gearan said.
   Biden, who is recovering from brain surgery, assured the
Massachusetts governor that he would work on his behalf when he
returns to the Senate later this year, his office said.
   Biden's office said the senator told Dukakis he was ``very
confident the Democrats will win back the White House and retain
control of the Senate in November.''
   Biden ended his quest for the presidency on Sept. 23, 1987,
after a week in which his campaign was rocked by admissions of
plagiarism and of false claims about his academic record.
   He was also criticized for lifting sections of other
politicians' speeches without attribution. A videotape, juxtaposing
a Biden campaign speech with a speech by British politician Neil
Kinnock and showing striking similarities between the two, was sent
to various news organizations.
   Biden said he had credited Kinnock on other occasions, but had
neglected to do so that time.
   It was later revealed that John Sasso, Dukakis' campaign
manager, distributed the video. One day after news reports linked
the Dukakis campaign to the video, the Massachusetts governor
admitted that Sasso was the source of the video. Sasso resigned
from the campaign, as did Paul Tully, Dukakis' campaign issues
director.
   Biden, 45, is chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee. He was
released from the hospital last month after successful surgery to
correct an aneurysm near his brain. It was the second aneurysm he
had suffered since February.
   An aneurysm is a ballooning of the weakened wall of an artery
and is caused by disease or injury.
</TEXT>
