<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MoscowChancery     06-23 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Moscow Chancery,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Consultants: Tearing Down Part Of Moscow Chancery `An Engineering
Nightmare'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consultants hired by the State Department have
concluded that to tear down a portion of the new U.S. Embassy
chancery in Moscow would be an ``engineering nightmare,'' according
to a report published today.
   Members of Congress and intelligence officers disclosed last
year that the unfinished building was riddled with Soviet listening
devices.
   The State Department asked a team of engineers, architects and
security experts to study the structure and analyze solutions for
making it secure.
   The consultants, in their initial finding, have concluded that
``partial deconstruction'' of the eight-story building ``isn't
feasible'' and would be more dangerous and difficult than
demolishing the entire the structure and rebuilding, The New York
Times reported today.
   One of the consultants referred to ``an engineering nightmare,''
the Times said.
   The new chancery was to have been the main embassy building for
diplomatic and classified activities. But after $22 million was
spent on it, construction was stopped in 1985.
   A State Department source told The Associated Press the
department has received a portion of the consultants' report, but
the complete report is not due until August. The source said no
decision on what to do about the building has been made.
   Robert E. Lamb, assistant secretary of state for diplomatic
security, told the Times, ``The building experts are saying that a
partial deconstruction isn't feasible, because it is very difficult
to take a portion of the building and build on the existing
structure.''
   ``Just from the efficiency of the construction, you're better
off taking the whole thing down,'' Lamb added.
   The current embassy, which the United States occupied in the
early 1950s, consists of one building. It's undergoing a $32.5
million renovation.
</TEXT>
