<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 0323EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Dial-A-Porn     06-23 0672</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dial-A-Porn,0690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Exchange For Adult-Oriented Phone Lines Draws Mixed Reviews</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM PAUL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The telephone company is instituting a new
exchange for ``dial-a-porn'' and party-line services that will be
available to customers only upon request, in a twist on efforts to
keep youngsters from having access to the services.
   Industry spokesmen say the new exchange could drive the services
out of business in Maryland.
   ``It will infringe on the rights of people who like this
entertainment,'' said Jonathon Golan, who provides two programs of
adult entertainment on 976 lines in Baltimore. ``Their rights will
be violated because (the new service) requires identification.''
   The Maryland Public Service Commission has approved Chesapeake
and Potomac's request to institute the new exchange for all adult
and conversation-line services, which have been available on 976
numbers.
   The new 915 exchange, expected to be implemented by the end of
the summer, will be accessible only by customers who have notified
the company they want to have access to it, said Al Burman, a
spokesman for Chesapeake and Potomac Telephone Co.
   Maryland is the first state to approve the subscription exchange
for dial-a-porn lines, Burman said. Sports lines, financial
services and other information lines will remain on 976 exhanges,
he said.
   ``It would essentially wipe out the vast majority of the 976
industry,'' charged Brad Woodward, treasurer of the Mid-Atlantic
Audiotex Association. Woodward describes the group as a loose-knit
organization of about 175 services in the
Baltimore-Washington-Philadelphia area.
   Callers to many 976 programs, such as teen party lines,
dial-a-date lines or other conversation lines, make the call on
impulse, Woodward said. The change to a subscription-type service
would eliminate those ``spontaneous-response'' callers, he said.
   Under the telephone company's plan, a customer wishing to obtain
access to the 915 lines would have to sign a consent form. Names of
those signing the forms would be kept confidential.
   Customers now can request that access from their phone be
blocked to certain 976 numbers. The new system will work in
reverse, providing the 915 service only to those people who
specifically request it by signing the form, Burman said.
   Across the country, ``dial-a-porn'' and party line services have
drawn criticisms from some who complain that they are too easily
accessible by children who have in some cases run up huge bills
without their parents' knowledge.
   ``The purpose is to provide customers increased control over
which services would be accessed from their telephone service and
to minimize billing disputes with customers,'' Burman said.
   One provider of 976 service in the Baltimore area thinks the
change will have a positive effect on telephone information
services.
   ``I think it's the best thing for it,'' said Joseph Katz, who
operates the International 976 Group in Baltimore, which operates
information services but no dial-a-porn lines. ``You're going to
have more people who are going to come into the
information-providing area. They're not thinking (976 service) is
going out of business. I think they've done away with the
objectionable part of it.''
   Katz agreed that the subscription service could eliminate
billing disputes. ``There's no excuse for somebody to say they
didn't know what they were getting,'' he said. ``They signed up.''
   But Golan contended that the adult-oriented business will suffer
because people won't want to be identified as a subscriber to 915.
``It's a very touchy issue, and it's being approached in a very
negative way,'' he said.
   Tony Parker, an attorney for the Mid-Atlantic Audiotex
Association, said the group is considering legal action to block
the Public Service Commission's decision.
   The commission is using the 915 service to drive dial-a-porn
lines from the marketplace, Parker said, adding, ``What they're
doing is doing indirectly what they can't do directly.''
   Annual revenue from 976-type services is about $330 million
nationwide, according to the Information Industry Bulletin, an
industry newsletter. Of that, about $54 million is from
``dial-a-porn'' lines; $90 million from conference conversation
lines; and $186 million from general-interest lines, such as
recorded sports results.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880623-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 0326EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush     06-23 0641</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Talks Tough On Crime To Sheriffs Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush says the U.S.
judicial system is being ``held hostage'' by politicians and judges
who get their legal views from the American Civil Liberties Union.
   That line won a round of applause from the audience of sheriffs.
But at least one member of the audience _ a supporter of Democrat
Michael Dukakis _ called Bush's positions ``simplistic.''
   Sheriff Robert C. Rufo of Suffolk County, Mass., claimed Bush's
tough talk on fighting crime is ``no more than a Republican
smokescreen to divert attention from where they are weak.''
   Rufo was in the audience on Wednesday as Bush delivered a
strongly worded law-and-order speech to the National Sheriff's
Association. He dismissed some of the vice president's views on
crime as ``complete idiocy.''
   Bush was spending today in Washington with no public appearances
scheduled. However, aides said he planned to meet at breakfast with
former United Nations Ambassador Jeane Kirkpatrick.
   Kirkpatrick is frequently mentioned as a possible running mate
for Bush if he decides to name a woman to his ticket.
   However, Bush spokeswoman Shelia Tate said there was no
indication of what Bush and Kirkpatrick would discuss, and the vice
president on Wednesday reiterated that he had not yet begun to
consider any specific individuals for the No. 2 spot on the
Republican ticket.
   At the same time, Bush made light of recent polls showing far
more support for him among men than among women voters.
   ``You hear a lot about the gender gap,'' Bush told local
interviewers. ``What you do is spell out your positions on the
issues and the gender gap goes away and you win the election.
That's what happened in 1984 and that's exactly what I want to have
happen in 1988.''
   In his speech to the sheriffs, Bush attacked Dukakis without
naming him in what the vice president billed as a non-partisan
address.
   ``For too many years, we've been held hostage by well-meaning
but misguided politicians and judges who get their legal views from
the ACLU,'' Bush said, a reference to the American Civil Liberties
Union.
   The ACLU often takes unpopular positions in representing
individuals or organizations it contends have been deprived of
their constitutional rights.
   Later, Bush told reporters that Dukakis had called himself ``a
card-carrying member of the ACLU.''
   ``That was a quote of his. That is not exactly the mainstream of
Kentucky politics,'' the vice president said.
   Bush reiterated his support for the death penalty for major drug
dealers and for drug-related deaths, but said he would not advocate
such a penalty for those convicted of drunken driving in a fatal
accident.
   ``I draw the line there,'' he told reporters.
   Bush also took another swipe at what is becoming a favorite
target: the since-abandoned Massachusetts program for prison
furloughs under which some convicted first-degree murderers were
let out of prison on weekend passes.
   ``The view that all convicts can be rehabilitated is not just
naive, it's dead wrong,'' Bush told the sheriffs' organization.
   ``When first-degree murderers sentenced to life without parole
get unsupervised weekend furloughs and commuted sentences, that
view goes from naive to dangerous, from well-meaning to
irresponsible,'' Bush said.
   Bush recounted details of the case of Willy Horton, a convicted
Massachusetts murderer who was released on a weekend furlough and
accused of raping a woman while he was free.
   Sheriff Rufo, who is the president of the Massachusetts
Sheriffs' Association, told reporters that ``there were 121,000
successful furloughs before that incident.''
   Rufo said that Dukakis inherited but did not initiate the prison
furlough program and now opposes allowing first-degree murderers
out of prison on weekend leave, just as Bush does.
   ``He shares the vice president's views on furloughs,'' said
Rufo, who wore a Dukakis campaign button to the event.
</TEXT>
