<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis     06-23 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says Jackson Receiving ``Very Serious Consideration''</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: May be led</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis ducked questions about whether
Jesse Jackson would be a liability on the Democratic ticket, while
the search for a running mate picked up steam.
   Campaign sources said Jackson _ along with Florida Sen. Bob
Graham, Ohio Sen. John Glenn and Georgia Sen. Sam Nunn _ had been
asked to submit background and financial information, and House
Majority Leader Tom Foley of Washington was being asked as well.
   The soliciting of such information from potential running mates
indicates interest on the part of the Dukakis campaign.
   But at least one potential running mate moved to take himself
out of the running.
   Nick Donatiello, a spokesman for New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley,
said Wednesday the senator had ``made it absolutely clear, both
publicly and privately'' to Dukakis campaign chairman Paul Brountas
that he was not interested. Brountas is heading the running-mate
search.
   Bradley's office has said it had not been asked to supply the
Dukakis campaign with background information. But Dukakis, asked if
that meant Bradley was not being considered, answered with a quick
``no.''
   The Massachusetts governor told reporters Wednesday that Jackson
would receive ``very serious consideration'' as his running mate
despite lacking government experience. Asked about surveys
suggesting Jackson could hurt the Democratic ticket, Dukakis
sidestepped.
   ``I'm not going to be checking a lot of polls, believe me. ...
We all have our strengths and our weaknesses.''
   On the matter of Jackson's qualifications, Dukakis said: ``I
don't know that you have to have held public office to in fact be
qualified.''
   But, he added, ``It helps.''
   In general, Dukakis was unwilling to say much about the search
for his running mate.
   ``I don't think it's helpful ... to do it with press conferences
at the end of the driveway every time you talk to somebody,'' he
said. ``We've just begun the process.''
   The probable Democratic nominee today was visiting a day-care
center in southeastern Massachusetts, continuing his attempt to
focus on issues he trumpets on the campaign trial.
   Dukakis picked up the endorsement Wednesday of Sen. Joseph Biden
of Delaware, who exited the presidential race shortly after
Dukakis' top aide, John Sasso, distributed a videotape showing
Biden had lifted rhetoric from a British politician without
attributing the remarks.
   On another front, Dukakis continued to defend himself against
Republican George Bush's attacks on a Massachusetts furlough
program that allowed for the release of a murderer who then escaped
while on furlough and raped a Maryland woman.
   Dukakis said he had since tightened eligibility requirements for
furloughs to exclude first-degree murderers, and said 45 states and
the federal government have some form of furlough system.
   He said Bush was focusing on the furlough-escape case because he
had no record of his own to promote on crime issues.
</TEXT>
