<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NixonLibrary     06-23 0196</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nixon Library,0200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plans Call For Low-Key Building For Nixon Library</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YORBA LINDA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The $25 million Richard M. Nixon
Presidential Library will be a classic-style building that will
blend with the surrounding neighborhood, according to plans.
   The library cleared two hurdles Tuesday with City Council
approval of the environmental report for the project and
designation of the ex-president's adjacent homestead as a historic
site.
   There was no public opposition or debate of the plans by Langdon
Wilson Mumper, a Los Angeles-based architectural firm. The plans
call for a classic revival, concrete and brick, U-shaped building
with a red tile roof to be built next to the wood frame house where
Nixon was born.
   The library is to be surrounded by gardens, a reflective pool,
fountains and 290 parking spaces.
   The city Planning Commission is scheduled next week to review
plans for the 84,500 square-foot, one-story complex.
Ground-breaking ceremonies are planned for November and the library
is scheduled to open in June 1989.
   Nixon, 75, has approved final details and a scale model of the
library. He is expected to attend groundbreaking at the site, about
30 miles southeast of downtown Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
