<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-Soybean Chief,0173</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybean Association President Among Drought Sufferers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Drought-Heat Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONOKE, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wayne Bennett may be national president of
the American Soybean Association, but his lofty position offers him
no protection from the drought that has withered the nation's
farmlands.
   About one-third of Bennett's 1988 soybean crop hasn't been
planted because dry, powdery soil covers the Lonoke County farm he
purchased with his father more than four decades ago.
   The rest was planted ``so we'll have a head start in case it
does rain,'' Bennett said recently. ``You have to be optimistic or
you can't be a farmer.''
   Bennett's optimism turned to joy June 16 when a spotty series of
afternoon thundershowers bathed his soybean fields, located about
25 miles southeast of Little Rock.
   But the rain didn't last long. And Bennett, like most of his
association's 27,000 members in 26 states, is back to watching his
soil turn parched and pale.
   His advice to association members?
   ``Pray for rain,'' he said.
