<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     06-23 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Stocks Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed sharply higher against the
Japanese yen in Tokyo Thursday, while prices on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange slid for the fourth consecutive trading day.
   The dollar closed at 128.55 yen, up a strong 0.95 yen from
Wednesday's finish. It had opened the day more than 2 yen higher at
129.80, the day's high, and briefly touched a low of 128.25 yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, a 64.79-point loser Wednesday, shed another 127.85
points, or 0.46 percent, to finish Thursday's session at 27,732.93.
   ``A sense of fear that the Bank of Japan would step into the
market and sell dollars to stem its rise stopped the buying
spree,'' said a foreign exchange dealer with a major commercial
bank, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Traders said it was not immediately known whether Japan's
central bank actually intervened to slow the dollar's rise. The
Bank of Japan does not officially comment on its market activity.
   The dealer said Japanese institutional buyers were buying
dollars during early trading following Wednesday's advance of the
U.S. currency in overseas markets.
   Traders said the stock market repeated much the same pattern as
Wednesday, when share prices climbed on the higher dollar, but then
tumbled as investors sold off on worries about higher interest
rates and inflation.
</TEXT>
