<DOCNO> AP880623-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 0345EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Drought-Nevada     06-23 0605</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-Nevada,0623</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nevada Reservoir is Drying Up for the First Time Ever</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Drought-Heat Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM GARDNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For nearly three-quarters of a century,
Lahontan Reservoir has made an agricultural oasis of this desert
region, weathering good years and bad to irrigate 65,000 acres of
alfalfa and other crops.
   But after two consecutive winters that produced half the normal
precipitation in western Nevada, Lahontan is drying up for the
first time since its completion in 1915.
   Like many areas in the Midwest and Plains straining under one of
the worst droughts in 50 years, this fertile area will soon be out
of water. Some fields will lack irrigation in a few weeks and by
mid-September, the 600-mile network of canals will be dry,
officials said Wednesday.
   ``We've got everybody on a 70 percent allocation but it's going
to be pretty tough to meet that,'' Lyman McConnell, project manager
of the Truckee-Carson Irrigation District said.
   Ted DeBraga, a Fallon farmer and president of the irrigation
district, said even the 30 percent cutback ``equates to dollars
when you start losing tonnage on the alfalfa.''
   When the flow to the alfalfa taps out, ``we'll just try to keep
it alive in hopes next year will be a better year,'' he said. ``It
isn't a rosy picture.''
   The University of Nevada-Reno has estimated the drought could
put a $14 million dent in the state's agriculture industry, the No.
3 business behind gaming and mining.
   Alfalfa, a legume with small, purplish flowers that is the
region's principal cash crop, is mainly a pasture plant used for
hay, which has fallen into short supply throughout the farm belt
because of the drought.
   McConnell said Lahontan currently holds 121,550 acre-feet of
water, barely one-third its capacity of 314,000 acre-feet. When it
reaches 10,000 acre-feet, or 32.6 million gallons of water, the
gates will be closed to maintain a small reserve for next year.
   An acre-foot is the amount of water that covers one acre to a
depth of one foot.
   The reservoir, which meanders for 20 miles along the former
Carson River bed 35 miles east of Reno, is also a popular
destination for fishing, swimming and boating.
   The project was begun shortly after the turn of the century and
within a decade had transformed the desert area into an
agricultural oasis. Despite close calls in 1924, 1929 and 1931, the
reservoir never has failed the farmers and ranchers it serves.
   Lahontan is fed by the Carson River, which is nearly exhausted,
and by water diverted from the Truckee River flowing from Lake
Tahoe and other smaller upstream reserves.
   While farmers have made their first cutting of alfalfa, most
will at best get only one more cutting rather than the typical
three, said Jeanni Conlan, of the U.S. Agricultural Stabilization
and Conservation Service in Fallon.
   Those who have made four cuttings in the past aren't likely to
be that lucky this summer, she added.
   ``I'd guess there will be little water left to raise a fourth
crop of hay,'' she said. Most farmers make their third harvest
between mid-September and mid-October, about the time the water is
expected to run out, Ms. Conlan said.
   DeBraga said he had not heard of any farmers or ranchers being
in danger of foreclosure, ``but that's always a possibility, even
in a 100 percent irrigation year.''
   ``In years like this, it's that much closer,'' he said. ``Next
year's the tough one. With all the reservoirs being empty like
they're going to be this fall, it would take an excellent year to
get back even close to normal.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
