<HEAD>Dissident Kemp, Robertson Backers Press Credentials Challenge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dissident Republicans are formally
challenging the credentials of Michigan's 77 delegates to the GOP
National Convention.
   The dissidents, who held their own alternative state
delegate-selection convention after a dispute over party rules,
sent the national party their competing list of New Orleans
conventioneers on Wednesday.
   The list is comprised mainly of the more conservative party
activists who supported the unsuccessful presidential candidacies
of Pat Robertson and New York Rep. Jack Kemp.
   They contend the convention they held was proper and followed
party rules to the letter while the one led by supporters of Vice
President George Bush violated party rules.
   The competing delegate lists now must be reviewed by the party's
``contest committee,'' which reports to the national convention's
credentials committee.
   From there, the party has a mechanism for choosing between
competing delegate slates and hearing appeals of those decisions.
