<HEAD>Maryland Voters Favor Dukakis Over Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLLEGE PARK, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis holds a
15-percentage point margin over Republican George Bush among
Maryland voters in a new poll conducted by the University of
Maryland.
   About 49 percent of the registered voters who responded favored
Dukakis, 34 percent favored Bush, 11 percent were not sure, 3
percent said they would vote for someone else, and 3 percent said
they would not vote at all.
   The poll was conducted by the university's Public Polling
Project May 4 and June 7 and contacted 1,005 residents by telephone.
   ``Of course, it's a long way to November, but the traditional
majority registration for the Democratic Party in this state may
give the Democratic candidate the edge,'' said Sue Dowden, director
of the polling project.
   President Reagan carried Maryland in his 1984 re-election
landslide, but the state went for President Carter in 1980.
</TEXT>
