<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel OKs Covert Actions Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Foreign Affairs Committee voted
along party lines in approving a bill that arose from last year's
Iran-Contra hearings to tighten congressional control over foreign
covert intelligence action.
   The full House is expected to pass the measure, with a vote
expected sometime later this summer, but its unclear whether it can
attract enough support to override an almost certain presidential
veto.
   The 22-17 committee vote on Wednesday came after Democrats
defeated a Republican attempt to ease the proposed restrictions.
   The bill would spell out more specifically how a president must
notify the House and Senate intelligence oversight committees when
he authorizes a covert action.
   Under the proposal, a version of which already has been passed
by the Senate, the president would be required to report any covert
action to the intelligence committees within 48 hours of its
authorization.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>South Africa Sanctions Bill To Go Ahead Despite Dim Prospects</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate supporters of a bill imposing harsh new
sanctions against white-dominated South Africa concede they do not
have the votes to override a threatened veto by President Reagan.
   But they said they would battle for Senate passage of the bill
to highlight congressional opposition to South Africa's racial
policies.
   The bill would end most trade with South Africa and call for
withdrawal of U.S. corporate investment.
   Testifying before the Senate Foreign Relations Committee on
Wednesday, Deputy Secretary of State John C. Whitehead strongly
opposed the harsh sanctions measure as counterproductive.
   And Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., the leading opponent of using
sanctions to increase pressures on South Africa to adopt majority
rule reforms, said he will introduce legislation repealing the less
severe sanctions bill passed over President Reagan's veto two years
ago.
   Whitehead said that while the Reagan administration believes
apartheid is repugnant, ``Resorting to drastic remedies, such as
the misuse of American power to destabilize the South African
economy, only increases the chances of a catastrophic outcome for
all South Africans.'
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>House Keeps Space Station Funds in $10.7 Billion NASA Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House approved $10.7 billion to run the
National Aeronautics and Space Administration after defeating a
move to divert $400 million from space station funds into social
programs.
   The measure still must pass the Senate, whose appropriations
committee on Wednesday also voted $10.7 billion for NASA. The
Senate bill, however, assumes that $600 million will be transferred
to the space station from unspent defense funds.
   That proposed fund transfer was called unacceptable in a letter
that President Reagan sent to Sen. John C. Stennis, D-Miss., and
Mark Hatfield, R-Ore., the chairman and ranking minority member of
the appropriations committee.
   At the same time, however, the president said that letting the
space station wither for lack of funds would be ``totally
unacceptable.''
   NASA had asked for $967 million in the fiscal year that begins
Oct. 1 to start the design phase of the $16 billion space station.
Under the bill passed by the House, the agency would get $902
million.
   The NASA funds are part of a $59.7 billion appropriation bill
for the Department of Housing and Urban Development and 15
independent agencies that passed the House 377-40.
</TEXT>
