<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DefenseProbe-Paisley     06-23 0578</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defense Probe-Paisley,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Consultant Allegedly Enlisted Officials to Smuggle
Documents</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Defense Probe Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense consultant Melvyn R. Paisley
allegedly arranged for high-level Defense Department officials to
smuggle classified documents out of the Pentagon and allow him to
copy the papers with the help of his wife, according to a published
report today.
   Citing unnamed government sources, the Los Angeles Times
reported today that Paisley allegedly passed sensitive information
to his major client, McDonnell Douglas Corp., which paid him what
one source described as ``staggering fees'' as a consultant.
   Paisley was retained by the defense contracting firm the day he
left his post as assistant secretary of the Navy on March 31, 1987,
according to the Times.
   James E. Gaines, Paisley's close deputy in the Navy Department
and one of six Pentagon officials stripped of access to secret
documents Tuesday, is suspected of being a major supplier of the
classified materials, according to a document in the investigation,
the Times reported.
   Sources familiar with the investigation told The Associated
Press Wednesday that Gaines is cooperating with government
investigators.
   The investigation that surfaced last week involves allegations
that defense contractors and consultants, many of them former
military men, bribed Pentagon officials for contracting details
that could be vital in winning contracts worth billions of dollars.
   The details on Paisley and Gaines cited by the Times are the
most detailed yet on how investigators believe the alleged scheme
worked.
   The Times quoted sources who said Paisley recommended McDonnell
Douglas hire Adm. James A. Lyons, retired commander of the U.S.
Pacific Command, whose offices were the target of a search warrant
last week, to assist in the effort to sell the company's F-18
fighter-bomber to South Korea.
   Lyons went to work last December to with Paisley on the effort.
   The warrant served in St. Louis seeks a wide range of documents
``relating to the work of Ace Lyons for McDonnell Douglas from
December, 1987, through 1988.''
   E. Lawrence Barcella, attorney for Paisley and his wife, Vicki,
said Wednesday it would be ``premature to make any comment. There
is nothing specific from the prosecutors to comment on.''
   ``This case is still in the evidence-gathering stage,'' Barcella
said.
   Paisley and Lyons could not be reached for comment.
   Paisley's involvement in the sale of F-18s to U.S. allies,
including South Korea, was a major focus of a warrant the FBI
obtained last week to search the office of Thomas Gunn, the firm's
marketing vice president, at the company's St. Louis headquarters.
   The search warrant said Paisley ``has provided McDonnell Douglas
and Thomas Gunn substantial information obtained from government
officials which has been classified and@or confidential or not
available to the contracting public.''
   Bob O'Brien, a spokesman in McDonnell Douglas' Washington
office, repeated a statement the company issued last week when
Gunn's office was searched.
   ``We are not aware of any improper requests by the company to
Mr. Paisley or any improper activities by Mr. Paisley on behalf of
the company,'' the statement said.
   Gaines, who was deputy assistant secretary for acquisition until
he was reassigned Tuesday by Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci,
was regarded as a key aide to Paisley when both were at the
Pentagon.
   Both men worked for the Boeing Co.'s aerospace unit in Seattle
in the 1970s.
   The Koreans, who have indicated they were interested in buying
as many as 120 new warplanes, have not yet chosen between the
General Dynamics F-16 and the F-18.
</TEXT>
