<DOCNO> AP880623-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 0517EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Refusenik     06-23 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Refusenik,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ailing Mathematician Receives Unofficial Word He Can Leave</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An ailing Jewish mathematician who has tried in
vain to leave the Soviet Union for more than nine years said today
that officials had told him they no longer object to his emigration.
   But refusenik Benjamin Charny, 50, said he still had not
received official permission to join relatives in the United States.
   Charny said he received a telephone call Wednesday from his
former workplace telling him that the Ministry of General Machine
Building that oversees it no longer objects to his emigrating.
   Charny's younger brother, Leon, told The Associated Press in an
interview from his Needham, Mass., home Wednesday that U.S.
officials called to say they had been informed Charny would be
allowed to leave.
   Asked about the reports in the United States, Charny said that
because of the high official sources, ``I think it is so.''
   However, he said in a telephone interview that he had no
official confirmation from the Soviet visa office.
   If they are given permission to leave, Charny said he and his
wife Yadviga would join relatives near Boston.
   In another long-time refusenik case, U.S. officials also said
that Yuri and Tanya Zieman and their 11-year-old daughter Vera
would be allowed to emigrate. President Reagan considered visiting
the Zieman family during his trip to Moscow but U.S. officials have
said he did not because high-ranking Soviet officials told them the
Zieman family never would be allowed to emigrate if Reagan visited
them.
   If the Charny and Zieman families are allowed to leave, it would
resolve two of best-known refusenik cases. Beginning last year,
Soviet officials increased Jewish emigration and have allowed most
of the best-known refuseniks to leave.
   But Jewish activists claim thousands of those who have not
attracted media attention remain behind and the Soviet system still
violates their rights to emigration by applying unreasonable state
secrecy criteria and demanding waivers of financial responsibilty
from relatives who stay behind.
   Charny was refused permission to leave because of calculations
on trajectories of space flight he did between 1966 and 1971.
   He had surgery eight years ago to remove a cancerous tumor, and
said he needs surgery for another tumor on his neck. He also
suffered a heart attack recently and said he needs medical
treatment in the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
