<DOCNO> AP880623-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 0539EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Beer     06-23 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Beer,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Beer Bars to Open As Anti-Booze Campaign Finds Moderation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City officials have approved plans to open 133 new
bars, automatic dispensers and restaurants to sell beer as part of
a more balanced approach to Mikhail S. Gorbachev's anti-alcohol
campaign, a newspaper reported.
   But Moscow News said in an article in its Wednesday editions
that Muscovites still have to be lucky to find a bottle of beer
anywhere.
   The newspaper said the city government's decision to allow beer
sales in more places is a ``step toward a more considered approach
to the struggle with drunkenness and alcoholism.''
   ``Life showed that this problem cannot be solved only with
prohibitive measures,'' it said.
   Moscow city officials also ordered a 19 percent increase in beer
production this year, but Moscow News said breweries cannot meet
their deliveries because of a shortage of bottles.
   And more than a month after city officials ordered the
establishment of bars, restaurants and dispensers to sell beer,
there is no sign of them. Moscow News said officials set no time
limit to fulfill the order.
   In one of his first major acts after becoming Communist Party
general secretary in 1985, Gorbachev cracked down on drinking. The
drinking age was raised, prices of alcoholic beverages went up and
the hours of liquor stores were restricted.
   Soviet officials credit the campaign with improving worker
discipline and improving public health, but there also has been
increasing criticism.
   Consumers often have to stand in long lines to buy a bottle of
vodka or wine, and moonshining has contributed to a sugar shortage.
</TEXT>
