<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 0558EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Obit-Day     06-23 0721</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Day,0745</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Irish Eyes Are Cryin' For Tenor Dennis Day, Who Died at Age 71</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dennis Day, a golden-voiced Irish balladeer
whose career as a foil for comedian Jack Benny spanned decades of
radio, television and film, has died after a long battle with Lou
Gehrig's disease. He was 71.
   Day died at his Bel Air home late Wednesday, surrounded by his
10 children and 13 grandchildren, said his publicist, Kitty Davis.
   ``Everyone is taking it very hard,'' she said.
   His wife, Peggy Margaret McNulty was admitted to St. John's
Hospital and Health Center earlier in the day for cardiac tests and
was in stable condition, said nursing supervisor Nancy Gauthier.
Doctors have not confirmed whether she suffered a heart attack, Ms.
Gauthier said.
   The cause of death was not determined, but Day was diagnosed
last year as suffering from amyotropic lateral sclerosis, a
progressive muscular ailment that killed Lou Gehrig.
   He had undergone brain surgery in March after suffering a fall,
and was readmitted to St. John's on June 5, the hospital said. He
was released from the hospital Monday.
   ``I'm very, very saddened by Dennis' death,'' said comedian
Jerry Lewis, national chairman of the Muscular Dystrophy
Association, which Day supported.
   ``Dennis Day was a brave, kind, talented man who showed his love
by giving. All you had to do was ask.''
   Day's career spanned decades in radio, television and movies,
and he was rated as one of the shrewdest talents in the business.
   Born Eugene Denis McNulty to Irish parents in New York City on
May 21, 1917, he was graduated from St. Patrick's Cathedral High
School and attended Manhattan College with plans to enter Fordham's
law school.
   His plans changed when Jack Benny was hunting for a singer to
replace Kenny Baker. A recording Day had made earned him an
audition, and an off-the-cuff wisecrack helped land him the job,
according to a studio biography.
   With all the applicants gathered in an audition room, Benny
called out, ``Oh Dennis!'' Young McNulty replied, ``Yes, please.''
   ``That's it!'' Benny whooped.
   He assumed the name Dennis Day when he joined Benny's radio show
as a singer in 1939, and quickly matured into a comic target for
the host. One of Day's trademark lines was a sprightly, ``Gee, Mr.
Benny!''
   With a nationwide audience on radio, Day gained popularity with
his renditions of ``Danny Boy,'' ``Clancy Lowered the Boom,'' and
other ballads. Another Day favorite, ``Peg of my Heart'' was a
ballad he sang for his wife, said Ms. Davis.
   In 1952, Day disclosed that Irish authorities had banned his RCA
recording of ``The St. Patrick's Day Parade.''
   ``The Irish didn't object to the song or to my singing,'' Day
said, but to shouted exlamations such as ``How are ye, Paddy, me
boy!'' as if he were marching in a parade.
   ``They said (it) sounded like stage Irish,'' Day said at the
time, with some bemusement.
   Day moved to television with Benny's show in 1950, making
irregular appearances.
   In 1951, Day demonstrated his business acumen by landing a movie
contract with 20th-Century Fox. At the time, he was the only Fox
contract player with television rights. He also signed a contract
with NBC, after allowing weeks of bidding between the network and
competitor CBS.
   Day became a regular on such TV variety shows as ``All Star
Revue,'' ``Hour Glass,'' ``The RCA Victor Show,'' ``Max Liebman
Presents'' and his own ``Dennis Day Show.''
   He also appeared in several films, including ``Buck Benny Rides
Again,'' ``Music in Manhattan,'' ``One Sunday Afternoon'' and ``The
Girl Next Door.''
   In their later years, the Days divided their time between their
Bel Air home and a second home in Hawaii. He enjoyed horseback
riding and sailing.
   During a vacation in Hawaii last year, Day became aware of a
muscle-control problem and returned to the Scripps Clinic in La
Jolla, where doctors diagnosed ALS.
   Day's publicist said that though he was confined to a
wheelchair, he continued to make appearances at Irish fairs and
medical benefits.
   ``Up to the end there, he was still doing benefits. After he
found out that he had ALS he said that he wanted to do as much for
this research group as possible,'' Ms. Davis said.
   Funeral arrangements were not announced.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880623-0060 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 0609EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WritersStrike     06-23 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Writers Strike,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Striking Scriptwriters Vote On Contract In Heated Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking scriptwriters packed meeting halls
on both coasts to vote on the latest contract offer in heated
meetings that could decide the outcome to the 16-week-old walkout
tonight.
   Writers Guild of America leaders in Los Angeles urged their
membership Wednesday night to reject the $71 million contract
offered last week by producers. Dissident writers, eager for a
settlement, called for its approval.
   A similar meeting took place in New York. Results of the vote
were to be announced late today.
   Union President George Kirgo called the balloting critical,
saying it would determine ``how we're going to deal with the whole
industry in the future.''
   The guild struck March 7 over the issue of payments for reruns
of one-hour domestic television shows and a bigger share in the
increased foreign market. The union also sought better guidelines
to protect a writer's work and allow writers to re-acquire
unproduced scripts.
   Agreement was reached on matters of creative control, but both
sides remain divided on the rerun economic package.
   Originally, officials had hoped to announce results after the
vote Wednesday night, but the overwhelming response slowed the
tabulation, an official said.
   Guild Executive Director Brian Walton refused to speculate on
how the vote would go.
   ``I don't know how big the vote will be to accept or reject. ...
I don't know how big the divisions really are,'' said Walton, who
received a standing ovation during a nearly hour-long presentation
advocating rejection of the contract.
   Bill Blinn, a member of the pro-settlement Writers Coalition,
told the audience, ``This industry feeds on us, and we feed on it.''
   He challenged the strategy suppositions made by Walton and the
union leadership, telling union members, ``There is one thing that
is absolutely definite ... there is a contract here that can get us
back to work in two days. That is a fact, that's not anyone's
supposition.''
   The union has about 9,500 members nationwide, about 6,000 on the
West Coast.
   Members of the dissident Writers Coalition suggested that if
they could get 30 percent of the vote they would have shown enough
strength to change conditions and force a quick settlement.
   But Kirgo disputed that claim, saying a 70 percent showing for
support after four months of striking would be a strong statement
for the union stance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880623-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 0609EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Salvador     06-23 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Salvador,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governing Party's Split Widens With Choice Of Second Presidential
Candidate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A faction of the governing
Christian Democratic Party has nominated a second presidential
candidate for next year's elections, further widening the split in
El Salvador's top political party.
   Fidel Chavez Mena was chosen unanimously Wednesday by 180
national delegates who gathered at Christian Democratic
headquarters in San Salvador.
   Chavez Mena, 48, is the former minister of the presidency and
communications under President Jose Napoleon Duarte's U.S.-backed
government.
   Julio Adolfo Rey Prendes, a businessman and former foreign
minister under Duarte, was nominated by the party's other faction
on April 29.
   Rey Prendes, 55, has said he will take the matter to the Supreme
Court. In comments to journalists Tuesday, he called Chavez Mena
``a thief.''
   Each faction considers the other's convention illegal.
   Duarte, honorary party president, called last month for both
hopefuls to step aside to make way for a unity candidate in the
March 1989 election.
   By law, Duarte cannot run for reelection. The president is being
treated in Washington for terminal cancer, though his son has said
Duarte will resume his duties in July.
   The bitter infighting has further hurt the Christian Democrats,
soundly defeated as they were by the rightist Republican
Nationalist Alliance, known by its Spanish acronym as Arena, in
municipal and legislative elections in March.
   El Salvador has had an elected civilian government since 1982,
but leftist rebels contend it is only a facade for dictatorial
military rule. They accuse rightist death squads and paramilitary
forces of killing civilians.
   The civil war that has claimed 65,000 lives since October 1979
is generally considered to be stalemated, but guerrilla leaders
recently pledged to step up their military campaign.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880623-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 0610EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Letter-BombArrest     06-23 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Letter-Bomb Arrest,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Woman Arrested In 1980 Letter Bomb Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman wanted for investigation in a fatal
1980 letter-bombing was arrested as she entered the United States
and was jailed pending a bail hearing, officials said.
   Rochelle Ida Manning, 48, was arrested Wednesday as she stepped
off a jetliner following a flight from Israel, where she had been
living as a fugitive, authorities said.
   She appeared before U.S. Magistrate George King, who ordered her
held.
   Ms. Manning, who holds dual U.S.-Israeli citizenship, was
charged with conpiracy to mail an explosive device and with aiding
in the mailing of the device on July 17, 1980, said U.S. Attorney
Nancy Stock.
   Ms. Manning's attorney, Lee Smith, said she also was questioned
by the FBI and postal inspectors about the Oct. 11, 1985, letter
bombing of Arab rights leader Alex Odeh in his Santa Ana office. No
one has been charged in that killing.
   Ms. Manning was charged along with her husband, Robert Steven
Manning, 36, in the fatal bombing of Patricia Wilkerson, a Prowest
Computer Corp. secretary who opened the package addressed to her
boss, Brenda Crouthamel.
   According to an affidavit by Postal Inspector Glenn Porter, the
fingerprints of Ms. Manning and her husband appeared on the letter
bomb sent to the Manhattan Beach-based company.
   Her husband remains a fugitive.
   Ms. Manning, who left her home in Kiryat Arba, on the Israeli
occupied West Bank, was aware of the investigation before she
returned to the United States, Smith said.
   A motive for the bombing has not been determined, said Postal
Inspector Michael Ahern. But, he added, the sending of the
explosive device did not appear to be politically motivated.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
