<HEAD>Senator Wants Actress To Join Him To Resolve Vietnam Legacies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. John McCain is challenging actress
Jane Fonda to take her apology to Vietnam War veterans for her
wartime trip to Hanoi a step further by helping to resolve
lingering problems the war created.
   Fonda apologized last week on national television to Americans
who served in Vietnam for her actions during the trip, which she
said she made in an attempt to help end the killing.
   McCain, R-Ariz., who was a prisoner of war in Vietnam, said he
accepts the apology ``if she is sincere.''
   In a Senate speech Wednesday in Washington, he said Fonda can
demonstrate her sincerity by working to help resolve the continuing
MIA issue in Vietnam.
   He said she also could appeal to the Vietnamese to end the
so-called re-education camps in which members of the South
Vietnamese army or administration are held.
   In addition, McCain said Fonda could help in the repatriation of
the 20,000 Amerasian children who remain in Vietnam.
   ``These issues we know will only be resolved when we can close
this chapter of American history which has caused so much pain,
suffering and division within our society,'' McCain said in his
speech's text, which also was released in Phoenix.
