<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Hyundai     06-23 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hyundai,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strike Ends At Hyundai Motor Co.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hyundai Motor Co. workers accepted
company-proposed wage increases today and formally ended a 26-day
strike.
   Both company and labor union officials said the company's plant
in the southeastern city of Ulsan would resume production later
today after preparation and cleaning.
   ``The settlement is not 100 percent satisfactory, but I am sure
most members would understand what we have achieved,'' said union
leader Lee Yung-bok.
   Company president Lee Yang-sup welcomed the settlement and said,
``All Hyundai officials and workers would do our best to make up
for lost production.''
   Hyundai said the strike cost $490 million in lost sales.
   The settlement will give workers an immediate pay increase of
$106 a month. Hyundai workers earn an average of $800 a month after
five years, including allowances.
   Union leaders called off the strike Monday, indicating the
company had assured them considerable pay hikes if their boycott
ended voluntarily.
   The union's decision prompted Hyundai to announce the reopening
of its plant on Tuesday. But the plant failed to reopen Tuesday as
union leaders changed their mind and made a new demand for payment
of lost wages during the strike.
   The company rejected the union demand but offered a one-shot
payment of $206 to ``encourage workers to work harder to increase
production.'' The union accepted the offer.
   Hyundai planned to produce 720,000 vehicles this year and export
two-thirds of them to the United States and other countries.
</TEXT>
