<2ND_LINE>PM-Battling Buddhists,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scores Injured As Rival Bands Of Monks Battle In Seoul</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 63 people were injured today
when hundreds of rival Buddhist monks and followers clashed with
clubs and rocks over the leadership of a temple.
   Witnesses said fierce fighting broke out shortly after midnight,
when about 150 monks, helped by followers armed with clubs, iron
bars and rocks, stormed the Bongun Temple in southern Seoul to
drive out rival monks.
   Local news reports said clashes contined for three hours before
dawn as about 100 monks barricaded the temple and resisted with
rocks and clubs, injuring 13 people on both sides. In the end, the
attacking faction took over the temple.
   Early today, monks driven out in the initial clashes returned to
the scene with about 100 followers and tried to recapture the
shrine, triggering another free-for-all, the Korean news agency
Yonhap said.
   Some followers used tear gas guns and knives, and clashes
involving fists and clubs went on for four more hours, injuring 50
more people, Yonhap said.
   About 300 riot police deployed around the temple stayed away
during the free-for-all.
   The Bongun dispute dates back to April 13, when South Korea's
main Buddhist sect, Chokye, tried to replace the head priest of the
temple. His followers disobeyed the reshuffle order.
</TEXT>
