<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0594</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Sweep Away Some of The Heat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Violent thunderstorms helped ease a searing heat wave in parts
of the Midwest and Northeast today but the storms brought hail and
wind up to 80 mph to New York and Massachusetts and a tornado to
Florida.
   Thunderstorms developing along a cold front Wednesday night in
the northeastern United States created severe weather in Vermont,
Massachusetts and New York.
   A tornado early Wednesday struck near Lakeland, Fla., injuring
two people slightly as it flipped one mobile home and damaged eight
others, a Polk County spokeswoman said.
   Winds blew to 80 mph at the Schenectady Airport in Albany, N.Y.,
and at Gardner, Mass., and to 74 mph at the Blue Hill Observatory
near Boston.
   In New York, hail as big as golf balls pelted Johnstown, Fonda,
northwest of Albany, and Troy. In Massachusetts, large hail also
hit Middlefield, Chester and Middlesex.
   Meanwhile, 64 cities in 24 states sweltered through another day
of record-breaking, blistering heat Wednesday. Temperatures climbed
into the 90s or above 100 degrees across much of the nation east of
the Rockies and soared well above 100 degrees in the Southwest.
   Afternoon highs of 98 degrees at Pittsburgh and 100 degrees at
Baltimore tied records for the month of June. The all-time record
of 112 degrees for Tucson, Ariz., established on Tuesday, lasted
only a day when the mercury soared to 114 degrees on Wednesday.
   But showers and thunderstorms ushered cooler weather into the
upper Midwest and the northeastern United States early today with
temperatures in the 60s, with 50s and upper 40s in northern Great
Lakes region.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from the
central Gulf Coast to Florida; widely scattered showers and
thunderstorms from the mid- Atlantic states and the Carolinas
across Tennessee, the Ohio Valley and the lower Mississippi Valley
to southern and eastern Texas; widely scattered afternoon and
evening thunderstorms through the northern and central rockies and
the inter-mountain West.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 90s to near 100 degrees
across much of the nation; between 100 and 105 degrees over the
Great Plains, the Great Basin and central valleys of California;
near 110 degrees over eastern Montana and to 115 degrees in the
desert Southwest; in the 70s and 80s from New England, across New
York, Pennsylania, the upper Ohio Valley and Great Lakes region to
the upper Mississippi Valley, as well as the Pacific Northwest and
along the California coast; a few locations across upper Michigan
will remain in the 60s.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 47
degrees at Sault Ste. Marie, Mich., to 100 degrees at Phoenix, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 77 fair; Boston 77 thunderstorms; Buffalo 67
fair; Charleston, S.C. 76 fair; Cincinnati 80 hazy; Cleveland 69
cloudy; Detroit 70 partly cloudy; Miami 80 fair; New York 75 fair;
Philadelphia 82 hazy; Pittsburgh 80 cloudy; Portland, Maine 70
showers; Washington 80 hazy.
   _Central: Bismarck 72 cloudy; Chicago 68 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
76 fair; Denver 72 partly cloudy; Des Moines 75 fair; Indianapolis
78 fair; Kansas City 78 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 70 fair;
Nashville 81 hazy; New Orleans 76 partly cloudy; St. Louis 86
partly cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 76 partly cloudy; Anchorage 55 cloudy; Las
Vegas 90 fair; Los Angeles 60 cloudy; Phoenix 00 fair; Salt Lake
City 80 showers; San Diego 62 fair; San Francisco 56 fair; Seattle
57 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 66 partly cloudy; Toronto 63 fair.
</TEXT>
