<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     06-23 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher In Active Trading, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose in active European trading this
morning, supported by widespread bullish sentiment. Gold prices
were lower, depressed by the dollar's strength.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the dollar was buoyed by the
recent improvement in the U.S. trade deficit, higher U.S. interest
rates and indications that world monetary authorities aren't overly
concerned about a stronger dollar.
   The dollar started the European day on a very bullish note in
hectic trading dominated by buyers. The market then calmed down a
bit, with more regular two-way trading.
   One Italian trader said central bank intervention against the
dollar's rise had been minimal, effectively giving the market a
green light to take the dollar higher.
   ``The dollar is on a forward march,'' a trader at a West German
bank in Dusseldorf said. ``The mood is confident.''
   But another dealer at a U.S. bank in Frankfurt said the dollar's
near-term direction isn't yet clear. ``The market is still unsure
whether the trend will continue upwards or whether there will be
some profit-taking,'' he said.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,
the dollar rose 0.95 yen to a closing 128.55 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted higher at 128.93 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Wednesday's
rates:
   _1.7865 West German marks, up from 1.7740
   _1.4802 Swiss francs, up from 1.4720
   _6.0285 French francs, up from 5.9747
   _2.0094 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9975
   _1,325.25 Italian lire, up from 1,314.50
   _1.2070 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2100
   In London, the dollar rose against the British pound. It cost
$1.7648 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.7710 late Wednesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $448.40 a troy ounce and
at midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $447.60. Both were down from Wednesday's late
bid of $448.50.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $447.80, down from $448.50 late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.68 to close at a bid $449.78.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.99 a troy
ounce, down from Wednesday's $7.06.
</TEXT>
