<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MotoristSlain     06-23 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Motorist Slain,0517</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-State Patrolman Convicted of Murdering Motorist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS GEORGATOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former state highway patrolman faces possible
life imprisonment for strangling a motorist whose death exposed his
habit of stopping young female drivers for lingering talks in the
dark.
   Craig Peyer, 38, of Poway, a California Highway Patrol officer
for 13 years, was convicted Wednesday in his second trial for the
on-duty murder of Cara Knott, 20, of El Cajon.
   A prosecution case strengthened through hindsight and the
inability of the defense to establish an alibi were the chief
reasons cited by lawyers for the jury's first-degree murder finding
after five days of deliberations. Peyer's first trial ended with a
hung jury Feb. 25.
   ``Holes closed in the second trial,'' District Attorney Ed
Miller said.
   ``The jury came to the conclusion that there was an overwhelming
abundance of evidence. I think what we've demonstrated is the
system works, justice has been served, and no one is above the
law,'' he said.
   Regarded as an exemplary officer before his Jan. 15, 1987,
arrest, Peyer was fired after an internal investigation. He is
appealing the firing.
   Peyer was the second officer in the 58-year history of the
agency to be charged with killing a motorist while on duty.
   ``He is crushed. He wants to appeal,'' said Peyer's attorney,
Robert Grimes.
   Peyer was convicted of strangling Knott, a San Diego State
University student, after pulling her car over on Dec. 27, 1986, as
she drove home along Interstate 15.
   Knott's abandoned car was found in a cul-de-sac near an offramp
of I-15, and her body was found in a creek bed beneath an old
highway bridge nearby. She had been strangled before being thrown
off the 65-foot bridge.
   Knott was described by the prosecutor as a careful young woman
who was trained in self-defense and who may have grown suspicious
of Peyer's actions and prompted him to kill her.
   During retrial, jurors heard testimony from 121 prosecution
witnesses, including two dozen women motorists who recalled their
encounters with Peyer. The former officer never made any sexual
advances, and was described by some as helpful and polite while
others said they were scared and uncomfortable.
   Superior Court Judge Richard Huffman scheduled sentencing for
July 20, and Peyer faces a prison term of 25 years to life. Grimes
said he would appeal the verdict at the sentencing.
   Peyer, who was free on $250,000 bail, was taken into custody
immediately after the verdict.
   ``We recognize the extraordinary courage of the witnesses who
came forward and through their soul-searching revealed the truth,''
said Knott's father, Samuel. ``We put our trust in the criminal
justice system and feel justice has finally been served.''
   Peyer's wife, Karen, vowed to stand by her husband.
   ``As a family, we're sticking together side by side,'' Mrs.
Peyer said outside the couple's house. ``It's a really tough time
for us, but we always remain a family and I trust totally in the
Lord Jesus Christ.''
</TEXT>
