<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Obit-Utley     06-23 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Utley,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Journalist Overcame Blindness To Become Conservative Guru</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   T.E. Utley, who lost his eyesight as a child and
went on to become one of Britain's leading conservative
journalists, has died, The Times of London and the Daily Telegraph
announced today. He was 67.
   Utley, who died Tuesday, worked for The Daily Telegraph, voice
of British conservatism, for 21 years, rising to the posts of
assistant editor and chief editorial writer.
   His essays and analyses won him respect as an oracle of
conservative ideology and a scholar of the Northern Ireland
question.
   Born Thomas Edwin Utley, he took the byline T.E. Utley but was
known throughout the newspaper world as Peter. Blinded by disease
at age 9, he adopted the black eyepatch that became his hallmark,
taught himself Braille and graduated from Oxford University with
honors.
   Utley reveled in poking fun at his handicap, often insisting
that as far as he could remember, cars still had running boards. He
spurned the white stick, preferring to be led about by promising
young journalists whose careers he wanted to promote.
   He retired from the Telegraph in 1985 and moved to The Times as
columnist and obituaries editor _ a move that sparked a battle
between the two great London dailies for the title of obituarist of
record.
   Both papers ran his death notice on the front page.
   Asked recently how he would headline his own obituary, Utley
replied: ``Hoist with his own petard,'' a line from ``Hamlet''
meaning destroyed by one's own poison.
   The Times did not oblige, preferring to headline him as
``defender of traditional values in politics and religion.''
   Utley is survived by his wife, Brigid, whom he married in 1951,
and four children.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880623-0077 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 0726EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Tibet     06-23 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Tibet,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Says Proposals By Dalai Lama Are Unacceptable</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China today rejected a proposal made by Tibet's
exiled leader, the Dalai Lama, that would have recognized its
control of Tibet's foreign affairs in exchange for limited
independence for the remote region.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Li Zhaoxing, at a weekly briefing,
said it was ``irrefutable'' that Tibet is an inseparable part of
Chinese territory.
   ``Therefore, to have independence or semi-independence will go
nowhere in Tibet. It is not tolerable or acceptable and even a sort
of independence in a disguised form is not acceptable,'' he said.
   The Dalai Lama, who fled to exile in India after a failed 1959
uprising against China, made the proposal last week in Strasbourg,
France.
   It was significant in that it acknowledged Chinese interests in
Tibet and granted China the right to keep troops in Tibet and run
the region's foreign affairs.
   The Dalai Lama said he proposed a ``middle way'' in which Tibet
would be a self-governing entity in association with China.
   The proposal was seen as a major concession by the Dalai Lama,
who in the past has called for the total independence of Tibet.
Last fall and again in March monks loyal to the Dalai Lama led
bloody anti-Chinese riots in the Tibetan capital of Lhasa.
   Sources in the Office of Tibet in New York said many Tibetans
were unhappy with the Dalai Lama's new proposal and had hoped he
would not give in to the Chinese. In his Strasbourg speech, the
exiled Tibetan leader acknowledged his proposal might be
controversial within the Tibetan community.
   Li today accused the Dalai Lama of attempting to
internationalize the Tibet question.
   ``We oppose any action or activities to be taken by Dalai Lama
in foreign countries which are detrimental to the unification of
the motherland and the national unity,'' he said.
   The Buddhist spiritual leader made his proposal during a private
visit to the European Parliament in Strasbourg. He was not invited
to address the body because of the parliament's concern for
maintaining good relations with China.
   After the speech, China canceled several visits to China planned
by Parliament members.
   Beijing strongly criticized the U.S. Congress for inviting the
Dalai Lama to testify on conditions in Tibet last fall, shortly
before the outbreak of rioting in Lhasa.
   ``We are also opposed to any foreign organizations or personage
who provides a forum for Dalai Lama to make statements which are
detrimental to national unity,'' Li said.
   Asked if there were any good points in the Dalai Lama's
proposal, Li would only say that Tibet ``is entirely a matter of
the Chinese internal affairs.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
