<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PigeonPoacher     06-23 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pigeon Poacher,0211</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Park Poacher Has His Wings Clipped</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man suspected of trapping thousands of pigeons
and selling them to poultry markets has had his own wings clipped
by the Parks Department.
   Domiano Parasmo, 73, of Brooklyn, was taken into custody by a
park enforcement patrolman Wednesday morning and issued a summons
for violating parks regulations that make it a crime to trap birds
or animals in parks.
   Bill Dalton, the Parks Department's chief of citywide
enforcement, sent Parasmo home after he promised to leave the
pigeons alone.
   ``I told him I would check with the people who complained and
maybe we'll drop the charges,'' Dalton said.
   ``(Parks) Commissioner (Henry) Stern doesn't want to prosecute
an elderly gentleman,'' Dalton said. ``He wants him to stop
trapping pigeons.''
   Parasmo has been issued summonses by the Society for the
Prevention of Cruelty to Animals three times and in each case, the
hearing judge dismissed the charges. There is no law against
trapping wildlife on city streets, as long as it is done humanely.
   However, Parks Department regulations say it is a crime to
``molest, chase, wound, trap, hunt, shoot, throw missiles at, kill,
remove or (possess)'' any bird from a city park.
</TEXT>
