<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 0811EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Rainmaking 1st-LdWritethru a0448 06-23 0662</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rainmaking, 1st-Ld Writethru, a0448,630</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs lede to delete reference to ``foolproof'' method;
inserts 2 grafs with costs of rainmaking programs after 10th graf
pvs, ``We've been</NOTE>
<HEAD>Can Rainmakers Help Drought-Stricken Areas?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists, medicine men and farmers have long
sought ways to make it rain on command. While that day may be
nearer, rainmaking cannot yet offer hope for breaking the drought
gripping America.
   Experiments have shown that cloud seeding ``can offer a modest
increase in what precipitation does fall, but it would not break a
drought or anything like that,'' said meteorologist Michael R.
Poellot of the University of North Dakota.
   Studies ``suggest man's ability to modify precipitation is
really quite minor,'' added Roscoe R. Braham, who teaches
meteorology at the University of Chicago.
   ``We're not dealing with a minor problem in the drought, we're
dealing with a major catastrophe,'' Braham said. ``There's no
reason to think cloud seeding could do anything to ameliorate the
dry conditions that we have.''
   Even Tom Henderson, president of Atmospherics Inc., in Fresno,
Calif., the nation's largest cloud-seeding company, conceded that
``weather modification, as a cure-all for drought situations, is
probably not a very viable technology.''
   Bruce Boe, director of the North Dakota Atmospheric Resource
Board, which operates a weather modification program in that state,
held out hope that ``something can be done.'' But, he noted, ``in a
drought, the opportunities are less.''
   Seeding ``might shorten the length of a drought a bit, but you
will not see a dramatic result from it in most cases.'' he said.
   Poellot reported that cloud-seeding experiments have increased
rainfall by as much as 10 percent. But, he noted, ``for cloud
seeding to work, it needs some clouds. So if there are no clouds,
you're out of luck.'' That same thought was echoed by the other
meteorologists.
   ``The atmosphere just does not have any clouds in it; we've been
totally cloud free,'' Braham said.
   ``We've been in the field since June 1, but we've flown very
litte,'' added Boe, whose agency operates an airborne cloud-seeding
program covering 6.6 million acres of western North Dakota.
   North Dakota spends about $1.5 million per two-year budget cycle
on weather modification, half from the state and half from a tax
voted by residents of the counties affected.
   Henderson said that the cost of running a commercial four-month
summertime cloud-seeding program covering 3,000 to 5,000 acres in
the Midwest would typically run from $100,000 to $125,000.
   Making it rain has obsessed mankind for thousands of years, and
many hoped for a breakthrough a few decades ago when the first
successes were achieved.
   In 1946, Vincent J. Schaefer accomplished the goal, although he
actually made it snow, rather than rain.
   Through the centuries, all sorts of less scientific methods had
been attempted, including animal sacrifice, setting out pots of
water, calling on various gods, clashing armor, ringing church
bells and even firing artillery into the sky.
   Schaefer, in a famous Nov. 13, 1946, experiment near
Schenectady, N.Y., sprinkled three pounds of ground dry ice into a
cloud and within minutes snowflakes formed, and a hole appeared in
the cloud.
   A lot of experimentation was done in the 1970s, sponsored by
state and federal governments, but there has been relatively little
scientific work on changing the weather in the 1980s.
   That is partly because of reductions in money available for the
work and partly because ``the scientists succeeded in defining the
situations where rainfall increases looked feasible and those where
it didn't look so feasible, and the window of opportunity kept
getting smaller and smaller,'' Braham said.
   Boe stressed that any cloud-seeding program has to be a
continuing one.
   ``If you're going to start a weather modification program to
deal with drought, and when it's over you bag the program, you're
taking the wrong tack,'' he said. Long-term cloud seeding adds to
the deep ground moisture, and can help resist the damage of
droughts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880623-0080 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 0812EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Vietnam 1stLd-Writethru   06-23 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vietnam, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0487,0551</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Premier Pledges To Press Ahead With Reforms</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout with new prime minister saying Vietnam trying
to break out of its isolation; no pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newly elected Prime Minsiter Do Muoi
said today that Hanoi is trying to end its international isolation
by seeking to end its 9-year-old military occupation of Cambodia.
   The official Voice of Vietnam radio quoted Do Muoi as saying
Vietnam may withdraw all of its troops from Cambodia before 1990.
   According to the broadcast, Do Muoi said that ``to widen
cooperation, first of all, it is necessary to maintain peace and
security. Vietnam is striving to solve the Cambodian issue.''
   Do Muoi, 71, was elected on Wednesday.
   Many non-communist Western and Asian countries have denied
economic aid to Vietnam and otherwise isolated the communist nation
to protest its late 1978 invasion and continuing occupation of
Cambodia.
   Vietnam has said it will remove all its estimated 120,000 troops
by 1990, and plans a pullout of about 50,000 troops this year.
Today's announcement was the first time a Vietnamese leader said
the withdrawal could be completed before that date.
   Hanoi-based diplomats say that under a new pragmatic leadership
that has given top priority to economic development, Vietnam has
made a series of diplomatic initiatives on Cambodia, which not long
ago was a non-negotiable issue.
   Vietnam recently decided to send Foreign Minister Nguyen Co
Thach to attend unprecedented peace talks involving Cambodian
guerrilla factions next month in Indonesia.
   In a speech Wednesday, Do Muoi pledged to continue Vietnam's
Western-style economic reforms to revive an economy Communist
authorities said they weakened through indecisiveness and poor
planning.
   An official Radio Hanoi report seen in Bangkok today quoted Do
Muoi as telling the National Assembly he will ``thoroughly grasp
the renovative spirit'' of resolutions adopted at a December 1986
party congress.
   The resolutions liberalized Vietnam's economy by allowing a
measure of free enterprise and opening up the country to foreign
investment.
   In a report to the assembly Wednesday, Vo Van Kiet, the acting
premier, said people were ``deeply worried'' about rampant
inflation, chaos in the distribution of goods and acute food
shortages in the northern provinces.
   Vietnamese sources had said Do Muoi was the most likely choice
as premier because he is a disciplinarian who can crack down on the
corruption and inefficiency among cadres involved in implementing
economic reforms.
   Some diplomats say the choice of Do Muoi could slow down the
reform momentum, sending a wrong signal to the average Vietnamese,
who preferred Kiet, 66, a pioneer of economic reform.
   Kiet was first vice premier before becoming acting premier after
Pham Hung's death. The radio report did not say whether he would
return to the old post.
   Do Muoi is the third-ranking member of the Politburo, the top
policy-making body. He gave up the vice premiership last year after
becoming the No. 2 man in the party secretariat, where he is said
to have directed a purge of inept and corrupt elements in the
1.8-million-member party.
   He joined the Communist Party in 1939 and held key party and
government posts during the struggle against the French
colonialists, the Americans and South Vietnam.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880623-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 0831EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Party     06-23 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Party,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Central Committee May Get New Members</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New members of the policy-making Central Committee
may be chosen at a national party conference next week, but most of
the sessions will be closed to the public, a Soviet official
indicated today.
   Yuri A. Sklyarov of the Communist Party Central Committee's
Propaganda Department told a news conference that the 5,000
delegates to next week's conference could have the right to elect
new members to the 300-plus Central Committee.
   The new members could replace the 60 to 70 members who have died
or have become so-called ``dead souls'' by losing the positions
that gave them the right to spots on the committee.
   Sklyarov refused to say definitely, however, whether new people
would make it onto the Central Committee or other leading party
organs.
   He was similarly vague about many details of procedure and
agenda for the conference scheduled to open Tuesday. It will be the
first since 1941.
   Sklyarov confirmed a report in the government daily Izvestia
that only the opening and closing sessions of the conference would
be broadcast live on national television, with other coverage
limited to summaries of conference speeches.
   That is likely to disappoint the many reformers who have
published demands in the state-run media for full television
coverage.
   Yegor Yakovlev, editor of the reformist weekly Moscow News, said
Wednesday about 70 delegates were likely to take the floor during
the conference, which government spokesman Gennady Gerasimov has
said will run from June 28 to July 1.
   Sklyarov refused to confirm that timetable, saying only the
conference could decide how long it would sit. He also tried to
suggest there was no fixed number of speakers, saying the presidium
would give the floor to speakers in the order they ask for it.
   Sklyarov said speakers would have the right to amend their
remarks for the written record.
   ``It is up to the delegate himself to decide what his remarks
will look like,'' Sklyarov said. ``That's his right.''
   Sklyarov said ``the most prestigious workers of the various
party organs'' will get together before the conference opens to
decide who should sit on the agenda-setting presidium.
   The restricted coverage of the party conference is similar to
the access at the previous party congress in 1986. As at that
forum, party leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev will give an opening
report followed by selected speakers.
   Gorbachev's speech is supposed to outline his further plans to
reform the economy and open up the party and society.
   There has been a growing feeling among Moscow intellectuals in
recent days that the party conference will not be a reform-setting
gathering, as was predicted several months ago, but rather a dress
rehearsal for the next regular party congress in 1991.
   Gorbachev had said in May he wanted conference delegates to be
strong partisans of perestroika, his term for the restructing of
Soviet society. But public protests in various Soviet cities over
undemocratic delegate selection, and the failure of some prominent
reformers to be elected delegates, indicate conservative party
forces have put a brake on the conference as originally envisaged.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880623-0082 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 0837EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Schoolesegregation     06-23 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-School @esegregation,0076</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study: Urban School Districts Increasingly Segregated Because of
Demographics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   School systems comprised of inner-city
neighborhoods and suburbs that bus students for racial balance are
the most successful at maintaining integrated schools, a study
concludes.
   The finding is one of several contained in a report released
Wednesday at the annual meeting of the National School Boards
Association.
   ``That was one of the more interesting findings, given the
fierce battling that goes on over desegregation,'' said political
scientist Gary Orfield of the University of Chicago. ``The
perception is often that reassigning students to other
neighborhoods encourages `white flight.'''
   ``But the places that have been most successful _ Nashville, Las
Vegas, Nev., most every big city in Florida except Miami _ have
been those where the city and suburbs are in the same district and
you can implement a districtwide desegregation plan,'' Orfield said.
   Researchers, led by Orfield and political scientist Franklin
Monfort of the University of Wisconsin, analyzed data from the 60
largest public school systems between 1967 and 1986.
   They concluded the schools have become increasingly segregated
over that period because of a dramatic rise in Hispanic students
and a steady erosion in white enrollment.
   ``Predictions about central city districts losing the majority
of their white students came true,'' Orfield said Wednesday, ``but
now, not only are blacks still being segregated, Hispanics are
being more segregated at an even-faster rate.
   ``However, the segregation is not the result of whites leaving
public schools, so much as migration patterns and changes in the
birth rates,'' he added.
   Among the report's most significant findings:
   _Total enrollment declined by 15 percent in the 60 districts to
6.7 million over the 19-year period. White enrollment declined by
16 percent, while the number of black students increased by 5
percent and Hispanic students by 103 percent.
   _The 25 largest central city school districts now serve 28
percent of all black students, 30 percent of all Hispanics, but
only 3 percent of white students.
   ``What that means,'' he said, ``is that the school systems that
are decisive to the future of large parts of our minority groups
are almost irrelevant to the white population.''
   _Almost half of the largest public school districts are now in
the suburbs and metropolitan counties alongside urban centers.
   The researchers did not attempt to assess the consequences of
segregation or to propose solutions.
   But Orfield said: ``Schools that serve black and Hispanic
populations exclusively serve a disproportionate number of poor
kids. They continue to do much worse than white schools in academic
achievement, graduation rates, and almost any other measure of
providing a successful education.
   ``And the worst part,'' he added, ``is that almost nothing
substantial is being done to change it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880623-0083 </DOCNO>
