<2ND_LINE>PM-Prison Escape,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Capture Two More State Prison Escapees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMPBELLSVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two more escapees from the Kentucky
State Penitentiary were captured after a brief exchange of gunfire
with police in a cornfield in rural central Kentucky, officials
said.
   The two convicted murderers were among eight inmates who escaped
a week ago from the prison at Eddyville. Three were captured
earlier, and officials in Tennessee were awaiting records to
determine whether a man in custody there was another escapee.
   State police Sgt. Mike Sapp said nobody was injured during the
shootout Wednesday that ended with the capture of Ronnie Hudson,
29, and Joseph Montgomery, 27, both of Louisville. Both men were
armed, he said.
   They were caught about two miles east of Campbellsville and only
about 300 feet from a temporary command post that state police had
set up in the parking lot of the Robinson Creek Baptist Church.
   The two were spotted crawling through the field by several
children playing kickball behind the church.
   Sapp said Hudson had dyed his hair red, and Montgomery had cut
his hair.
   ``No, I never thought we'd get caught,'' Montgomery told
television reporters after his capture.
   Late Tuesday night, state police had discovered tote bags
containing bullets, new clothing, canned food, and hair dye
believed dropped by the two fugitives.
   The eight prisoners escaped from the maximum-security prison by
sawing open their cell doors. They cut through a prison window and
climbed down an extension cord while guards were distracted by
fires set elsewhere in the prison by other inmates.
   Officials in Sullivan County, Tenn., said they were checking the
identity of a prisoner there to see if he might be one of the
escapees. The prisoner fits a physical description of the escapee,
but fingerprint records and photographs would not be available
until sometime today, officials said.
</TEXT>
