<HEAD>Blackout Darkens Israel's Major Cities, Cause Under Investigation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with electric company spokesman
saying outage not result of sabatoge; picks up 9th graf pvs,
``Underground leaders ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's major cities, the occupied West Bank
and the Gaza Strip lost electrical power today for up to three
hours, but a utility spokesman ruled out sabotage.
   At about 11:15 a.m. (4:15 a.m. EDT) power went out in Jerusalem,
Tel Aviv, and as far south as the seaside resort of Eilat on the
Egyptian border.
   Also affected were the occupied West Bank cities of Nablus,
Ramallah and Bethlehem, and the occupied Gaza Strip.
   The Israel Electrical Corp. was investigating the causes, but
company spokesman Avri Ravid told Israel radio about four hours
after the outage that officials had ruled out sabotage.
   Power was restored to most locations after an hour, although Tel
Aviv and some parts of the Gaza Strip remained without electricity
for another two hours.
   Southern District police spokesman Rafi Levi initially told The
Associated Press that police were investigating whether the outage
was a case of sabotage.
   But Ravid later said officials had determined the outage was not
caused deliberately, although they were still were unsure about
what caused the electrical failure.
   Underground leaders of the 6{-month-old Palestinian uprising, in
a leaflet distributed Wednesday, called on Palestinians to
``continue destroying the property of our fascist enemy.''
   The leaflet was one of the most militant directives issued,
urging Arabs to form paramilitary ``strike forces,'' to destroy
Israeli property and attack Palestinians who collaborate with the
Israelis.
   Israeli army officials said they were affected by the power
outage but that the electrical cut did not hamper security
operations in the occupied territories.
   Radio broadcasts appeared unaffected by the outage as stations
apparently switched to emergency power generators.
   In Tel Aviv, long lines formed at banks after computers went
down and tellers had to conduct transactions manually. Outdoor
cafes were packed as shoppers and store owners fled from hot
shopping malls when air conditioning went out.
   Massive traffic jams were reported in Jerusalem and Tel Aviv,
where police directed drivers by hand at major intersections.
