<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Unrest     06-23 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Unrest,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pravda Says Soldiers Deployed in Nagorno-Karabakh</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pravda said today that soldiers have been deployed
in several cities of the disputed region of Nagorno-Karabakh, the
site of massive ethnic protests.
   The Communist Party newspaper warned that those responsible for
the ethnic unrest in the southern republics of Armenia and
Azerbaijan eventually would be held responsible for their actions.
   ``In the past days, the situation in Nagorno-Karabakh has become
even more tense,'' Pravda said in a report from Stepanakert, the
main city of the disputed region.
   Nagorno-Karabakh has belonged to Azerbaijan since 1923, but
Armenians consider it part of their ancestral homeland and are
demanding that it be incorporated into Armenia. The majority of its
160,000 residents are Armenian.
   ``The migration of Armenian families to Armenia and Azerbaijanis
from Armenia to Azerbaijan is continuing. In a number of cities,
including those of Nagorno-Karabakh, soldiers have been brought
in,'' Pravda said.
   A general strike and daily meetings and demonstrations are
continuing in Nagorno-Karabakh, Pravda said.
   It did not say where the soldiers have been deployed, but Moscow
dissidents showed film Monday of soldiers protecting the Armenian
section of Baku, the capital of Azerbaijan.
   Reports said eight Armenians and eight Azerbaijanis were injured
last week in fights in two Armenian villages, Masis and Sayat Nova.
   ``Those who put the long friendship of the two nations in
danger, sooner or later must be held accountable,'' Pravda said.
   ``Only quiet, restraint, a clear understanding of the current
situation can prevent extremely undesirable consequences,'' it said.
   Residents of Nagorno-Karabakh have been agitating since February
to have their territory annexed to Armenia.
   The governments of Nagorno-Karabakh and Armenia have backed the
demand, but Azerbaijan has refused to go along. National officials
have offered an economic and social development plan.
   Officials say 32 people, six Azerbaijanis and 26 Armenians, were
killed in rioting in the Azerbaijani city of Sumgait at the end of
February and beginning of March.
   Pravda said a general strike that began May 23 in Stepanakert
has led to despair among some residents, but they cannot back down.
   ``Many understand the senselessness and absurdity of their
method of self-exhaustion, but there is nothing they can do. The
affair has gone too far.''
   On Wednesday, a resident of Stepanakert said some residents had
been persuaded to return to work by their legislature's request to
central authorities to approve the annexation request.
   The resident said about half of the estimated 30,000 strikers
remained off their jobs.
   Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov said
Wednesday that the annexation request would be taken up by the
Presidium of the national Supreme Soviet, the Soviet Union's
highest legislative body, but that it probably would not be
discussed in the near future.
</TEXT>
