<HEAD>Teen-Ager Held in Shotgun Slayings of Parents, Sister</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Resending to fix paragraphing.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DAVISBURG, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple described as friendly and
church-going and their 11-year-old daughter were slain by a
shotgun-wielding assailant, and police arrested the couple's
14-year-old son in the killings, authorities said.
   Detective Lt. Bruce Naile of the Oakland County sheriff's
department declined to speculate on a motive for Wedneday night's
slayings of Michael and Carol Carnell and their daughter, Candace.
   Their bodies were discovered by police on the kitchen floor of
the Carnells' home about 3{ miles north of Davisburg in
northwestern Oakland County, said Naile.
   Mrs. Carnell, whose age was unavailable, and her daughter were
dead at the scene, he said. Carnell, 35, was pronounced dead at
Pontiac Osteopathic Hospital.
   The boy was at the house and offered no resistance, Naile said.
He was being held in Oakland County Children's Village while
authorities sought warrants charging him with three counts each of
open murder and use of a firearm during commission of a felony.
   Divers recovered a shotgun believed to have been used in the
slayings from a pond behind the home, the detective said.
   An unidentified neighbor told The Oakland Press of Pontiac that
the boy ran to her house about the time of the shootings.
   ``The boy pounded on my door and said he needed help,'' the
woman said. ``He said, `Someone shot my mom and dad and they are
after me.' He was a very frightened young kid. I turned the outdoor
light on. I said, `Don't worry, I'll call the police.'''
   The woman said police advised her not to let the boy inside.
   Police said the boy initially told them his family had been shot
by two men, the newspaper said.
   Another neighbor, who was not identified, told the newspaper
that the Carnells had lived in the small ranch house for five years
after Michael Carnell bought it from his father.
   ``They go to church almost every night,'' the neighbor said.
``They are very nice people. They never hurt anybody. They were
friendly. Carol was very nice. Everytime they go somewhere, their
children were with them. The children go to Springfield Christian
School.''
