<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 1032EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TerroristSentencing     06-23 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Terrorist Sentencing,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Men Sentenced For Smuggling Bomb Into Vermont</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANICA KIRKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BURLINGTON, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys for three men convicted of
smuggling a bomb into the United States say they won't appeal the
prison terms of up to 16 years given to their clients.
   The government alleged the three men, who are natives of Lebanon
and hold Canadian citizenship, are members of a Syrian political
group responsible for several acts of terrorism.
   But U.S. District Judge Albert Coffrin told the men Wednesday it
didn't matter to him whether they belonged to an extremist
political party; his concern was that the explosive device they had
been carrying could have caused serious damage.
   ``The lethal potential, however, is clear,'' Coffrin said. ``Any
victim of a bombing is an innocent victim.''
   Defendant Georges Younan and co-defendant Walid Kabbani each
received a 16-year sentence in federal prison. Walid Mourad, who
pleaded guilty one day before the others went to trial, was
sentenced to eight years in prison.
   Younan had faced the stiffest penalty, up to 35 years in prison.
Mourad had faced 10 years in prison, and Kabbani, 30 years and six
months.
   Younan and Kabbani pleaded innocent but never testified at their
trial. None of the three addressed Coffrin during the sentencing
hearing. Instead, they chose to have their attorneys speak for them.
   ``He says, `I'm not a terrorist,''' Kabbani's attorney Mark
Keller said. ``He simply says, `I know what I am.' ... He asked me
not to beg on his behalf, not to grovel on his behalf.''
   The defense attorneys claimed victory with the sentences, saying
the government had proposed a plea bargain in which 20-year prison
terms were offered in exchange for a guilty plea and cooperation
with the government.
   The three were arrested last October and charged with smuggling
a homemade bomb into the United States through Richford, a small
town on the Vermont-Canadian border. The U.S. government claimed
the three were members of a terrorist group responsible for the
1982 assassination of a Lebanese President-elect Bashir Gemayel.
   Their attorneys described them as mere bunglers as opposed to
professional terrorists.
   U.S. Attorney George Terwilliger III and the FBI, however, said
the three men are members of the Syrian Social Nationalist Party.
The group was founded in the fascist era of the 1930s and was
devoted to the formation of ``Greater Syria'' that encompassed
several Middle East nations.
   Younan's cousin says Younan is a member of the party, but denied
that it was a terrorist group. Attorneys for Kabbani and Mourad
denied their clients were members at all.
   Terwilliger said he felt the sentence was appropriate. ``It's
one of a very few incidents involving a person associated with
Middle Eastern terrorist organization actually being in possession
of explosives on U.S. soil,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880623-0096 </DOCNO>
