<HEAD>Some Arrested Manigat Aides Are American Citizens</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with former prime minister's
nephew and three other U.S. citizens reportedly detained. Pick up
9th graf pvs: `He said...' DELETES last 3 grafs to trim.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ The new military regime today
arrested the former prime minister's nephew in a growing roundup of
members of the deposed government and their relatives, family
friends said.
   The United States has protested the arrests and says at least
two of those reportedly being held have U.S. citizenship. An
independent radio station today said three other U.S. citizens also
were being detained.
   Family friends told The Associated Press that armed men in
civilian clothes early today arrested Alix Celestin, nephew of
former Prime Minister Martial Celestin. The friends said that the
men in plainclothes stole jewelry they found in the house.
   Meanwhile, a newspaper reported the arrests of three telephone
company officials, apparently because they had cut the lines to the
homes of Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy and his top officers during last
week's power struggle between the military and the civilian
government.
   Namphy overthrew President Leslie Manigat on Sunday night and
proclaimed himself president the next day. Manigat is in exile in
the Dominican Republic.
   Manigat said he believes at least 20 of his supporters have been
jailed. Some said Wednesday they were going into hiding. One,
75-year-old adviser Pierre Rigaud, was released Wednesday. His
family said he was fatigued and wouldn't comment.
   A spokesman for the regime confirmed Wednesday there had been an
unspecified number of detentions since the army took over Monday.
No reason has been given for the roundup.
   U.S. Embassy spokesman Jeffrey Lite confirmed that Roger Savain
Jr., son of the also-detained former Minister of Information Roger
Savain Sr., and Robert Benodin, a top Manigat adviser, are U.S.
citizens.
   Radio Haiti-Inter today said Benodin's wife, Mireille, and
Manigat party officials Sandy William and Frantz Jean-Louis also
hold U.S. citizenship and were detained.
   The private daily Le Matin reported today the arrests of Eddy
Jeanty, director of the state telephone company TELECO, and of two
members of his staff, Harry Gerard Loiseau and M. Borgart. The
army, the paper said, arrested them for having ordered the lines
cut to the homes of Namphy and his top officers.
   The United States on Wednesday expressed concern.
   ``We find that alarming as one of the first acts of the Namphy
regime,'' State Department spokesman Charles E. Redman said in
Washington. ``We have taken that issue up with Haitian officials,
making clear ... that we expect strict respect for internationally
recognized human and civil rights.''
   Also said to be among the arrested Manigat aides was Jean
Lescouflair, an Information Ministry official who worked as a
schoolteacher in Miami. Lite could not say whether Lescouflair is a
U.S. citizen.
   
   He said there had been no direct contact between the embassy and
the new government's leadership.
   Namphy ran the country as head of an interim junta for two years
after dictator Jean-Claude Duvalier fled into exile. He turned over
power in February to Manigat, who was elected the previous month in
military-run elections that were rife with fraud.
   Independently run balloting Nov. 29 was thwarted by attacks on
voters in which more than 30 people were killed.
   Last Friday, Manigat placed Namphy under house arrest and
dismissed him as military chief in a dispute over assignments of
army officers.
   Soldiers freed the general Sunday night, captured the national
palace and sent Manigat to the Dominican Republic, which shares the
Caribbean island of Hispaniola with Haiti.
   Col. Acedius St. Louis, information minister of the new military
government, confirmed Wednesday over independent Radio Antilles
that some prisoners still were being held. He did not say how many,
but said they were being treated well.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
