<1ST_LINE>u i PM-BerlinAirlift 1stLd-Writethru   06-23 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Berlin Airlift, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0492,0526</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>^Ceremonies Commemorating Berlin Airlift Open Today</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with today's reenactment, other
details. Pick up 8th graf: `The Berlin...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A vintage U.S. transport plane left Frankfurt for
West Berlin today to mark the 40th anniversary of the Berlin
Airlift, a massive mission to feed and clothe millions of Berliners
sealed off from the rest of the world by Russian troops.
   The C-47 aircraft took off from Frankfurt and landed at
Templehof Airport in West Berlin at 4:14 p.m. at (10:14 a.m. EDT).
   It's a short flight between the two cities, but for the 2
million Berliners blockaded by the Soviets at the end of World War
II, the 250-mile jaunt meant the difference between life and death.
   During the airlift's 15 months, U.S. and British cargo planes
ferried more than 1.8 million tons of food, coal and other vital
supplies to the Allied-controlled sectors of Berlin, an enclave
deep inside what was then Soviet-held territory and is now
Communist East Germany.
   Among the passengers aboard the C-47 flying to West Berlin today
were the U.S., British and French ambassadors to West Germany.
   Earlier, the ambassadors attended the opening of an airlift
exhibit in Bonn and ceremonies at the U.S. Rhine Main Air Base near
Frankfurt.
   Most of the airlift flights originated at Rhine Main.
   Taking part were U.S. Ambassador Richard R. Burt, British
Ambassador Sir Christopher Mallaby, French Ambassador Serge
Boidevaix, West German Defense Minister Rupert Scholz, and West
Berlin Mayor Eberhard Diepgen.
   The Berlin Airlift began June 26, 1948 and ended Sept. 30, 1949.
It was masterminded by U.S. Army Gen. Lucius D. Clay, the military
governor of the American zone of conquered Germany following World
War II.
   Bitter disputes between the Kremlin and the three other
victorious World War II Allies led to the Soviets move to cut
Berlin off from the West.
   Soviet dictator Joseph Stalin was staunchly against creation of
a unified German state in the three Western occupation zones, and
when the Western allies backed a currency reform to speed up
economic recovery of war-torn Germany, Moscow imposed the blockade.
   Just four days after the money reform on June 20, the Soviets
blocked all roads, waterways and railway lines leading to West
Berlin _ 110 miles deep in Soviet-occupied territory.
   In response, Clay ordered all cargo planes available to deliver
provisions to keep the hope for democracy in West Berlin alive.
   The continuous string of small C-47, C-54 and other cargo planes
ferried about 120 tons of supplies to West Berlin daily at the
start.
   By April 1949, the ``Raisin Bombers,'' so-called because the
crews often brought along candy and raisins for Berlin's hungry
children, were bringing in about 13,000 tons of supplies a day.
   After the Soviets called off the blockade on May 12, 1949, the
Western allies continued the flights to the end of September until
normal land, waterway and rail traffic had resumed.
   More than 277,000 flights were conducted during the airlift,
costing $200 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
