<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0462,630</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: Top 5 grafs new with Jackson comments today; pick up 5th graf
pvs bgng ``Brown steered...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson said today he has privately
decided whether he would accept the vice presidential nomination
but has not shared that decision with likely Democratic nominee
Michael Dukakis.
   ``Privately, yes,'' Jackson said when asked the question by a
reporter after a meeting with his state campaign chairmen from
around the country. However, he reiterated the campaign's public
position that he has earned ```serious consideration'' to be
Dukakis' running mate.
   Before departing on a trip to thank his supporters in Puerto
Rico, Jackson said he's certain that Dukakis at some point will
announce the criteria he is using to pick a running mate.
   Asked to assess whether he's been given fair treatment by the
Democrats in convention preparations, he said, ``I feel positive
about it. I feel hopeful about it.''
   He said the process is ongoing, adding, ``The process is one
thing. The conclusion...is another.''
   The director of Jackson's convention operation, Ron Brown, said
Wednesday the Jackson forces want to see some changes in party
rules, but do not anticipate trying to challenge any rules in
Atlanta next month because their concerns are being met through
``accommodations.''
   Acknowledging some sticking points remain on foreign policy
platform issues, Brown nonetheless expressed optimism a consensus
could be reached with apparent presidential nominee Michael Dukakis.
   Brown steered away from any hint of convention turmoil, saying
negotiations with Dukakis representatives have shown ``a real
willingness and desire'' to iron out differences in the two camps.
   He said the campaign wanted ``to make it known that we are going
with a positive, constructive, unifying attitude, to make it known
that we want the party and the ticket to be stronger when it leaves
Atlanta than when it goes in.''
   Speculation about how much of a fuss Jackson would make at the
convention over rules and platform issues has followed the
committee process leading to this weekend's drafting of the
platform in Denver and the rules committee meeting in Washington.
   Jackson has several suggestions for rules changes he wants the
convention itself to address.
   Asked if he would try to change any rules for purposes of this
summer's convention, Brown indicated that probably would not be the
case as long as Dukakis keeps working on shifting delegates to
Jackson in the states where Jackson considers the process unfair.
   The proposals, he said, ``are prospective in nature,'' adding:
``As far as 1988 we are seeking accommodations. And we feel
positive about the way those discussions are going.''
   Jackson wants to see rules changes that would tie the popular
vote more closely to the candidates' delegate counts in states
where it is not directly proportionate. He also wants to make the
so-called ``super delegates,'' who are free to vote as they like,
more representative of the popular vote in their states.
   Later today, Jackson was leaving for a three-day trip to Puerto
Rico, where he won a non-binding ``beauty contest'' primary. But
voting for delegate slates there awarded all 57 to Dukakis.
   While Jackson may be hoping to persuade some of the delegates to
support him at the national convention, his local backers say he is
mainly interested in underlining the role of Puerto Ricans in his
``Rainbow Coalition.''
   Puerto Rico Gov. Rafael Hernandez Colon endorsed Dukakis and
went to New York to campaign for him, angering some Puerto Rican
politicians on the mainland as well as at home.
   Hernandez Colon, who recently met with Puerto Rican political
leaders in New York to patch up any differences, planned to meet
with Jackson.
   The island's 3.2 million people are U.S. citizens but do not
vote in general elections.
</TEXT>
