<2ND_LINE>PM-Destroyer Slaying,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Keeps Death Sentence As Possible Punishment In Paymaster
Slaying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MAYPORT NAVAL STATION, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Navy judge today refused to
rule out the death penalty as a possible sentence in the
court-martial of a sailor accused of killing a disbursement officer
in a robbery.
   Petty Officer 1st Class Ruben Colon is charged with murder,
robbery, kidnapping and receiving stolen property in the March 15
shooting death of Lt. j.g. Ratish Prasad and the theft of the
$94,629 payroll from the destroyer USS Hancock.
   His court-martial is scheduled to begin July 5.
   Defense counsel Lt. Matthew J. Michels asked the judge, Cmdr.
John A. Studer, in motions Monday to rule out capital punishment if
Colon is convicted.
   But Studer said today that capital punishment could be an
appropriate penalty in the case.
   The Navy has not executed anyone since 1849, according to Nick
Young, a Navy spokesman.
   The judge today also denied motions to dismiss some of the
charges against Colon.
   Defense lawyers also are seeking to suppress statements gathered
by investigators and other evidence.
   Most of the cash taken in the robbery was found in a
safe-deposit box that had been rented by Colon, investigators say.
   Colon, an electronic warfare technician from Vega Baja, Puerto
Rico, was arrested April 12 and has been held since then at the
brig at Jacksonville Naval Air Station.
   About 10 members of the Hancock crew are expected to fly back
from the Middle East, where the ship is now on patrol, to testify
in the trial.
</TEXT>
