<1ST_LINE>u a PM-HospitalClosings 1stLd-Writethru a0556 06-23 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hospital Closings, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0556,0467</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nearly 700 Hospitals May Close in Next Five Years, Survey Shows</HEAD>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING to fix garble in keyword line.</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Recasts lead to make clear survey reflects opinion of
executives, and 2nd graf to state that accounting firm paid for
survey.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nationwide survey of 1,400 hospital executives
shows that 48 percent of them think reduced Medicare reimbursements
may force their hospitals to close in the next five years.
   Small, rural and government-owned hospitals in Arkansas,
Louisiana, Oklahoma and Texas are most vulnerable, according to the
survey conducted and paid for by the Boston-based Touche Ross
accounting and management consulting firm.
   Suburban hospitals and hospitals owned by religious
organizations also may be much more likely to close than in
previous years, the survey showed.
   Hospitals in New England showed the greatest increase in the
likelihood of closure, according to the study titled ``U.S.
Hospitals: The Future of Health Care.''
   In 1986, hospital executives estimated that 21 percent of their
facilities might close. In the recent survey, the chance for
closure jumped to 46 percent of local hospitals.
   ``The fact that so many hospitals anticipated failure is even
more dramatic when one realizes that 150 hospitals have already
closed in the last two years,'' said Raymond Cisneros, national
director of health services for Touche Ross.
   If the survey predictions are accurate, 680 hospitals will close
in the next five years, he said.
   Cisneros said the main reason for what the survey called
American hospitals' ``increased vulnerability to failure'' is the
decrease in revenues under the Medicare Prospective Payment system,
a program created in 1983 to standardize the amounts Medicare
reimburses hospitals for in-patient care.
   Almost 70 percent of the hospital executives surveyed said
hospital incomes have dropped since the program's inception.
   In contrast to small, rural and suburban hospitals, inner-city
hospitals and other urban hospitals show no indication of a greater
potential for closure since a 1986 survey, Cisneros said. Hospitals
with the least chance of closure are located in the mid-Atlantic
states and on the West Coast.
   Other findings of the survey:
   _Occupancy rates are at an all-time low. Forty-six percent of
the hospitals surveyed reported average occupancy of less than 50
percent.
   _The quality of care was perceived as declining. In 1986, 55
percent of hospitals ranked the health care available in their
regions as excellent, but in 1988 that number dropped to 44 percent.
   _There are signs of increasing limitations on health-care
delivery. Three-fourths of the hospital officials questioned
believe health care given patients should be curtailed when the
cost of providing that care becomes excessive.
   Questionnaires were sent to hospital executives at all 5,678
acute-care hospitals in the country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
