<1ST_LINE>u a PM-People-NewmanTrial     06-23 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Newman Trial,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Declares Mistrial in Suit Against Actor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA STOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge today granted a mistrial in a
lawsuit pitting actor Paul Newman against a delicatessen owner
after jurors said they could not deliberate impartially after
getting a look at unauthorized evidence.
   Superior Court Judge Howard Zoarski declared the mistrial after
jurors sent a note out of the jury room that they couldn't ignore
depositions that were never entered into evidence but were
inadvertently turned over to them before deliberations began two
days ago.
   The judge's ruling reversed one he made earlier in the day when
he instructed jurors to disregard copies of depositions from
Westport deli owner Julius Gold and others involved in the case.
   Gold had alleged during the three-week, breach-of-contract trial
that an attorney for Newman promised him 8 percent of the stock
from Newman's food company in return for helping Newman's Own Inc.
   The jury, which had deliberated for eight hours over two days,
was sent home Wednesday after its foreman told the court that it
had received depositions from Gold and some defendants and wanted
to see Newman's.
   W. Patrick Ryan, Newman's attorney, said Wednesday it appeared
the clerk who took the exhibits into the jury room inadvertently
also took the depositions.
   Author A.E. Hotchner, Newman's longtime friend who is also being
sued, said, ``Alice in Wonderland falling down the rabbit hole had
a more sane time of it than I did falling in this judicial hole.''
   Gold filed suit against Newman, another Westport resident; his
two food companies, Newman's Own Inc. and Salad King Inc.;
Hotchner, and Kalman.
   Gold claimed that he helped develop and market Newman's Own
salad dressing and was promised the stock. Gold said he contributed
30 months effort to Newman's company and believed that his work led
to its success.
   The defendants have denied all of the allegations.
   Newman's Own, whose products include spaghetti sauce, lemonade
and popcorn, has donated $15 million to charity since 1982.
   Newman said he once considered giving a gift of stock to four
people who contributed to the food venture but Gold was not among
them. He also said he decided not to give away any stock after his
lawyer advised him against it.
</TEXT>
