<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 1242EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Texas-DeathPenalty     06-23 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Texas-Death Penalty,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Death Row Inmate Gets Stay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL L. GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A death row inmate who faced execution
Saturday won a 30-day stay on the same day that the Supreme Court
upheld the state's death penalty law.
   Convicted killer Fletcher Mann got the stay Wednesday from a
federal judge in Dallas because new attorneys in his case asked for
more time.
   Also Wednesday, the high court announced its long-anticipated
decision that it had voted 6-3 to uphold the conviction and death
sentence of Donald Gene Franklin of San Antonio.
   Attorneys for Franklin had contended jurors were not allowed to
consider any mitigating circumstances in sentencing Franklin for
the 1975 abduction-slaying of nurse Peggy Moran.
   Since the high court agreed to hear the case late last year,
only one inmate, Robert Streetman, was put to death. Dozens of
prisoners used the pending case to obtain stays of execution.
   After hearing of the high court decision Wednesday, death row
inmates were predictably glum.
   Mann, 27, who had not yet heard of his stay was philosophical.
``If it's going to happen, it's going to happen,'' he said of the
possibility of his death.
   Many inmates believed the Franklin case, the most serious
challenge to the Texas death penalty law in several years, would
result in a ruling favorable to them and commutations of their
sentences to life.
   ``I feel like an idiot having put my hopes in the court,''
inmate Jim Vanderbilt said. ``This is a bitter disappointment. It's
not easy seeing your friends hauled off to be killed.''
   ``I'm afraid they'll try to get as many as they can before the
next issue comes up,'' said James Beathard, another death row
resident.
   Franklin has turned down interviews since the ruling.
   His attorney, Mark Stevens, said he likely would seek a
rehearing for Franklin but that the high court rarely granted such
motions.
   Stevens said he doubted the pace of executions would quicken and
speculated the court would analyze capital cases on a case-by-case
basis.
   ``It's pretty nice when the Supreme Court of the United States
says you're right,'' said Bob Walt, an assistant attorney general
who handles death row cases. ``The plurality opinion is very close
to what we said in our brief.''
   Walt said it is likely Franklin would be rescheduled for
execution and the Supreme Court would vacate stays issued to other
Texas inmates who cited the Franklin case.
   Texas, which uses lethal injections, has executed 27 convicted
killers, more than any other state since the Supreme Court allowed
the death penalty to resume in 1976.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
