<1ST_LINE>u p PM-PoliticalRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0479 06-23 0888</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0479,890</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 9 grafs new with Dukakis-prison probe, Jackson veep
comments; pick up 10th graf pvs bgng ``However campaign...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURA KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis said today his administration had been
entirely open about a prison controversy under investigation by the
FBI. Jesse Jackson said he has decided whether he wants to be
Dukakis' running mate but would not divulge his decision unless
offered the job.
   Dukakis toured a day care facility at a private business as the
prison probe erupted. The FBI, noting Dukakis' status as the
certain Democratic presidential nominee, took the unusual step of
saying the governor himself was ``not the subject of an
investigation.''
   The FBI said it is looking into a Dukakis administration
multi-million dollar proposal to purchase land for a prison in New
Braintree in central Massachusetts, a plan vigorously opposed by
the community.
   ``The process was as open as it could possibly be... We have
very tough procedures for the acquisition of property,'' Dukakis
told reporters today.
   Jackson, meanwhile, was besieged with questions about the vice
presidential nomination. Had he decided in his own mind whether he
would accept if offered? ``Privately, yes,'' Jackson said. But then
he cut off reporters.
   Republican George Bush had a series of private meetings
scheduled today: breakfast with former U.N. Ambassador Jeane
Kirkpatrick, an afternoon session with President Reagan and
Agriculture Secretary Richard Lyng, and evening meetings with
Australian prime minister Bob Hawke.
   Kirkpatrick has been mentioned as a longshot vice presidential
prospect on a Bush ticket. Some observers believe a woman on the
ticket might boost Bush's support among female voters. A number of
polls have suggested that women are far more likely to back
Dukakis, the all-but-certain Democratic nominee, than Bush, his
likely opponent. But the vice president dismissed such surveys.
   ``What you do is spell out your positions on the issues and the
gender gap goes away and you win the election,'' Bush told local
reporters Wednesday on a trip to Louisville, Ky.
   On Wednesday, Dukakis told reporters in Boston that the process
of picking a running mate had ``just begun.''
   However, campaign sources indicated the pace was picking up, as
several vice presidential prospects _ including Florida Sen. Bob
Graham, Ohio Sen. John Glenn and Georgia Sen. Sam Nunn _ were
invited to submit background and financial information to the
Dukakis campaign for scrutiny.
   One lawmaker, however, said he wants to be crossed off the list
of contenders. New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley said through a
spokesman that he had told the Dukakis campaign he wasn't
interested.
   ``He's absolutely unambiguous about this,'' said Bradley
spokesman Nick Donatiello.
   Pressed about Jackson, Dukakis replied that the second-place
finisher in the primary races was under ``very serious
consideration.''
   However, Dukakis said ``it helps'' for a vice presidential
contender to have held public office. Jackson never has.
   The two met Tuesday in California, after weeks of signals from
Jackson that he should be offered a spot on the ticket. Jackson
said the two talked about the selection of a running mate, but
refused to elaborate.
   Ron Brown, the head of Jackson's convention team, said Jackson
did not directly ask for a place on the ticket.
   Dukakis, who has enough delegates for a first-ballot victory at
next month's Democratic National Convention in Atlanta, betrayed a
flash of impatience when asked about Jackson's refusal to concede
the nomination.
   ``It's over,'' the nominee-to-be said shortly.
   Dukakis on Wednesday won the backing of Biden, who dropped out
of the race last September amid allegations of plagiarism and
exaggerating his academic record.
   One of the most damaging stories to surface at that time was
Biden's liberal borrowing, without credit, from a speech by British
politician Neil Kinnock.
   After Biden bowed out, Dukakis' top aide John Sasso admitted
that he distributed the ``attack video'' featuring the Biden and
Kinnock speeches that triggered the stories.
   The Dukakis campaign had initially denied any role in the
incident. And when Sasso told Dukakis what he had done, the
candidate wavered before finally accepting his aide's resignation.
   However, Biden said later he blamed only himself.
   The Delaware senator's expression of support for Dukakis, nine
months after the collapse of his candidacy, came in a telephone
call from Biden's home, his office in Washington said. Biden is
recuperating from surgery last month to repair an aneurysm near his
brain.
   Dukakis spokesman Mark Gearan welcomed the endorsement, praising
Biden as a ``leader and a fighter'' who can be a ``tremendous
help'' to the campaign.
   Two of the Massachusetts governor's other former rivals for the
Democratic nomination _ Sen. Albert Gore of Tennessee and Rep.
Richard Gephardt of Missouri _ were to be on hand for a pricey
Democratic fund-raiser in Washington tonight.
   In other developments:
   _Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young said reports that his city will not
be ready in time for the Democratic National Convention are
exaggerated. ``Anybody who doesn't like Atlanta can go somewhere
else,'' said the mayor.
   _Dissident Republicans in Michigan have taken the first step
toward challenging the credentials of Michigan's 77 delegates to
the GOP National Convention. After a dispute over party rules, the
dissidents had walked out of the state GOP convention and held
their own gathering. Now, they have sent the national party their
competing list of delegates to the convention.
</TEXT>
