<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RunawayTrain     06-23 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Runaway Train,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unmanned Engines Run Through Three Towns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORANGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three unmanned locomotives today sped
through three towns at speeds up to 40 mph before stopping on their
own, officials said.
   The runaway engines traveled about 10 miles between the towns of
Orange and Gardner in north central Massachusetts.
   There were no injuries reported as a result of the runaway
engines, said Colin Pease, spokesman for Guilford Transportation
Industries, which operates the trains.
   Pease said a crew working on engines near the Gardner rail yard
discovered the string of locomotives was gone at about 5 a.m. and
they notified a dispatcher, who alerted local authorities.
   He said he believes the trains were released by vandals, and he
said it was at least the second runaway since another string of
locomotives sped out of control through nine towns last November
until they were deliberately slammed into empty freight cars in
Deerfield.
   There were no injuries in that incident, and the FBI said it has
found no evidence of sabotage.
   Pease, however, said the two runaways and a third last January
form a pattern that cannot be coincidental.
   ``The circumstances are just too close,'' Pease said.
``Hopefully somebody will begin realizing this is a serious problem
and that we need help.''
   The latest incident came four days after striking rail workers
began returning to work, ending a six-month walkout over safety
issues.
   Union leader Mike Maloof said today that the workers could not
have been involved in the alleged vandalism because they were busy
taking physical exams.
</TEXT>
