<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 1305EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SeatBelts     06-23 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Seat Belts,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Private Study Concludes Back-Seat Lap Belts Are Risky</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rear-seat lap belts expose victims of car
crashes to greater risk of paralysis or death than lap-and-shoulder
restraints, according to a study released Thursday by
product-liability lawyers.
   The Institute for Injury Reduction, a Dunkirk, Md., organization
founded this year by attorneys involved in product-injury
litigation, presented the study at a hearing of the House
government activities and transportation subcommittee.
   ``In crash after crash, children and adults are dying, being
rendered paraplegic or quadriplegic or suffering disabling injuries
to their abdominal organs while wearing only rear-seat lap belts,''
A. Benjamin Kelley, president of the institute, testified.
   The tests commissioned by the institute were conducted by
Automotive Safety Testing Inc. of East Liberty, Ohio.
   The tests used instrumented dummies belted into the rear-seat
assembly of a 1987 Honda Accord LX and subjected to simulated
crashes.
   A 33 mph simulated crash using dummies the size of 6-year-old
children showed pressure against the outer part of the lap belt
when used alone was 61 percent greater than with a lap-shoulder
combination.
   In a simulated crash at 27 mph using adult-size dummies,
pressure on the outside part of the lap belt when used alone was
338 percent higher than with a lap-shoulder combination. A similar
test at 32 mph showed a 145 percent difference.
   The results indicate ``a greater likelihood for lap-belt only
occupants to sustain severe ... or fatal injuries in such
crashes,'' the study said.
   Peter Sursi, program manager at Automotive Safety Testing, said
in an interview the study did not address the question of the
position of the lap belt on the passenger.
   Auto manufacturers and the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration have said a properly adjusted lap belt will provide
protection because the force of the crash will be absorbed by the
large pelvic bones.
   A misadjusted belt will result in the belt's cutting through the
soft abdomen to the spinal column, studies have shown.
   NHTSA's policy is to encourage manufacturers voluntarily to
install lap-and-shoulder belt combinations in the rear seat while
asserting that a lap belt alone provides better crash protection
than no belt.
   A 1986 study by the National Transportation Safety Board,
however, concluded that lap belts used alone may cause serious
injury rather than providing protection.
   Thomas Hanna, president of the Motor Vehicle Manufacturers
Association, which represents the nation's automakers, told the
committee ``by 1990 virtually every car produced in the U.S. will
be equipped with lap-shoulder belts in outboard rear seating
positions.''
   Automakers offer kits for nearly all models made in the last 10
years that allow owners to install lap-should belt combinations in
the back seat of vehicles, Hanna said.
   The Institute for Injury Reduction, however, said knowledge and
availability of such kits is limited.
   The institute, on May 25-26, conducted a random telephone poll
of 30 dealers for five automakers in six cities and found none had
lap-should belt kits in stock, 21 said no kits were available and
only eight said kits could be ordered.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880623-0117 </DOCNO>
