<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Pope 3rdLd-Writethru   06-23 0711</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pope, 3rd Ld - Writethru,a0592,0727</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Arrives In Austria For Controversial Visit</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with pontiff's reference to Nazi
death camp, background on 50th anniversary of annexation with Nazi
Germany. Pickup 7th graf pvs, ``The Polish-born ...'' Minor editing
to trim</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II today urged Austrians
to remember its World War II past as he began a controversial trip
that includes meetings with President Kurt Waldheim and a visit to
a former Nazi death camp.
   Waldheim, under bitter attack from Jews and shunned by most
Western leaders for his alleged complicity in Nazi war crimes, led
the official government welcoming delegation for the Roman Catholic
leader.
   Waldheim, in his own greetings, denounced ``intolerance,
intransigence and hate among nations, religions and classes,'' but
made no direct comments about the dispute over his past as a German
army officer.
   The white-robed pontiff's special Alitalia DC-9 aircraft touched
down at Vienna' Schwechat Airport during a light shower.
   In comments delievered in German, John Paul mentioned his second
trip as pope to Austria will include the site of the former
Mauthausen death camp.
   He said such places recall ``times of hardship which have left
their indelible mark.
   ``Let us, when we meet, bring before God not only the great and
burdensome legacy of the past but also the joys and sorrows of the
present,'' the pontiff said.
   Many Austrians claim they were victims of Adolf Hitler's Nazi
rule, and the nation's events marking the 50th anniversary of the
1938 annexation with the Third Reich have sparked a renewed round
of soul-searching.
   The Polish-born pontiff drew the ire of Jews when he received
Waldheim a year ago at the Vatican, an audience the pope later
defended as ``necessary'' because Waldheim came as a democratically
elected president. The Vatican says the pope's meetings with world
leaders do not imply his support for an individual or political
system.
   ``This is not a political visit. It is a pastoral visit. He (the
pope) was invited by the bishops,'' said Vatican spokesman Joaquin
Navarro.
   Today, six American Jews demonstrated outside Waldheim's office
to show their displeasure with the pope's decision to meet with him.
   ``Do not embrace Waldheim, no!'' said Rabbi Avi Weiss of the
Hebrew Institute of Riverdale, N.Y. Standing with him were five
Jewish students dressed in black-and-white striped uniforms
reminiscent of those worn by concentration camp inmates during the
Nazi era.
   Earlier this week, two representatives of major Jewish
organizations met with a Vatican envoy in Jerusalem to register
their protests over the meetings.
   Dr. Avi Beker of the World Jewish Congress said the pope was
``going out of his way to legitimize Waldheim.''
   But Rabbi Marc H. Tanenbaum, director of international relations
of the American Jewish Committee, warned against ``extremist
hysteria and stridency'' over the meetings.
   In a statement from New York on Wednesday, he pointed out that
the pope was visiting a predominantly Catholic country and that it
was Vatican policy for popes to meet with heads of states of
countries with which the Holy See has diplomatic relations.
   Tanenbaum also said his group had been informed by Vatican
officials that the pope's contacts with Waldheim ``will be kept to
an absolute minimum.''
   Waldheim has denied that he committed war crimes, but the United
States has barred him, saying it found evidence he was involved in
deportations of Balkan civilians in World War II.
   An international commission of historians appointed by the
Austrian government to investigate the allegations concluded in
February that Waldheim was aware of Nazi atrocities in the Balkans
and did nothing to prevent them. It left open the question of
whether he was guilty of wartime atrocities.
   John Paul is to deliver about 20 speeches during the trip, his
second to a country where the Vatican counts 6.4 million Roman
Catholics, or 85 percent of the 7.5 million population. He paid a
three-day visit in 1983.
   On Friday, the 68-year-old pontiff is scheduled to meet with
representatives of Austria's 12,000 Jews, then visit the site of
the Mauthausen concentration camp where 110,000 prisoners died
during World War II. On pilgrimages to his homeland, the pope
visited the Auschwitz and Majdanek death camps.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
