<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 1305EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-LeaningTower     06-23 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Leaning Tower,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Landmark Leans A Little Bit More</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PISA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The famed leaning tower tilted another
fraction of an inch in the past year, a rate that might cause the
landmark to topple in about 100 years, an expert said Thursday.
   Gero Geri of the University of Pisa said that since June 1987
the tower has leaned 0.05 inches, according to measurments taken
Wednesday.
   Geri is a member of the team which makes semi-annual checks of
the displacement of several of Pisa's architectural treasures,
settling into the city's soft clay foundation.
   Although December's check-up showed encouraging signs that the
tower's tilt may be slowing, Geri said Wednesday's readings
indicated the monument had resumed its average tilting pace of
about 0.04 inches per year.
   The 180-foot tower, completed between 1360 and 1370, is now
leaning 14.6 feet off the vertical.
   ``We really do not know why it's still standing,'' Geri said.
``But judging from its current rate of shift and from the centuries
the process has taken, we estimate that the structure will fall in
a century if nothing is done to stop it.''
   He added: ``No one is really sure when it will go down.''
   The Ministry of Public Works has been trying for years to come
up with a plan to save the tower, but any project is far from
implementation.
</TEXT>
