<2ND_LINE>AM-Stalin,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Exhibits Changed At Stalin Museum, Georgian Official Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Rybakov, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Recent criticism of the crimes of Josef V. Stalin
have prompted unspecified changes at the museum honoring him in his
Georgian birthplace, the Communist Party leader of the southern
republic said Thursday.
   The Stalin museum in his native town of Gori _ which also has
the last town square statue of the dictator left standing in the
Soviet Union _ contained a large and uncritical display of
artifacts tracing Stalin's life and political career.
   Georgian party head Dzhumber Patiashvili was asked at a news
conference Thursday whether the museum showed the Georgian party
had a different attitude to Stalin than Mikhail S. Gorbachev, who
in November condemned the dictator's ``enormous and unforgiveable
crimes.''
   ``There can be no other interpretations,'' said Patiashvili.
   He added that although Stalin ``is not a Georgian problem at
all,'' but a Soviet one, the museum at Gori had been reviewed since
November and ``the exhibits there have been changed in the spirit
of Gorbachev's report.'' He did not detail the changes.
   There have been unconfirmed reports the museum would close prior
to being turned into a museum of Stalin's ``cult of personality,''
which is fiercely criticized in Soviet media.
   Almost all monuments extolling Stalin were dismantled after
Nikita S. Khrushchev condemned the former leader in 1956.
   In Georgia, however, some residents still proudly display
pictures of Stalin at home or in car windows. In the capital of
Tbilisi, a river embankment, park and mountain railway are named
for Stalin.
   Even after Khrushchev's condemnation, Stalin continued to be
extolled as a hero of the Soviet Union's World War II victory over
Germany.
   In Volgograd, formerly Stalingrad, quotes from Stalin are
engraved on World War II memorials.
   This week, however, articles coinciding with the anniversary of
the June 22, 1941, invasion by the Nazis have openly criticized
Stalin for failing to heed Red Army warnings of a coming German
invasion, suggesting he left the nation unprepared for attack.
</TEXT>
