<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Drought-Governors     06-23 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-Governors,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Midwest Governors Meet On Drought</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Expanding federal crop insurance and diverting
Lake Michigan to allow resumption of Mississippi River barge
traffic are among the steps needed to deal with the drought,
speakers today told Midwestern governors.
   ``We'll need a little bit of time to determine what the losses
are,'' said U.S. Agriculture Secretary Richard Lyng. ``But we will
do what is needed to minimize the severity of the damage.''
   The 10 governors at the meeting told Lyng about a number of
problems.
   Illinois Gov. James Thompson said his state's soybean and corn
crops would be lost without substantial rain in the next 30 days,
while Gov. George Sinner of North Dakota said 70 percent of his
state's grain crop already is lost.
   ``Welcome to the heart of the drought land,'' Thompson said in
opening the conference. ``We used to be known as the heart of the
heartland. Now we are both.''
   Thompson said barge traffic _ much of it bringing crops to
market _ is virtually closed on the vital commercial waterway of
the Mississippi, and he called for the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers
to petition the Supreme Court and allow diversion of Lake Michigan
water in order to get the traffic flowing again.
   Sinner said the one-day conference would address how to prevent
farmers struggling because of the drought from going broke and
leaving the land and devising a long-term solution to dropping
water tables throughout the northern tier and Western United States.
   Lyng said the federal government's response would include
expansion of existing crop insurance and disaster loan programs. He
also cited the creation of task forces in the Congress and within
President Reagan's administration preparing to respond to problems
of the drought.
   Lyng left the conference after his speech, but said he would
meet with Reagan on Friday morning to update him on the drought
situation.
   Attending the day-long meeting, besides Sinner and Thompson,
were the governors of Minnesota, Wisconsin, Montana, South Dakota,
Mississippi, Ohio, Kansas and Nebaska.
   Lyng announced a toll-free number for farmers affected by the
drought and seeking federal help. The number is 1-800-541-3375.
</TEXT>
