<2ND_LINE>AM-Mofford,0211</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mofford Says She's Feeling Better, Intends To Run in 1990</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Rose Mofford says she is recovering
from the concussion she suffered a month ago and still intends to
run for governor in 1990.
   ``I've made the bend and am starting to feel better again,''
Mrs. Mofford said during a two-hour appearance Wednesday at the
Tucson Rotary Club, her first public outing of more than three
minutes since her injury in a fall.
   At one point, she raised her arms and emphatically told the
luncheon audience, ``If I didn't quit when I became acting
governor, I'm not gonna quit now.''
   She took office upon the state Senate's conviction April 4 of
impeached Gov. Evan Mecham.
   She joked about her fall off a dais in Yuma, saying, ``Today is
exactly one month that the Phoenix Cardinals were trying to sign me
up.'' In the incident, Cardinals' Coach Gene Stallings accidentally
grabbed onto her as he fell backward, knocking her from her chair
and causing her to hit her head.
   The 66-year-old governor said her doctor has told her to limit
her activity, but she added, ``I'm doing pretty good and I'm making
a good comeback. That was quite a fall.''
