<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Jews     06-23 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Jews,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moscow Synagogue to Acquire Building It Lost During War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City officials agreed Thursday to return a
building now used as a medical institute to the synagogue that
owned it before World War II, two American and Soviet rabbis
announced.
   ``We asked for this five years ago, 15 and 20 years ago, but no
one would listen,'' the Soviet Union's chief rabbi, Adolf
Shayevich, said in an interview.
   The return of the two-story building to the Choral Synagogue on
Arkhipova Street in central Moscow fits a pattern of liberalization
that began during preparations for the celebration of the 1,000th
anniversary of Christianity in Russia.
   During the celebration earlier this month, the government
returned a monastery it had controlled in Kiev and several churches
throughout the country to the Russian Orthodox Church. The Soviet
government has taken over church property since the 1920s.
   After the structure was built more than 100 years ago, the
synagogue used it for Jewish community activities, but the
government took it away in 1941 and made it into a hospital for
World War II casualties, Shayevich said. It now houses a training
center for doctors. It is adjacent to the beige synagogue, and the
two doors connecting it to the synagogue are sealed.
   Arthur Schneier, a New York rabbi, said he began campaigning 1{
years ago for the return of the building but made progress with
Soviet officials just in the past two weeks, during the millennium
of Christianity.
   ``It's part of a process that seeks to align religious believers
with restructuring and rebuilding of society,'' Schneier said in an
interview in a synagogue office. ``They are trying to reach out to
the masses.''
   He said the return of the building ``would have been
unthinkable'' during his first visit in 1966 and ``improbable five
years ago.''
   Schneier said Moscow's deputy mayor, Gennady D. Arzhanov, agreed
on behalf of the Moscow City Council Thursday to turn over the
building to the synagogue. The oral agreement is to be followed up
with a formal contract later.
   Schneier said the Jewish congregation he represents at New
York's Park East Synagogue will help pay for restoration of the
building and will send architects and construction specialists to
offer advice. He predicted the building could be used within two
years for adult Jewish education classes and a museum.
   The New York synagogue also has agreed to help the medical
institute find other quarters, Schneier said.
</TEXT>
