<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 1325EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-HousePhones Bjt   06-23 0742</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-House Phones, Bjt,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Phone Problems Bedevil House of Representatives</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Donnald is correct in 13th graf, ``House Clerk''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House of Representatives telephone system
went dead Thursday for the fourth time in two weeks, silencing half
of Congress and leading one lawmaker to complain that Alexander
Graham Bell would be ``depressed and despondent.''
   The widespread outage brought howls from congressmen cut off
from their constituents and district offices, and prompted a
scramble by top officials of American Telephone & Telegraph Co.,
which installed the $16 million system, to find out what went wrong.
   ``I don't know what motivated this installation of the new
system, but it's certainly proven to be a failure,'' Rep. Walter
Jones, D-N.C., complained.
   Had Bell, the inventor of the telephone, been around during the
last two weeks, he ``would have been most depressed and despondent,
to say nothing of being embarrassed,'' Jones said.
   Rep. Jim Kolbe, R-Ariz., said the communications glitch reminded
him of the AT&T television commercials showing distraught employees
bemoaning their choice of a phone system and discussing how their
businesses had been ruined. The commercials end by proclaiming AT&T
``the right choice.''
   ``Well, in the interest of ... truth in advertising, I think we
ought to admit that the same source of that advertising is the one
that has the telephone system here in the House,'' Kolbe said in a
floor speech.
   When the system went down for the first time last week, he said,
``it was kind of nice to have the break. No calls coming in, quiet
in the offices. Everybody went off and got a Coke or did
something.''
   But as the outages kept recurring, he said, ``tempers
increased.''
   Members and staff described variously everything from totally
dead telephones to intermittent operation of some lines. Calls
could not be transferred. At times, all the lights on a telephone
would go on at once and all the phones in an office would ring
simultaneously.
   Officials in the House clerk's office, which administers the
phone system, said they were working feverishly to find out what
had gone wrong and that AT&T had sent its top technical experts
from all over the country to help diagnose the problem.
   ``It's a flukey sort of thing,'' said Deputy House Clerk Ray
Colley. The switching system which is the heart of the telephone
network is a computerized AT&T System 85, which is in wide use and
has not been a problem elsewhere, he said.
   Colley said he believed the House system, which has some 17,000
telephones, is one of the largest in the country.
   ``We're losing a lot of calls, obviously,'' he said. ``Believe
me, we have total attention from AT&T.'' Technicians suspected a
software problem but were examining everything, including the
possibility of computer hackers tampering with the system from
outside, he said.
   An AT&T spokesman, Herb Linnen, said the company had pulled
together its best technical minds and was working ``around the
clock'' to resolve the problem.
   ``We do not know the cause. We have tried to replicate the
calling situation of the House in our Bell Lab facilities in Denver
to see if we can spot a software or hardware problem, but we have
not been able to replicate it,'' he said.
   Linnen said the company was ``totally empathetic'' with
lawmakers' frustration. ``We are frustrated. We have a commitment
to get the ... problem fixed as quickly as possible,'' he said.
   The system was installed last August, and after some initial
startup problems worked fine until it went dead for the first time
last week, Colley said. Since then, outages of an hour or more
occurred on Tuesday, Wednesday and Thursday.
   House Clerk Donnald K. Anderson defended the system. ``We've got
the best system on the market,'' he said. ``I still have confidence
in System 85.''
   Meantime, Kolbe had a suggestion for members frustrated by being
unable to communicate with constituents: use the House floor and
its television system as an ``electronic billboard'' to send open
messages back home.
   ``And if nothing else works, my staff has come up with a
prototype system,'' he said, holding up a pair of styrofoam coffee
cups linked by a piece of wire.
   ``If I get the contract for $10 million or so to install this in
the House of Representatives, I promise that it will work just as
well as the phone system we have here now.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
