<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Angola     06-23 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Angola,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Welcomes `Flexible Approach' By Angola On Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States welcomed on Thursday what it
hoped was a ``flexible approach'' by Angola toward negotiations to
end a 13-year-old war between Cuban-backed government forces and
U.S.-supported guerrillas.
   State Department spokesman Charles E. Redman, noting reports
that the Angolan government is willing to enter peace discussions
without demanding cessation of U.S. support for the rebels, said
``we welcome a flexible approach to these very complex problems
we're addressing.''
   His comments were made on the eve of U.S., Cuban, South African
and Angolan talks in Cairo on a possible settlement of the conflict
that has enflamed southern Africa for more than a decade.
   One of the stumbling blocks in recent years has been Angola's
unwillingness to negotiate a withdrawal of Cuban forces in the
country as long as the United States backed the guerrilla forces of
the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola, or UNITA.
   UNITA receives more than $15 million a year in U.S. assistance.
   In Thursday editions, The New York Times quoted Angolan Justice
Minister Fernando Franca Van Dunem as saying U.S. support for UNITA
would not be an issue in the talks about to begin.
   ``It is not appropriate for us to raise the issue now,'' the
minister said. ``We will raise it with the United States
separately, at another juncture. The issue is not on the table for
the current negotiations. We should not mix these subjects.''
   Redman said that ``the U.S. position has always been that that
is not a subject for discussion and it has never been on the table
in these negotiations.''
   The American spokesman also said Secretary of State George P.
Shultz would meet next week with UNITA leader Jonas Savimbi.
   After Shultz met with the Angolan government delegation on
Wednesday, the department issued a statement declaring ``the United
States believes that the quickest way to end the conflict that has
already consumed the lives of thousands of Angolans, is for
Angolans themselves to meet and resolve their differences
peacefully and without the pressures and interference of outside
forces.''
</TEXT>
