<1ST_LINE>r i AM-JournalistsStrike     06-23 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Journalists Strike,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second Day of News Strike Keeps Papers Off Stands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nationwide journalists' strike, in its second day
on Thursday, kept nearly all of Italy's national newspapers off the
newstands and reduced state-run broadcasts to bare-bone accounts.
   The contract dispute also stilled news agencies, including the
two major national ones, ANSA and AGI.
   Among the missing papers were the leading sports dailies, but
for soccer fans, it was probably just as well. The strike meant no
post-mortems of Wednesday's night match between Italy and the
Soviet Union, which saw the Soviets kill the Italians' title hopes
for the European championship.
   The state broadcasting network RAI had carried the match live to
show the journalists' ``sensibility'' to the nation's soccer fever.
The broadcast, which involves the services of journalists, was the
only exception on Wednesday to the no-work day.
   On Thursday, however, RAI radio and television carried reduced
newscsts, without video or audio services. Instead, an announcer
designated by the journalists' union read the news in reduced form,
including a declaration of why the strike was called.
   The strike was scheduled to end Friday, allowing the publication
of Saturday's newspapers.
   Local papers and some that are outside the union, such as the
leftist Manifesto, did publish.
   Officials of the National Press Federation called the strike,
which began Wednesday morning, over a breakdown in negotiations.
   Publishers and union officials have agreed on a $381 monthly pay
increase in the new contract.
   But the unions are want a clause preventing newspaper chains
from using a central newsroom to provide national and international
news for the group, and publishers say that would be too costly.
</TEXT>
