<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon     06-23 0612</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0632</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rival Palestinian Factions Battle For Control of Camps</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival Palestinian guerrilla factions
battled with mortars and machine guns Thursday for control of two
refugee camps in Beirut. Police said two people were killed and
nine wounded.
   In a related development, the Abu Nidal group issued a threat to
assassinate Yasser Arafat's chief spokesman for issuing a statement
saying the Palestine Liberation Organization was ready to recognize
Israel.
   The camp fighting raised the overall toll to 53 people killed
and 215 wounded since the latest round of the war between Arafat's
mainline Fatah guerrillas and Col. Saeed Mousa's Fatah-Uprising
broke out 14 days ago.
   By police count, 102 people have been killed and 468 wounded in
the camps of Chatilla and Bourj el-Barajneh since the two factions
began their bloody feud May 1.
   A police spokesman said Mousa's guerrillas, dislodged from the
two shantytowns in previous rounds of fighting, shelled the camps
from Syrian-controlled territory in west Beirut early in the day.
   He said shells slammed into the two camps at the rate of one
every 10 minutes at certain times. The shantytowns have suffered
from repeated attacks from Israel and Syrian-backed Shiite Moslem
militias since 1982.
   The spokesman said sniper fire ``kept most roads in the two
camps closed throughout the day.'' He could not be dentified in
line with standing regulations.
   The fighting continued despite repeated efforts by neutral
guerrilla groups and Libyan mediators to arrange a cease-fire
between Fatah and Mousa's group.
   The cease-fire broke down in part because of a statement issued
by Arafat chief spokesman Bassam Abu Sharif saying the PLO was
willing to recognize Israel's existence.
   On Thursday, the Abu Nidal faction issued a veiled threat to
kill him.
   ``Abu Sharif is acting like the interred traitor Issam
Sartawi,'' said a statement from Abu Nidal's Fatah-Revolutionary
Council published by Beirut's leftist as-Safir daily.
   Sartawi, a roving ambassador for Arafat, was assassinated in
Madrid in 1983. The PLO blamed Abu Nidal's group, which opposes any
negotiations with Israel.
   Sartawi was among the most moderate PLO leaders. He had met with
Israeli moderates before he was killed.
   Abu Sharif ``expresses the willingness of the group represented
by Arafat ... to negotiate with the Zionist entity,'' the statement
said.
   Abu Sharif said in a statement released in Tunis, Tunisia,
earlier this month that the PLO was willing to recognize Israel and
accept a Palestinian homeland in the occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip as a solution to the 40-year-old Arab-Israeli conflict.
   Abu Sharif's unusually conciliatory proposals drew strong
condemnation from five Syrian-backed guerrilla groups.
   Abu Nidal, whose real name is Sabri al-Banna, broke with Arafat
in 1974. He is wanted in the United States and Western Europe for a
chain of terrorist attacks, including the December 1985 Vienna and
Rome airport attacks in which 16 people were killed.
   In Kuwait, the Al-Qabas daily reported Thursday that the U.S.
administration will deal with the PLO if it publicly endorses Abu
Sharif's statement.
   The newspaper quoted ``reliably informed Western diplomatic
sources'' as saying in a report from Paris that this had been
conveyed to Arafat through an unidentified third party.
   State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said this week that
the statement by Abu Sharif was a positive step, but stressed it
lacked the authoritative support of the PLO leadership.
   Al-Qabas quoted diplomatic sources as saying the Americans
considered Abu Sharif's statement as ``the first PLO statement
which talks in detail about the Palestinians' desire to live in
peace with the Israelis and the existence of an agreement between
the Palestinians and the Israelis to live in peace and security.''
</TEXT>
