<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 1413EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Democrats-Credentials     06-23 0836</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Democrats-Credentials,810</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Harmony on Credentials: Rules Fights To Come</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats for the first time are headed to
their national convention with no fights pending over delegates
after the Credentials Committee on Thursday ratified the names on
the roll to be called in Atlanta.
   Harmony and winning in November were the sounds from the
campaigns of nominee-to-be Michael Dukakis and remaining rival
Jesse Jackson.
   ``Reverend Jackson wishes to insure, by starting in unity with
this committee today, that the tone will be set for a united
convention leading to a united Democratic victory in November,''
said Toney Anaya, the former New Mexico governor speaking for
Jackson.
   ``Jesse Jackson has made us all proud. Michael Dukakis is
looking forward to a very unified and winning convention in
Atlanta,'' replied Joe Warren of Massachusetts, speaking for his
governor. ``He is especially thankful to the Jackson campaign for
the determination to make 1988 the year of the Democrats.''
   The campaigns had cut deals in recent days to resolve each of
the remaining battles about delegates who will meet in Atlanta July
18-21. Jackson complaints about delegates in Pennsylvania and
Puerto Rico _ which were not filed as challenges _ are being worked
out privately.
   But Anaya warned that fights were to come this weekend when the
convention Rules Committee meets to talk about 1992 and beyond.
   ``There is still some disagreement with party rules, state and
national,'' he said. ``Reverend Jackson has determined the proper
place to take those disagreements is the Rules Committee and seek
changes prospectively.''
   Ann Lewis, a top Jackson adviser, said the candidate wants
changes that will bring the delegate totals in 1992 closer to the
primary vote. He wants those changes written into the rules by the
1988 convention.
   The credentials meeting in Washington _ the only one scheduled _
was a quiet affair as the group slowly ratified every deal that was
cut to settle the total of 21 delegate challenges. The group also
put its stamp of approval on the delegates from all the states
which had not been questioned.
   And a lack of credentials fights in Atlanta suits Democratic
National Committee Chairman Paul Kirk just fine.
   ``We never get a second chance in life to make a first
impression,'' Kirk said. ``When we think about what we are doing
today, I think it is the first time in recent political history _
as far back as the secretary's office can advise us _ we've never
started out the general election process at the Democratic
convention free of credentials challenges.
   ``I think it's a credit to the presidential campaigns ... to
settle these differences without rancor, in a sense of unity so we
can begin this process with an eye on November.''
   ``The chair will be absolutely delighted if on the evening news,
nothing appears on television about us,'' added committee chairman
K. Leroy Irvis of Pennsylvania.
   Irvis gaveled the resolutions through methodically, joking at
one point as he called for a vote: ``Those who approve say aye.
Those who disapprove nay _ we won't hear them anyway.''
   The last four battles to be resolved were Jackson delegate
squabble in Indiana, Kansas and Virginia and a spat between the
national party and Maine.
   In the first two states, a few extra delegates were added _
without increasing the number of votes _ to settle fights.
   In Indiana, two delegates were added with full votes to enable
both current Gary Mayor Thomas Barnes and former Gary Mayor Richard
G. Hatcher _ and one supporter each _ to go to Atlanta. Barnes
defeated Hatcher in the Democratic mayoral primary last year.
   Originally, Barnes and his supporter, Rudy Clay, were elected
delegates, but Hatcher challenged that in court, arguing that he
and his supporter, Carlos Tolliver, should be seated. Now all four
will go and the votes of four other Indiana delegates backing
Jackson will be cut in half to make room.
   This settlement, worked out Thursday morning, was slightly
different from what officials said the deal was on Wednesday.
   In Kansas, Jackson picks up six more delegates with a half vote
each. Five delegates for Sen. Albert Gore Jr. and one for Dukakis _
challenged by Jackson _ will go to the convention, but with half
votes.
   Thus, Jackson will gain three votes in Kansas, while Gore will
lose 2.5 votes and Dukakis half a vote.
   In Virginia, four Jackson supporters who were tossed off the
delegate list by other Jackson backers dropped their challenge,
credentials officials said.
   In Maine, the state party ignored a national rule setting a
threshold of 15 percent support before a candidate or group could
win delegates to the national convention. The state convention last
month gave three delegates to an uncommitted slate, even though it
had only 13 percent support at the meeting.
   To settle the argument, the three uncommitted delegates have
been accepted as Dukakis delegates by the campaign, even if they
don't vote for the Massachusetts governor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
