<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Vietnam     06-23 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vietnam,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Premier Says Hanoi Wants to Leave Cambodia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam's new premier said Thursday
that Hanoi wants to end its 9-year-old military occupation of
Cambodia so it can improve relations with other countries.
   ``The renovation in relations between Vietnam and foreign
countries is very important,'' the official Voice of Vietnam radio
quoted Do Muoi as saying.
   According to the broadcast, Do Muoi ``said that to widen
cooperation, first of all, it is necessary to maintain peace and
security. Vietnam is striving to solve the Kampuchean (Cambodian)
issue.''
   He said if possible, Vietnam will withdraw all its estimated
120,000 soldiers before 1990, its self-imposed deadline for a total
pullout. Other Vietnamese officials previously have said an early
withdrawal is possible if a political settlement is reached.
   Vietnam is to begin this month what it says is a pullout of
50,000 troops, the largest annual pullout.
   Do Muoi, a 71-year-old veteran organizer in the ruling Communist
Party and its third-ranking official, was named Wednesday by the
National Assembly to replace Pham Hung, who died in March.
   Many non-communist Western and Asian countries have embargoed
economic aid to Vietnam since it invaded Cambodia in late 1978.
   Hanoi-based diplomats say that in the past two years, Vietnam's
new pragmatic leadership _ which gives priority to economic
development _ has made a series of diplomatic initiatives on
Cambodia. Before that, Vietnamese diplomats said the situation was
``irreversible.''
   Foreign Minister Nguyen Co Thach announced in Bangkok earlier
this week that he will attend unprecedented peace talks involving
Cambodian guerrilla factions next month in Indonesia.
   Do Muoi said Vietnam has established good ties with India and
Indonesia, and there were prospects for such ties with the pro-West
Association of Southeast Asian Nations. ASEAN groups Thailand,
Indonesia, Malaysia, Brunei, Singapore and the Philippines.
   The premier said Vietnam is ``seeking all means'' to hold peace
talks with China. Relations between the two countries have been
tense since they fought a bloody border war in early 1979.
   On Wednesday, Do Muoi pledged to continue Western-style economic
reforms. A Radio Hanoi report seen here Thursday said he told the
National Assembly he will ``thoroughly grasp the renovative
spirit'' of reform resolutions adopted at a December 1986 party
congress.
   The party has blamed years of orthodox Marxist policies for an
economy that is one of the world's poorest. The reforms involve
decentralization of management, material incentives and limited
free enterprise.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
