<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Fight,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Car Deal Turns Sour, Dozens Detained in Restaurant Fight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two gangs that disagreed about payment in a car
deal drove into downtown Moscow and battled it out with wooden
clubs and metal rods in a popular restaurant, newspapers reported
Thursday.
   Police investigator N. Chekmazov told the Moscow city newspaper
Lenin's Banner that 36 people, including witnesses and victims,
were detained after the clash at the Uzbekistan Restaurant on
Wednesday night.
   He said two gangs disagreed about terms of a car
buying-and-selling deal they made Monday in Southern Port, a site
on the Moscow River notorious for illegal trading in cars. The
gangs spent two days ``mobilizing their forces'' before coming to
blows at the restaurant, Chekmazov said.
   The newspaper said in a separate dispatch by the Tass news
agency that the gangs arrived at the restaurant in their own cars.
   Neither Chekmazov nor Tass gave details of the car deal that
turned sour.
   Those arrested, who were mostly from Moscow's outskirts, ranged
in age from 22 to 30 and included six people with criminal records.
Lenin's Banner published a Tass dispatch saying the gangs were
armed with wooden clubs and metal rods. It did not give a figure
for the number of injured.
   Soviet newspapers have covered crime more extensively since
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev launched his ``glasnost'' policy
of openness on selected social, historical and other issues three
years ago.
