<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NavyDeath     06-23 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Navy Death,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Admiral Gets Confidential Recommendations in Mirecki Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investigative officer has made
confidential recommendations on whether an officer and five
instructors should be court-martialed for the death of a recruit at
the Navy Rescue Swimmer School, a spokesman confirmed Thursday.
   Cmdr. Daniel J. D'Alesio, a Navy legal services officer
stationed in Philadelphia, made the recommendations, based on
hearings earlier this month, to Rear Adm. David R. Morris, chief of
naval air training, said Morris spokesman Lt. Lee Saunders.
   Morris is expected to make a decision before he leaves his
present job July 1 to take command of an aircraft carrier battle
group in the Atlantic Ocean. But depending on what he decides, the
disclosure of his action may be delayed until after that date,
Saunders said.
   Morris may decide to call for a court-martial, non-judicial
punishment or dismissal of the charges.
   The five instructors were charged with involuntary manslughter
and conspiracy to commit battery by forcing Airman Recruit Lee
Mirecki, 19, of Appleton, Wis., into a swimming pool at the
Pensacola Naval Air Station and holding his head under water until
he collapsed. The alleged actions occurred when the sailor panicked
on March 2 and said he was quitting the rescue course.
   Lt. Thomas A. Torchia, officer in charge of the school, is
charged with the lesser offense of dereliction of duty. He has been
relieved of his command.
   During the hearings, a pathologist testified Mirecki died of
``sheer terror.'' The recruit's phobia of being dragged under water
triggered heart failure that was followed by drowning, the
pathologist said.
   Mirecki panicked during an exercise known as ``sharks and
daisies'' in which instructors grabbed students in head-holds to
simulate a panicking air crash survivor. The exercise now has
students practice rescue exercises on each other rather than
instructors.
   The school was closed March 29 and reopened Monday with
instructors barred from touching trainees. Students also are
required to immediately be pulled from training if they say they
want to quit or show fear, panic or excessive fatigue.
</TEXT>
