<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel Bjt   06-23 0731</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, Bjt,0752</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Israeli Children Hurt in Bus Stoning</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Israeli children on their way back from a
school hike were hurt by flying glass when their bus was stoned in
an Arab neighborhood of east Jerusalem, a police spokesman said
Thursday.
   In a further sign of resurgent unrest that has struck Jerusalem
recently, outlawed Palestine Liberation Organization flags were
flown from utility poles in several parts of the city.
   West Bank commander Maj. Gen. Amram Mitzna decided to free 89
Palestinian detainees and prisoners. An army official said the
decision followed appeals from Arab notables and was made ``to
contribute to the restoration of normal life.''
   The army said it would pardon 17 prisoners, stop proceedings
against 27 detainees, and cut short six-month prison terms of 45
administrative detainees. The Palestinians would be released
Friday, it said.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, speaking at a ceremony at the
National Police Headquarters, urged the police to suppress all
manifestations of unrest in Jerusalem.
   ``These threats must become a challenge to the Israeli police,
who should make a special effort to repel every attack and cut off
every hand that would be raised against the unity of Jerusalem, our
eternal capital,'' he said.
   Police spokesman Rafi Levy said the incidents appeared linked to
orders issued by underground Palestinian leaders in a leaflet
distributed Wednesday.
   The leaflet calls on Arabs to focus their disturbances on
Jerusalem to protest Israeli control of the disputed city. Israel
annexed the Arab sector of the city after driving out Jordanian
troops in 1967, but most countries have refused to recognize
Jerusalem as Israel's capital.
   Palestinian girls from a high school in the Shuafat quarter of
Jerusalem stoned two Israeli buses heading toward Neve Yaacov, an
isolated Jewish neighborhood surrounded by Palestinian communities,
Levy told The Associated Press.
   The 11-year-old Israeli children were returning from a visit to
Ammunition Hill, the site of a key battle in the 1967 Middle East
war.
   Three students were hurt and treated at Jerusalem's Hadassah
Hospital, Levy said, adding that the injuries were believed to be
minor.
   Police detained several Palestinians, including Arab students,
he said.
   In a separate incident, a Palestinian stoned an Israeli bus on
Saleh el-Din Street, the main shopping thoroughfare in the Arab
part of the city, Levy said. The stone smashed a window but caused
no injuries, he said.
   The latest unrest, following a four-month lull in violence in
Jerusalem, began Saturday when Palestinian protesters blocked city
streets with stones and attacked a police van and a lookout post
atop the Old City's Damascus Gate.
   Also Thursday, the Israeli army accused the London-based human
rights group, Amnesty International, of using biased sources of
information and denied an Amnesty report that soldiers had killed
Arabs by using tear gas improperly in its fight against the Arab
uprising.
   The report accused Israeli soldiers of firing tear gas into
confined areas in violation of manufacturers' order, thus killing
at least seven Palestinians.
   But a military communique said soldiers had instructions not to
fire into rooms and said the tear gas used by Israel ``is not
dangerous to human life.''
   An electric power failure paralyzed most of the country and the
occupied territories, stopping factory production, causing traffic
snarls and disrupting telephone and other communications. The
electric corporation spokesman ruled out sabotage as a cause of the
outage.
   The power failure caused blackouts of up to three hours in most
parts of Israel, including Jerusalem and Tel Aviv. It reached as
far south as the resort town of Eilat on the Egyptian border.
   Police spokesman Levy initially said police were investigating
whether the outage was the work of Palestinian saboteurs. However,
Avri Ravid, spokesman for the Israel Electric Corp., later told the
AP the failure was caused by a torn high tension wire.
   ``No person could have cut it,'' Ravid said. ``If anyone tried,
there would be nothing left of him.''
   Israeli officials and Palestinian landowners said mischievous
Israeli children and Jewish settlers seeking retaliation set some
of the blazes that have scorched thousands of acres of land since
May.
   Most of the 35,000 acres of greenery torched since this spring
were destroyed by Arab arsonists. Underground Arab leaders called
an ``Arson Day'' on Wednesday, and nine of the 14 fires which broke
out apparently were set by Palestinians, police said.
</TEXT>
