<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bullfighter     06-23 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bullfighter,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Bullfighter `El Cordobes' Loses Paternity Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court Thursday ruled against legendary
bullfighter Manuel Benitez, agreeing with an American woman who
alleged he fathered her 19-year-old son, the matador's lawyer said.
   Attorney Antonio de la Riva said three members of the five-judge
Supreme Court voted to overturn two lower court decisions against
Elizabeth Velasco.
   She said her son, also named Manuel Benitez, was conceived while
she lived with the millionaire bullfighter, known as ``El
Cordobes,'' from 1968 to 1972.
   Two judges voted against Ms. Velasco, a 38-year-old Santa
Monica, Calif., resident who first brought suit in 1982 against
Benitez, Spain's most popular matador during the 1960s and early
1970s.
   In the decision, the majority said the 52-year-old matador's
refusal to take a blood test was ``obstructionist behavior'' and a
clear sign of his fear the test would prove Ms. Velasco's claim.
   El Cordobes had argued the test represented an affront to his
honor.
   The Supreme Court ordered El Cordobes to pay the costs of Ms.
Velasco's original 1982 suit. It also ordered both of them to share
the costs of the latest appeal.
   Ms. Velasco's lawyer, Carlos Vinader, said he was ``greatly
satisfied'' by the ruling. He said the court had not officially
informed him of its decision.
   ``It's a good thing she has a strong heart,'' he said of
Velasco. ``She has suffered many injustices.''
   De la Riva said El Cordobes planned to appeal the decision to
the Constitutional Tribunal, Spain's highest court.
   In 1982, represented by attorney Marvin Mitchelson, Ms. Velasco
sought an award of $2 million and an obligation for child support
from a Cordoba court.
   She lost that suit and an appeal to a court in Seville, capital
of the Andalusian autonomous region.
   Ms. Velasco later dropped her demand for a cash settlement.
   El Cordobes and his wife of 13 years, Marina Freysee, have five
children.
   The flamboyant bullfighter, who retired in 1981 but gave benefit
performances in 1982 and 1986, emerged from humble origins to
become immensely popular and wealthy during his career which lasted
from 1958 to 1981.
   He is a businessman with a personal fortune estimated at $20
million.
</TEXT>
