<DOCNO> AP880623-0144 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 1456EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Drought-Steamboats     06-23 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Steamboats,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drought May Eliminate Some Stops On Annual Steamboat `Race'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Drought-Heat Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN McGILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two paddle-wheelers take off Friday for the
annual re-creation of a historic steamboat race, but the drought
that's drying up the Mississippi River could prompt officials to
eliminate some ports of call.
   The 10-day trip still will begin on schedule, said Capt.
Lawrence Keeton of the Mississippi Queen.
   Keeton said Thursday that river traffic was being shut down at
Memphis, Tenn., to allow for dredging of the shallow river channel.
But by the time the Mississippi Queen and its rival Delta Queen
reach that point, the river may be open, he said.
   ``Hopefully, we'll be thre just at the right place at the right
time,'' Keeton said.
   The company that operates both steamships said planned stops at
Greenville, Miss., Memphis, Carthersville, Mo., and Cairo, Ill.,
may have to be changed.
   Both ships are scheduled to steam into the port at St. Louis,
under the Gateway Arch, at 9 a.m. on the Fourth of July. Among
precautions being taken by the steamship company to assure safe
navigation of the shallower river will be the use of a towboat
pushing a barge with a 9-foot draft. The tow and barge will travel
ahead of the steamships, acting as a pathfinder.
   The ``race'' pits the Mississippi Queen against the Delta Queen
in what is billed as a re-enactment of the June 24, 1870, race
between the Natchez and the Robert E. Lee. However, instead of
trying to match the speed of that race _ which was won by the Lee
in three days, 18 hours and 14 minutes _ the two modern-day
steamboats will set a leisurely 10-day pace.
   The boats traditionally stop at Natchez, Vicksburg, Memphis and
other ports where passengers and crew from each vessel take part in
contests such as ``dueling calliopes,'' the ``Floozie Parade
Competition'' and a kite flying contest. Points gained during all
the events determine the winner of the ``race.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
