<DOCNO> AP880623-0145 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 1503EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Trade     06-23 0661</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Big Trade Bill Lands In Senate Hopper Again</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Plant Closing Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senators dumped an overhauled version of their
vetoed, 1,000-page bill in the hopper Thursday and expressed
optimism that the measure will reach President Reagan's desk this
year.
   ``This represents a consensus on trade policy _ it's a consensus
that has been a long time in coming,'' Sen. John C. Danforth,
R-Mo., told reporters.
   Finance Committee Chairman Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, said he saw
``an excellent chance of getting trade legislation and I'm
optimistic.''
   Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., said, however,
that there would not be time to take up the legislation at least
until late July. He said he wants to get all of the fiscal 1989
money bills through the Senate first.
   That timetable threatened to put the slimmed-down trade bill in
a time squeeze, with some lawmakers opposed to any such legislation
while others may be eager to wrap up congressional business and hit
the campaign trail.
   A similar bill quietly went into the House hopper last week and
there were signs that it might see faster action.
   The measure is shorn of a provision that would require companies
to provide 60-day notice of plant closings and major layoffs.
   As the lawmakers fielded questions at a news conference, the
Senate debated a separate plant-closings bill with provisions
identical to those removed from the trade bill.
   A similar plant-closings measure was pending in the House, and
lawmakers in both houses planned to vote on the measure before the
July Fourth break. Democratic leaders have been saying for three
weeks that prospects appear good for passage of separate
plant-closings legislation.
   Labor unions had lobbied against detaching the plant-closings
provision from the trade bill in April and refused to give in when
Democratic leaders asked them to go along with dropping it. The
leaders then pushed the bill with the provision intact despite
predictions that it meant a sure veto.
   This time union leaders again lobbied against detaching the
plant-closings provision. But Democratic leaders insisted on doing
so, a move that insulates them from election-year charges of
refusing to compromise on trade.
   Also dropped from the modified version of the trade bill were
provisions to restrict Alaska petroleum exports.
   They would limit exports from new oil refineries in Alaska to
70,000 barrels a day and 50 percent of output. Up to 50,000 barrels
a day could be exported to Canada but only after making a detour in
an American-flagged vessel to a port in the lower 48 states.
   President Reagan objected to both the plant-closings and Alaska
oil provisions in his veto of the earlier version of the
legislation.
   Central features of the measure would overhaul the system under
which the United States imposes import curbs to aid threatened U.S.
industries and retaliate against international trade violations.
   Other features range from repeal of the 1980 windfall profits
tax on oil industry earnings to substantial agricultural subsidy
programs.
   One feature targeted in Reagan's veto message but left intact
when seantors overhauled their measure would allow duty-free
imports of Caribbean ethanol, used for making gasohol. Corn
producers have been fighting to get it erased.
   ``All you have to do is look at the drought,'' Bentsen said.
``... They're not going to have the corn for ethanol.''
   Danforth appealed for support from farm groups.
   ``This bill is very good farm legislation,'' he said. ``As a
matter of fact I think it is the most significant agricultural
legislation that I've ever seen in the Senate.''
   It would provide $1.5 billion in payments to grain companies to
spur exports as well as millions of dollars to agribusinesses to
advertise their wares in global markets.
   Under the measure, wheat, feed grains and oilseed crop producers
would receive stepped-up subsidies aimed at stimulating global
sales if negotiators fail to make progress on farm issues in the
current Uruguay Round of world trade talks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
