<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 1459EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Homosexuals 1stLd-Writethru a0669 06-23 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Homosexuals, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0669,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Approves Homosexuals' Association</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to CORRECT that association not the first
in East bloc.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has approved in principle
the registration of an association for homosexuals, a member of
parliament said Thursday.
   Mikolaj Kozakiewicz, a prominent sexologist and member of
parliament from the United peasant Party, said in an interview that
he was told by the Ministry of Health that homosexual associations
may be formed for different cities in Poland.
   It would be the second association for homosexuals in the East
Bloc. Hungary approved a similar association several months ago
after much public debate.
   The Polish associations will have the right to their own
publications and will be ``linked in some way to the public health
service,'' he said.
   According to Kozakiewicz, there are about 30 male homosexuals in
Warsaw who are willing to join the association, and a much larger
group which would support it.
   Kozakiewicz said he was approached last year by a small group of
homosexuals and was asked for help in winning permission for an
association. He said he met personally with Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak,
minister of the interior, to discuss the matter.
   He received word that it was approved Wednesday from Deputy
Health Minister Jerzy Bonczak, he said.
   Homosexuality is legal in Poland and persecution of homosexuals
is unheard of. But it is much less open than in Western countries
and homosexuals have complained of intolerance and bigotry.
   For the first time in Poland last year, four representatives of
the nascent gay movement appeared on television, on a late-night
talk show ``Intimate Talks.'' They spoke frankly about their
problems, but appeared only with their backs to the camera.
   The unwillingness of homosexuals to identify themselves has been
considered one obstacle to the government's efforts to combat the
AIDS virus in Poland. Homosexuals have been asked to volunteer for
blood tests under an ambitious government program to counter the
disease, which has claimed at least three lives in Poland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880623-0147 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 1450EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-FCC-Indecency Bjt   06-23 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FCC-Indecency, Bjt,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Missouri TV Station First To Be Fined Under New `Indecency' Rules</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission voted
Thursday to impose the first fine under its decency standards on a
Missouri television station for broadcasting a ``pandering and
titillating'' sex comedy during prime time.
   The FCC voted 2-1 to levy the maximum $2,000 fine on KZKC-TV, a
UHF station in Kansas City, for showing the movie ``Private
Lessons'' at 8 p.m., a time at which the agency said children were
likely to be watching.
   The movie, broadcast May 26, 1987, is about a 15-year-old boy
who is seduced by his housekeeper and included scenes in which the
woman appeared bare-breasted. The FCC said the scenes ``were
neither isolated nor fleeting.''
   The commission said that while nudity and sexual themes are not
necessarily ``indecent,'' their context and treatment in ``Private
Lessons'' were.
   ``The movie included nudity and scenes depicting sexual matters
which were dealt with in a pandering and titillating manner,'' the
commission said.
   ``The story line of the seduction of a 15-year-old boy by an
older woman, together with the inclusion of explicit nudity, would
have commanded the attention of children and the sexual references
would have been readily understood by children who tuned into the
program,'' the FCC said.
   Attorney Tom Davidson, representing Media Central Inc. of
Chattanooga, Tenn., owner of KZKC-TV, said he was ``shocked and
surprised and outraged by the imposition of the maximum fine in
light of the circumstances.''
   Davidson said the punishment was unfair because the standards
are vague and this is the first time they have been applied to
television.
   ``We don't know what is indecent because the standard doesn't
provide any guidance,'' he said.
   The guidelines are being challenged in court by broadcasting
groups, news organizations and public interest advocates as being
unconstitutionally vague and overbroad.
   Media Central has not decided what action to take, Davidson
said. Station officials have said the movie was edited for
television by an inexperienced editor and violated its own
standards for good taste but that they took immediate corrective
action, including clarification of the station's policy on nudity.
   All three commissioners agreed that the movie was indecent and
that children are likely to be in the audience before midnight, but
Commissioner Patricia Diaz Dennis said the commission has no
evidence there is a substantial number of unsupervised children in
the audience at that time.
   ``Parents, not the commission, should bear the primary
responsibility of deciding what their children should watch at
night,'' she said.
   FCC Chairman Dennis R. Patrick said surveys have shown that 42
percent of all children are watching TV at 8 p.m. and that ``it is
reasonable to assume that there are unsupervised children in the
audience.''
   Commissioner James H. Quello said the FCC's action was
significant because ``this serves notice that we are going to
enforce indecency standards'' in regard to television as well as
radio stations. It marked the first indecency finding against a TV
station and was the first time the agency imposed a fine under its
tough new standards.
   The FCC decided in April 1987 to toughen its existing decency
standards by applying the wording of a 1978 Supreme Court decision
that said indecent material is ``language or material that depicts
or describes, in terms patently offensive as measured by
contemporary community standards for the broadcast medium, sexual
or excretory activities or organs.''
   The commission said indecent material may be aired only when
there is a reasonable risk that children are not in the audience.
In a subsequent ruling in November 1987, the FCC said it would
consider that children were not likely to be in the audience after
midnight. Previously the FCC had considered 10 p.m. the cutoff time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
