<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 1504EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Alimenti     06-23 0120</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Alimenti,0124</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Noted Italian TV Journalist Dies After On-Air Stroke</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dante Alimenti, a journalist who covered the papacy
for Italy's state-run television for 10 years, died Thursday after
suffering a stroke a week ago during an on-air interview at the
Vatican. He was 54.
   Alimenti reported on most of Pope John Paul II's trips abroad
and in Italy, and had been scheduled to travel with the pontiff to
Vienna on Thursday.
   Last week, he suffered a stroke while interviewing Vatican
spokesman Joaquin Navarro, collapsing while millions of Italians
heard his voice trail off on the main evening news program.
   Alimenti joined the RAI network in 1962.
   He is survived by his wife, Giuseppina, and a daughter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880623-0149 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 1506EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson     06-23 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Won't Divulge Private Decision on Veep Question</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: May be topped</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson said Thursday he has decided in
his own mind whether he wants to be Michael Dukakis' running mate,
but said he has not shared that decision with the likely Democratic
presidential nominee.
   After reiterating his stance that he has earned serious
consideration for the post, Jackson was asked if he has privately
decided whether he wants the job.
   ``Privately, yes,'' he replied. But as to informing Dukakis on
his point of view, he said teasingly, ``No, that would be public.''
   He made the comments to reporters after a pre-convention meeting
with his state campaign chairmen from around the country who are in
Washington for briefings on convention strategy and planning.
   Jackson then departed for Puerto Rico, where he plans a series
of appearances over the next three days.
   Puerto Rico has been an object of Jackson complaints about
unfair distribution of delegates during the primary season. Jackson
won Puerto Rico's non-binding ``beauty contest'' primary, but all
57 delegates were awarded to Dukakis.
   Jackson said Thursday that ``no doubt there will be some
adjustments made in Puerto Rico'' in delegate distribution as there
has been in New Jersey, Illinois, and Pennsylvania, other states
where he objected to the way delegates were allocated.
   The island's governor, Rafael Hernandez Colon, said Thursday he
was considering Jackson's request for some of the delegates.
   Hernandez Colon said ``we are willing to examine a petition of
that nature within the context of the need for unity in the
Democratic Party, and always, in coordination with Dukakis'
campaign.''
   Hernandez Colon also said Jackson ``should be seriously
considered for the position (of vice president) since he won second
place in the primaries all over the United States.''
   Puerto Rico's 3.2 million people are U.S. citizens but do not
vote in general elections.
   Jackson was asked here whether he thinks Dukakis is giving him
fair and serious consideration for the vice presidential spot. He
said the process is ongoing.
   ``So far we are a part of the process. The process is one thing.
The conclusion ... is another,'' he said.
   He said, however, that so far, ``I feel positive about it. I
feel hopeful about it.''
   Regarding the non-publicized criteria that Dukakis is using to
pick a running mate, he said, ``Some judgment must be made on some
criteria which has not yet been established.''
   Jackson listed his own baseline criteria for a running mate _
ability to inspire youth, experience in the Third World and ability
to erase traditional discrimination based on race or sex.
   Although the focus for weeks has been on Jackson's vice
presidential aspirations, he is refusing to follow the other
runnerup candidates in endorsing Dukakis before the convention.
   ``That's somebody trying to get me to play some rules that are
not in the interest of my constituency,'' he said. ``My
constituency has a reason to continue our campaign to Atlanta'' and
take an active role in the platform, rules and credentials
committees.
   He said he would endorse the ticket ``at the appropriate time,''
if he loses the nomination, and said that ``those who have thrown
in the towel early, they are people who have fainted in the face of
adversity.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880623-0150 </DOCNO>
