<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 1531EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Kenya-Hospital     06-23 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kenya-Hospital,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Debtors Threaten Premier Kenyan Hospital With Closure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kenya's premier hospital may close because
it is owed about $1.8 million, a third of it by state-controlled
companies, its director said Thursday.
   ``We have no source of income other than fees paid by patients.
I don't see how we can continue unless debtors pay up,'' Briton
Watkins Pitchford said of the private 194-bed Nairobi Hospital.
   This week, he placed an advertisement in a newspaper appealing
to debtors to ``search your conscience and settle your bills.''
   ``If you don't do so now, it is very possible there may be no
Nairobi Hospital to turn to next time you and yours succumb to
illness,'' the ad said.
   Pitchford said the debt, owed by individuals, private and
state-owned companies, international organizations and diplomatic
missions, has accumulated since 1986. He refused to further
identify the debtors.
   Spokeswoman Carole Argwings-Kodhek said it was not feasible to
take legal action because the hospital has so many debtors.
   The 38-year-old establishment belongs to the 1,000-member Kenya
Hospital Association, a non-profit company with no share capital.
It employs 700 people, including 14 doctors and 300 nurses, and
operates one of this East African nation's two best equipped
intensive care units.
   Kenyans who have a choice shun the country's mismanaged state
hospitals, where patients often share beds or floor space and there
are drug shortages.
   Ill tourists, expatriate workers or diplomats traditionally go
to Nairobi Hospital.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880623-0152 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 1539EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MarylandMotto     06-23 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Maryland Motto,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Couple Works To Change Maryland State Motto</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLLEGE PARK, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Linda and Tom Wolfe discovered
Maryland's motto when their son wrote a history report, and began
another campaign to persuade the General Assembly to change a motto
they consider sexist.
   The motto in Italian, ``Fatti maschii parole femine,'' means
``Manly deeds and womanly words,'' according to the state's
accepted translation.
   ``There it was right on the seal. ... It is pretty disgusting,''
Mrs. Wolfe said recently. She and her husband have formed MOMMA, or
Modernization of Maryland's Motto Association.
   Since mid-May about 400 people have signed the Wolfes' petition,
which hangs on the cash register at their College Park store, the
Smile Herb Shop. They hope to have 3,000 signatures on the petition
when they submit it to state officials.
   The Wolfes are not the first to try to change the motto. In
1978, a joint resolution requested a legislative committee to
devise ``a more appropriate state motto.''
   ``The motto is incompatible with the equal rights and privileges
accorded to women by the Constitution of the United States,'' read
the bill, which died in the Senate.
   During the past three centuries, scholars have debated the
motto's proper translation. ``Deeds are of more avail than words''
and ``Act boldly but speak softly'' are among the less offensive
translations, said Gregory Stiverson, former editor of Maryland
Manual, a handbook of state government.
   Stiverson believes a corrupt translation has created the motto's
sexist slant. While he favors a change in the traditional
translation, he said state legislative action may prove difficult.
Legislators argued at length a few years ago about whether
``maschii'' should be spelled with a single ``i,'' a double ``i''
or end in the letters ``ij.''
   In their campaign, the Wolfes contacted their legislator,
Delegate Timothy Maloney.
   ``Frankly I'm not convinced the motto itself is sexist,''
Maloney said, ``but if it is, we ought to change it.'' He said a
bill would most likely change the translation, not the motto.
   ``My concern is to just change it so that deeds and words are
not related to gender...and so (the motto) says something
positive,'' Linda Wolfe said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880623-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 1505EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Rowan 3rdLd-Writethru a0664 06-23 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rowan, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0664,600</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDS: Subs grafs 2, The young man, and 11, Smith and Bachman, with
teen-agers pleading innocent, trial date set.</NOTE>
<HEAD>US Won't Charge Columnist, Intruders Plead Not Guilty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syndicated columnist Carl T. Rowan will not be
charged with assault against a man whom he shot after calling
police to report a predawn prowler, the U.S. attorney's office said
today.
   The young man, Benjamin N. Smith, 18, of Chevy Chase, Md., and
his companion, Laura Bachman, 19, of Bethesda, Md., pleaded
innocent to charges of unlawful entry onto Rowan's property in
northwest Washington.
   The U.S. attorney's office said it was referring to District of
Columbia authorities the decision whether to bring weapons charges
against the columnist.
   Rowan, asked to comment on the day's developments, told a
reporter:
   ``I am not saying one word about that decision. I think I've
been very generous in talking to the media, and I've said all I'm
going to say.''
   A city police investigation of the June 14 incident revealed
that .22-caliber handgun Rowan used was not registered with the
District of Columbia.
   U.S. Attorney Jay B. Stephens said in a statement that while his
office believes Rowan should be charged with possession of an
unregistered firearm, the city traditionally prosecutes such
charges.
   Rowan told authorities that the gun had belonged to his son,
Carl T. Rowan Jr., a former FBI agent. Rowan maintained that his
son had been told by city officials he did not need to register the
weapon when he left the FBI. The district's far-reaching 1976
handgun ordinance says that all weapons must be registered.
   If Rowan is charged with possession of an unregistered handgun
and ammunition, he could face penalties on each charge of up to a
year in prison and a fine of up to $1,000.
   Smith and Bachman face a maximum penalty of six months in prison
and a $400 fine on the misdemeanor charges. District of Columbia
Hearing Commissioner J. Dennis Doyle set a trial date of Aug. 18.
The two had been charged with illegal entry shortly after the
incident, but those charges were withdrawn within hours.
   The statement from the U.S. attorney's office said investigators
had found ``insufficient evidence'' to file an assault charge
against Rowan.
   Rowan has said he called police after hearing noises in his
backyard, investigating and finding four people in his pool.
   The columnist said he fired at Smith after the young man lunged
at him. Smith disputes that, saying he was trying to flee when he
was shot.
   Wounded in the hand, Smith was treated and released from a local
hospital.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880623-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 1543EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-GayCandidate     06-23 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gay Candidate,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressional Candidate Acknowledges Homosexuality</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALE LEACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressional candidate endorsed by the
Democratic Party said Thursday he is a homosexual and hopes his
acknowledgement will allow him to concentrate on more important
issues.
   ``Some people say, `Do you want to be honest or get elected?' I
think I can do both,'' said Michael Gelpi, who is running in the
12th District.
   Officials from the Franklin County Democratic Party and Gelpi's
campaign said reaction was mild.
   ``We were prepared for lots of phone calls, and the phone calls
that we have had ... have been very postive and very supportive,''
said Karen Zoeller, Gelpi's campaign manager.
   Gelpi, a 47-year-old businessman, is running as an independent
for the seat held by Rep. John Kasich, a Republican seeking his
fourth term from the central Ohio district, which includes part of
Columbus. Gelpi won the endorsement of the Democratic Party after
it determined that Michael P. Brown, who ran unopposed in the
Democratic primary, is a supporter of extremist Lyndon LaRouche.
   His acknowledgement of his sexual orientation came in a news
release.
   ``I say that my status as a gay person doesn't have anything to
do with this campaign,'' the statement said. ``This campaign is
about issues. It is about the fact that I will do a better job of
representing my constituents than John Kasich _ a much better job.''
   Kasich's Washington office declined comment.
   Gelpi said the issues he feels are important in the campaign
include fighting drug abuse, and improving education and the
economy.
</TEXT>
