<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Fires     06-23 0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Fires,0553</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israelis Responsible For Some Cases of Arson</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mischievous Israeli children and Jewish
settlers seeking retaliation set some of the blazes that have
scorched thousands of acres of land since May, Israeli officials
and Palestinian landowners said Thursday.
   Arab arsonists destroyed most of the 35,000 acres of greenery
torched since this spring. Underground Arab leaders called an
``Arson Day'' on Wednesday, and nine of the 14 fires which broke
out apparently were set by Palestinians, police said.
   But a rarely mentioned fact is that Israelis are responsible for
some of the blazes, despite the importance the Jewish state places
on cultivating the land.
   Settlers living in the occupied West Bank burned more than 400
acres of wheat crops and olive trees in the past month on
Arab-owned land near the city of Nablus, according to Palestinian
farmers.
   They said the settlers appeared to be acting in retaliation for
attacks by Arabs during the 6{-month uprising against Israeli
occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   The Arab farmers' complaints were backed by the daily Haaretz,
which reported settlers were suspected of setting at least eight
recent fires in the West Bank. Israeli police officials in the West
Bank said they could not confirm the reports.
   In addition, some recent fires in Israel were set by Jewish
children who acted ``just for the fun of it,'' Police Minister
Chaim Bar-Lev said on Israel radio.
   Three 9-year-old Jewish boys were caught this week starting a
fire in a field near the Mediterranean coastal city of Tel Aviv,
said Bar-Lev's spokesman Nahum Mendel. Bar-Lev said the three were
simply mischievous, but Mendel declined to elaborate.
   Israeli soldiers are a third group which causes some fires.
Troops sometimes unwittingly ignite fields and trees by gunfire or
flares during target practice or border combat, Galilee Fire Chief
Danny Hanania told The Associated Press.
   In fact, one of the worst blazes Wednesday was caused by
soldiers who shot flares in a grove of avocado trees as they chased
a squad of Palestinian guerrillas near the Lebanese border, Hanania
said.
   He said training accidents were the cause of dozens of fires in
northern Israel in recent months, but he declined to be more
specific. The army routinely refuses to comment on damage or
casualties caused during military training.
   Most of the fires set since May were inside pre-1967 Israel. But
Palestinians in the West Bank also have been victims.
   Farmer Mohammed Amran of Burein village near Nablus said he saw
2{ acres of his wheat crop go up in flames on June 6 after men
wearing Jewish skullcaps parked a van by his field.
   ``I saw three settlers park near my land. Shortly afterward I
saw the field engulfed in smoke,'' Amran said.
   In another case, two shepherds employed by Abdel Moati Silwada
of Rash Rash village near Nablus said they saw two gun-toting
Jewish settlers set a fire that razed 2{ acres of fig and olive
groves on June 13.
   Attorney Muna Rishmawi of Law in the Service of Man, an Arab
affiliate of the Geneva-based International Commission of Jurists,
said details of such cases were being gathered for publication.
</TEXT>
