<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Perot-Mail     06-23 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Perot-Mail,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GAO To Look at Perot's Postal Contract</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate-ordered investigation may delay
completion of a study by billionaire businessman H. Ross Perot to
find ways of saving money at the Postal Service.
   The Senate has requested the General Accounting Office to
investigate terms of the deal, and directed the Postal Service to
delay phase two of the contract.
   Postal officials, meanwhile, defended the deal Thursday and said
they welcomed the investigation.
   ``Although we are aware that adverse statements about the
contacrt are emanating from would-be competitors of Mr. Perot _ and
are presenting a distorted view of this opportunity to bring his
vast business experience to bear on resolving some of our problems
_ we believe this contract is an appropriate step that is
consistent with our ongoing efforts to prepare the Postal Service
for the future,'' the agency said in a statement.
   The $500,000 deal, calling for computer specialist Perot to
analyze postal operations and recommend cost-saving changes, was
announced June 2. It was to last for 90 days, and be followed by a
second phase in which Perot would be paid a percentage of any
savings the service realized from implementing his recommendations.
   ``It's a beautiful arrangement for Perot, but not so pretty for
the postal customers,'' said Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich. ``The Postal
Service will pay the costs for the first phase, then the Perot
company gets a cut of the savings, if phase two is successful.''
   Also critical of the the deal, which was not opened to
competitive bids, were Sens. Paul Simon, D-Ill., and Charles E.
Grassley, R-Iowa.
   The Senate resolution called on the GAO to look into the
contract and report back within 45 days. It also called on the
Postal Service to delay implementation of any second phase of the
contract for a further 45 days to give the Senate time to study the
GAO report.
   Thus, if the study suggests changes in postal operations,
implementation could be delayed by a month or so.
</TEXT>
