<1ST_LINE>r a AM-UrbanHerbs     06-23 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Urban Herbs,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Bronx Herb Farm Bites the Dust</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A greenhouse that provided herbs from the urban
jungle for plates in posh restaurants has gone bankrupt after seven
years.
   The demise of Glie Farms, known officially as South Bronx
Greenhouse, put more than 80 residents of the blighted South Bronx
neighborhood out of work.
   ``They're no longer there. Their jobs have disappeared,'' said
Allen Morrison, spokesman for the Port Authority of New York and
New Jersey, which runs the Bathgate Industrial Park, where the herb
farm once thrived.
   This week, the Sanitation Department removed rows of unkempt
herbs after neighbors complained of the rotting smell. But the
empty greenhouses still may see future harvests.
   ``Something will be grown at Bathgate in their wake; we're
optimistic,'' Morrison said Thursday.
   Glie Farms was founded in 1981, with the help of a federal
grant, as a non-profit venture to provide jobs for runaway youths.
After several years, it became a for-profit venture, building up a
clientele of 800 restaurants and 15 supermarket chains and grossing
as much as $250,000 a month.
   ``Glie Farms was a real Cinderella story,'' said Bob Menge, the
purchasing director for the Four Seasons restaurant in Manhattan.
``But that's the food business. You see so many companies come and
go.''
   Glie founder Gary Waldron said his principal problem had been
difficulty in securing a $1.5 million loan that he negotiated last
year to start a farm in Puerto Rico. The company filed for
bankruptcy a few weeks ago.
</TEXT>
