<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Turkey-Landslides Bjt   06-23 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Turkey-Landslides, Bjt,0456</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>100 Feared Buried by Turkish Landslides</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos FRA4, NY23</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ZEYNEP ALEMDAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mud and rock loosened by rain roared down
on a mountain village and highway Thursday, burying up to 100
people, including 30 travelers stranded in a coffee house by an
earlier landslide, officials said.
   State television said villagers reported hearing people cry out
for help from beneath the ooze and rubble.
   ``It happened all at once after a noise that sounded like
thunder. The rocks swept away everything in a second,'' said Turan
Alemdar, a trucker who saw the disaster, as quoted by the Hurriyet
News Agency.
   Another witness, Zeki Ilha, was quoted as saying: ``I saw the
mountain coming at me and started running away.''
   Rescuers were hampered by rain. Another landslide at 8 p.m.
forced a suspension of the rescue work, but caused no casualties,
the television reported from Catak village, 500 miles northeast of
Ankara near the Black Sea.
   The Black Sea region is known for frequent landslides, some of
which are blamed on extensive cutting of forests.
   Enver Hizlan, the provincial governor, said only one body had
been recovered. Earlier reports said three were found.
   Deputy Gov. Haydar Ozgun told The Associated Press by telephone
the rescue work would resume when landslide experts declared it
safe. The Anatolia news agency said huge searchlights were set up.
   Safa Giray, federal public works minister, flew to the site.
   State radio said 31 people were injured by the landslide in a
mountainous area of Trabzon province.
   Tons of mud and rock covered at least three houses, four stores,
a restaurant and the coffee house crowded with at least 30 bus
passengers stranded by an earlier landslide, the news agencies
reported. A high school also was buried but no children were there
because of summer vacation.
   Several buses and cars were on the road when the landslide hit,
Anatolia reported. Television said it also clogged a river, which
flooded the village, and showed footage of submerged houses.
   Anatolia quoted a supervising official, not identified, as
saying rescuers might need two weeks to clear the debris if the
rain continued. It said 40 trucks and 20 bulldozers were at the
scene.
   Two minibuses were uncovered but no one was inside, the news
reports said.
   Turkey's Red Crescent, the Moslem equivalent of the Red Cross,
sent 150 tents to the area, Antatolia said.
   A dispatch by Hurriyet said the Red Crescent announced over
loudspeakers at scene that 300 people had been killed, causing a
temporary panic. Officials at the scene and elsewhere estimated the
number buried at 100 or fewer.
</TEXT>
