<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FairHousing     06-23 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fair Housing,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Keeps Family Provision in Housing Discrimination Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Thursday refused to kill a
proposal barring discrimination in housing for families with
children.
   The House rejected on a vote of 289-116 an amendment proposed by
Rep. Clay Shaw, R-Fla., that would have stripped the protection for
families with children from legislation designed to strengthen the
enforcement of the nation's fair housing law.
   Under the bill, families with children under 18 could not be
refused housing except in retirement communities where at least 90
percent of the tenants are 55 or older and the facilities are
specifically designed for the physical or social needs of retirees.
Any community renting to those 62 or older would be exempt even if
it did not provide special facilities.
   Final action on the bill was delayed as the House recessed for
the day to attend the funeral services of Rep. John J. Duncan,
R-Tenn., in Knoxville. The bill is expected to be taken up again
late next week.
   Senate leaders have said they would take up the bill after the
House approves it, indicating that the legislation may go to the
White House before the end of summer.
   Civil rights groups and Realtors earlier this week ended a
20-year battle by reaching a compromise to put teeth in the basic
fair-housing law while still satisfying President Reagan's concerns
about constitutional guarantees.
   The bill would give the Department of Housing and Urban
Development the power to bring actions on behalf of individual
victims of discrimination, would ban discrimination against the
disabled and would forbid limitations on renting to families with
children, except in the clearly defined retirement communities.
   Under the compromise, HUD would be required to investigate
complaints of discrimination in the sale or rental of housing. And
it would be authorized to lodge charges if it finds ``reasonable
cause'' to believe that discrimination may have occurred.
   At that point, there would be an administrative proceeding
unless either the plaintiff or the defendant requests a jury trial;
either proceeding could lead to imposition of fines or injunctions
and could be appealed to a higher court.
   The compromise language which gives the accused the right to a
civil trial by jury was introduced by Rep. Hamilton Fish Jr.,
R-N.Y., and was passed by the House 401-0.
   The House also passed by voice vote an amendment by Rep. Barney
Frank, D-Mass., which would permit the exclusion of an individual
who threatens the safety of others and one by Rep. Robert S.
Walker, R-Pa., to take away protection of the law from anyone
convicted of drug manufacturing.
   The Shaw amendment would have eliminated the provisions of the
bill extending protection from housing discrimination to families
with children under the age of 18. It would have required the Civil
Rights Commission to conduct a study on the nature and extent of
housing discrimination against familes with children and report to
Congress within three years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880623-0163 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 2046EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Grain     06-23 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Grain,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kremlin Launches New Grain Push</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has sharply raised the bonuses it
pays to farms for grain in a major new effort to stimulate
production and cut imports, Tass reported Thursday.
   The decision by the Communist Party's policy-making Central
Committee and the government's Council of Ministers, the Cabinet,
reflects the hard push Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev is making
to invigorate the sluggish Soviet economy.
   The new drive to breathe life into Soviet agriculture comes at
an important time politically for Gorbachev: just days before the
Communist Party holds a conference to review progress in the three
years of his program of perestroika, or restructuring. About 5,000
delegates from around the country are to convene the meeting in
Moscow on Tuesday.
   Bonuses for grain production were introduced last year.
Gorbachev, a former Central Committee agriculture secretary,
apparently believed the time was ripe to increase the incentives.
   Tass, the official news agency, said the sharp increases in
bonuses were aimed primarily at stimulating production of
high-quality grains.
   ``The noted bonuses are paid out when the quality of production
meets the demands of state standards,'' the report said.
   The bonus for durum wheat was raised to 150 percent. Tass did
not say what the earlier level was. This means that if any farm
produces more durum wheat than the state orders, any surplus is
bought for the regular price plus 150 percent of that price.
Bonuses were also raised for increased production of other grain
products.
   The new bonuses are to take effect July 1, but one Western
diplomat familiar with Soviet agriculture said he doubts there will
be any quick results.
   ``It's like telling a football team at the end of the third
quarter that if you win the game, you'll get a $5,000 bonus instead
of a $2,000 bonus. It just comes too late,'' said the diplomat,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Soviet grain production has consistently fallen below targeted
levels, and this has forced the country to make large imports. Last
year's harvest was 211.4 million tons. This was an improvement
since larger shortfalls in previous years. The United States
Agriculture Department estimates Soviet grain production this year
will amount to 215 million tons. The targeted level is 235 million
tons.
   Under an agreement with the United States, the Soviet Union must
buy at least 9 million tons of grain annually.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
