<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia     06-23 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strikers Assault Mayor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking autoworkers demanding a 50
percent pay increase assaulted the mayor of the Slovenian city of
Maribor on Thursday as he tried to calm them down, the official
Tanjug news agency said.
   Tanjug said the workers were angred by a report that most of the
strikers from the TAM truck and military vehicle factory had
returned to work, and Mayor Ivan Cuk tried to soothe them.
   ``Instead, he hardly managed to escape an assault of several
angry persons,'' Tanjug said, without elaborating.
   The incident took place in the northern Yugoslav city when
strikers reportedly refused to accept a proposed 7.5 percent pay
increase. A company spokesman said Thursday that about 4,000 of the
employees had returned to work.
   Tanjug said that 1,500 TAM workers were joined by 3,000 workers
from three other plants and marched to the center of the city.
   It added that the workers began dispersing around noon. Sources
said police blocked off one downtown street, but no arrests were
made.
   The 5,000 employees of TAM went on strike Tuesday seeking higher
wages. Several hundred workers from four other plants in the
Slovenian city joined the walkout in the first such show of
solidarity reported in Yugoslavia.
   The Belgrade daily Politika said as many as 7,500 workers were
involved.
   The strikers claim their wages threaten minimum standards of
living.
   Yugoslavia is planning to reduce inflation to 90 percent this
year, compared with an average 170 percent last year.
   Yugoslavia's economy, a mixture of free-market elements and
Soviet-style central planning, has been growing at a sluggish rate
averaging less than 1 percent annually over the past six years.
   The government on Saturday launched an austerity program that
   included substantial price increases, wage cuts of up to 30
percent and a 23.9 percent devaluation of the dinar, the national
currency.
</TEXT>
