<1ST_LINE>u w AM-SwindallProbe     06-23 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Swindall Probe,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Ethics Panel to Probe Congressman in Loan Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House ethics committee announced Thursday
it is launching a formal preliminary investigation into whether
Rep. Patrick L. Swindall, R-Ga., violated the law or House rules in
seeking a loan that he knew was being financed by drug proceeds.
   The panel, formally known as the Committee on Standards of
Official Conduct, said it had recieved evidence ``reasonably
indicating'' that Swindall may have departed from acceptable
standards in seeking to negotiate the $850,000 loan.
   Secretly taped conversations reported last week by the Atlanta
Constitution showed that Swindall was advised by an undercover
agent that the money almost certainly came from drug trafficking,
but he continued to pursue the transaction for a month.
   The two-term congressman was seeking to refinance a construction
loan on his $1.2 million home in Stone Mountain, Ga., near Atlanta,
and convert it to a long-term mortgage.
   An aide to Swindall, Bill Thorne, said the ethics committee had
``done what we asked them to do.'' He said Swindall had sought the
investigation and was confident he would be cleared of wrongdoing.
   Swindall was on his way back to Georgia for the weekend and
unavailable for comment, Thorne said.
   A preliminary inquiry is the first step in an ethics committee
investigation. If the panel finds reason to believe that the
alleged violation in fact occurred, it makes a formal statement of
the violation and can ultimately recommend disciplinary action.
   Swindall ultimately backed out of the deal after being told he
would have to accept the cash loan in person and sign a receipt for
it.
   ``The only reason I can't do that is I would then be essentially
laundering y'all's money,'' Swindall told an Internal Revenue
Service undercover agent, according to the Constitution.
   ``In other words, if Charles (LeChasney, who has subsequently
been indicted on money-laundering charges) wants to launder y'all's
money, fine, but I can't do that, and to sign a receipt of cash
would be to do that.''
   Swindall, at a town meeting in his congressional district last
week, apologized for his behavior and asked voters to forgive him.
   ``I did entertain the idea, and it was wrong,'' Swindall said.
But he said he had no intention of resigning, and ``I hope (voters)
will find it in their hearts to forgive what I have done.''
   Swindall, who faces a tough re-election battle this fall, said
he was tempted to accept the loan because of financial pressures
stemming from cost overruns on the large new house he was building.
   But he said he backed away when he became convinced the
transaction was illicit.
   ``When it was between myself and my maker, I made the right
decision,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
