<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 1614EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-WhiteHouseForecast     06-23 0636</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-White House Forecast,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sprinkel Says His Rosy Economic Views Weren't Rosy Enough</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beryl Sprinkel, chairman of President Reagan's
Council of Economic Advisers, took a lot of heat in the months
after the stock market crash for seeing the world through
rose-colored glasses and predicting strong, steady economic growth
this year.
   Many private economists had issued deeply pessimistic
projections, fearing that the Oct. 19 market collapse, when
investors lost $500 billion in a single day, would shock consumers
into cutting back and topple the country into a recession.
   But the actual performance of the economy as measured by the
gross national product _ 4.8 percent annual growth in the fourth
quarter of 1987 and 3.6 percent growth in the first three months of
this year _ made even the White House estimates look too gloomy.
   ``Our rosy forecast wasn't rosy enough. The economy is doing
better than even we expected,'' a smiling, confident Sprinkel told
reporters at a White House briefing Thursday.
   He said the administration now expects the economy to grow 3.5
percent, year-over-year, in 1988, compared with an earlier
projection of 2.9 percent. The forecast of average unemployment is
moving from 5.8 percent to 5.5 percent
   And despite fears of inflation by stock and bond traders, he
said he's holding steady on his prediction for consumer price
inflation of 4.3 percent and expects only an average increase in
interest rates of half a percentage point.
   President Reagan, responding to a reporter's question at a
picture-taking session, said he's not worried about inflation
either.
   ``All the evidence shows us that our recovery is going on and,
no, there is no great threat of inflation,'' the president said.
   Private analysts found little fault with the administration's
new growth estimate, but they said its optimistic view of inflation
fails to take into account the potentially devastating effect on
food prices of the drought scorching crops in the nation's
midsection.
   ``He's certainly right about better growth ... but the rest is
just pie in the sky stuff,'' said Michael K. Evans, an economic
consultant in Washington.
   Sprinkel conceded the drought could have ``a significant effect
on food prices,'' but said it is too soon to say how significant.
   ``We cannot guess because I don't know whether it's going to
rain. I hope soon,'' Sprinkel said
   But the National Weather Service said Thursday that the
six-to-10-day outlook for the Midwest and Great Plains calls for
more hot, dry weather.
   Sprinkel noted, however, that the farm community generates only
about 2 percent of the gross national product.
   David Jones, chief economist of Aubrey G. Lanston & Co., a
government securities dealer, said, ``I think almost everyone is
underestimating how devastating the drought can be to food
prices.'' He noted that food makes up about one-fifth the consumer
price index.
   ``I think the shading of the administration's estimates on
inflation may involve at least some election year politics in
addition to economic analysis,'' he said. ``I think what the
administration is trying to do is present a picture of strong
economic growth and low inflation as we come into an election.''
   But Sprinkel said, ``Our economy is not overheating, as
sometimes feared.'' He said the administration bases its inflation
predictions on the expectation that economic growth will slow
somewhat in the remaining nine months of they year from the
first-quarter pace.
   He said growth projections for 1989 and beyond were being
revised downward slightly to offset the upward revision for 1988
and the stronger-than-expected growth experienced during 1987. For
1989, the administration expects the economy to grow 3.1 percent.
   ``For those of you who are always trying to figure out what we
are thinking, it means we envision some decline in interest rates
later this year,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
