<1ST_LINE>u i AM-GulfRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0654 06-23 0640</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0654,0656</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraqis Blast Iranian Oil Targets</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs `All the...' with 1 graf to UPDATE with
total number of missions claimed by Iraq. INSERTS 1 graf after 7th
pvs `The agency...' to UPDATE with Iraq denying hitting civilian
areas. PICKS up 8th graf pvs bgng, INA quoted a ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq said its warplanes bombed 10 Iranian
oil installations Thursday in the heaviest air raids on Tehran's
economic backbone in weeks.
   The official Iraqi News Agency said six production installations
in the Ahwaz oilfields in southwestern Khuzestan province were set
on fire.
   Later, two installations at the Bibi Hakimah oilfield, 120 miles
to the southeast, were bombed and set ablaze, INA said. The report
was monitored in Nicosia.
   Another formation of jets hit two pumping stations at the Gash
Saran field north of Bibi Hakimah at about the same time, leaving
them shrouded in flames and smoke, the agency said.
   INA said its jet fighters flew 113 missions and its helicopter
gunships 30 missions and all returned safely to their bases.
   There was no independent confirmation of the Iraqi claims. But
Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency, also monitored in
Cyprus, reported that Iraqi jets bombed ``a residential area and
labor quarters'' in the Ahvaz area, killing one civilian.
   The agency said other unspecified areas also were bombed. But it
made no mention of oil installations being hit.
   INA denied residential areas were hit, saying the bombing ``was
confined to striking installations at oilfields and Iranian
military positions.''
   INA quoted a military communique as saying the raids were a
message to Tehran that ``it has lost the war in all fields and that
there is no alternative to save Iran from total deterioration but
to accept peace.''
   Thursday's raids were the first significant attacks on Iran's
vital oil installations on land since early May, when
fighter-bombers attacked several oil refineries and petrochemical
plants.
   The air force also has attacked several Iranian oil tankers in
the Persian Gulf in its campaign to choke off Iran's oil exports
which Tehran needs to pay for its war effort.
   Iran and Iraq have been at war since September 1980.
   French-built Iraqi Mirage F-1s carried out a long-range
1,500-mile raid on Iran's Larak Island oil terminal in the Strait
of Hormuz May 14.
   Five tankers were set on fire. They included the world's largest
vessel, the 564,739-ton Seawise Giant, which was badly damaged.
   The Iraqi air offensive inflicted considerable damage on Iran's
oil infrastructure in March and April, oil industry and diplomatic
sources reported. Refineries were repeatedly hit.
   Oil industry sources have reported that Iran has been forced to
import unprecedented amounts of refined products, such as aviation
fuel and kerosene, because its refinery production has been badly
reduced.
   Despite the Iraqi raids, Iran has maintained its oil production
at around an average of 2.3 million barrels a day, with exports of
around 1.4 million barrels a day, the respected Middle East
Economic Survey reported.
   That's about the mimimum level Iran needs to maintain to earn
sufficient revenue to keep its war effort going. Oil revenue
accounts for some 95 percent of Iran's foreign exchange earnings.
   Oil sales earned $20 billion a year in 1983, but plummeted to
only around $6 billion in 1986 when oil prices collapsed.
   The Iranians have suffered two major battlefield defeats in
recent weeks, which along with political in-fighting in Tehran and
economic woes, have pushed them on the defensive for the first time
in several years.
   Iraq's air force has been concentrating on attacking Iranian
troop buildups in the past few weeks as the land war heated up,
with the Iraqi Army abandoning its long-held strategy of static
defense to go on the offensive for the first time in six years.
</TEXT>
