<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soweto     06-23 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soweto,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High-Rise Apartments Planned for Black Township</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A company said Thursday it
plans to build the first high-rise apartment complex in Soweto, the
vast black township where tens of thousands of people live in
shacks because of a housing shortage.
   The project envisions 40,000 people would be able to live in
7,000 to 8,000 apartments in buildings up to 25 stories. Two dozen
schools will be built in six three-story buildings nearby,
according to the $230 million plan by the non-profit Foundation for
Community Development.
   The highest building in Soweto, where an estimated 2.5 million
people live on 40 square miles of low hills, is now a 10-story
nurses' dormitory.
   Aside from a few two-story houses in higher-income
neighborhoods, Sowetans live on small lots in one-story houses.
Many have outside toilets and no bathrooms.
   Most homes now have running water and electricity, but
squatters, relatives and friends of householders live by the
thousands in shacks, sheds and garages.
   There are relatively few apartment buildings for blacks anywhere
in South Africa.
   The proposed Soweto complex would house 40,000 people where two
hostels previously accommodated 4,000.
   The non-profit foundation said a studio apartment in the new
complex would be sold rather than rented and would cost about
$6,000. It said that compared to an average $6,500 for a serviced
plot of land without a house in a township.
   South Africa's apartheid laws require blacks to live in
segregated townships, most of them relatively far from urban
centers where they work. Under apartheid, South Africa's 26 million
blacks have no vote in national affairs and have separate schools
and health services.
   Anti-apartheid activists accuse of the government of restricting
the available land for black housing to control the numbers of
blacks in urban areas. One result has been massive squatter camps.
   The government recently announced a plan to add vacant land to
the black townships around Johannesburg for more black housing. One
proposed community north of Johannesburg may be designated as an
area where people of any race could live.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
