<HEAD>Congressman Denies His Aide Was Under FBI Surveillance Before
Suicide</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Defense Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Roy Dyson, D-Md., on Thursday labeled as
``absolutely untrue'' and ``politically motivated'' a newspaper
report that the FBI had Dyson's aide under surveillance last month
when the aide committed suicide by jumping from a New York hotel.
   ``There is absolutely no basis in fact to these reports. I've
never been contacted by any investigators, no one in my office has
been contacted, none of my friends has been contacted,'' Dyson said
in an interview.
   The New York Post, quoting unnamed law enforcement officials,
said FBI agents were watching the hotel as part of an investigation
of alleged Pentagon fraud and bribery.
   The newspaper quoted the sources as saying the FBI was
monitoring the trip because the event was financed by Unisys, a
defense contractor. The aide, Tom Pappas, committed suicide by
jumping from a hotel window in midtown Manhattan on May 1.
   Dyson, a member of the House Armed Services procurement
subcommittee, is one of five House members whose names had been
linked to the Pentagon investigation in the past week.
   But on Wednesday, Henry Hudson, the U.S. attorney in charge of
the case, told House leaders that no congressmen are targets of the
widespread investigation. House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, said
he had been assured that no congressmen are among the targets.
   ``The speaker said yesterday and the U.S. attorney said
yesterday that no member of Congress is a target,'' Dyson noted.
``I just have to assume that if somebody's leaking this stuff, it's
politically motivated and they're just trying to focus attention
away from the Pentagon and onto Capitol Hill.''
   ``I can't tell exactly who's behind it, but if these kind of
leaks come about and there's no foundation for it, I would have to
assume it's partisan. It would have be Republicans,'' he said.
   ``This is absolutely untrue, unfounded and I don't think it's
honorable of people in the executive branch to leak this kind of
stuff,'' Dyson said.
</TEXT>
