<HEAD>TV Hall of Fame Announces New Inductees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Television Hall of Fame will induct eight
new members this fall, including two of TV's most famous teams,
Burns and Allen and Huntley and Brinkley, it was announced Thursday.
   The inductees include four comedians, two newsmen and two
producers, who will be inducted Nov. 19 in a two-hour special to be
telecast on Fox Broadcasting Co. on Nov. 28.
   They are: Jack Benny, George Burns and Gracie Allen, Chet
Huntley and David Brinkley, Red Skelton, David Susskind and David
Wolper.
   The Hall of Fame was established five years ago by the Academy
of Television Arts & Sciences.
   Comedians Burns and Allen were on radio and television for many
years. Huntley and Brinkley were television's top news team in the
1950s and 1960s.
   Benny and Skelton were popular comedians, and producers Susskind
and Wolper were responsible for some of television's most memorable
programs.
   Burns, Brinkley, Skelton and Wolper are expected to be at the
ceremonies. The others will be honored posthumously.
