<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SpoletoFestival     06-23 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spoleto Festival,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spoleto Festival Opens with American Ballet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPOLETO, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The annual Festival of Two Worlds opened
Thursday night in the medieval hilltown of Spoleto, amid
projections the event would surpass last year's attendance figures.
   The Joffrey Ballet, the renowned U.S. dance company, kicked off
the 18-day program with an Italian premiere of ``Light Rain,''
followed by Stravinsky's ``Rite of Spring,'' the prototype of
modern dance first performed in 1913.
   Among the highlights of the 1988 festival will be Polish-born
director Roman Polanski's presentation of Franz Kafka's surrealist
``Metamorphosis,'' and a new tragedy by Italian playwright Mario
Missiroli. Missiroli's work explores the relationship between
Italy's fascist dictator Benito Mussolini and his mistress, Clara
Petacci, in the setting of the country's fascist upheaval of the
1930s and 1940s.
   The festival includes three operas, five ballets, 11 plays and
47 concerts, in addition to art exhibits and film showings.
   Ticket sales have so far outpaced last year's advance sales,
according to a festival spokesman, who added that most of the
performances for the first five days have been sold out.
   Organizers said Thursday they are optimistic this year's
attendance will exceed the 1987 levels of more than 100,000
visitors, despite a production schedule containing 60 fewer
performances than last year.
   Last year the festival earned $650,000 from ticket sales, far
short of the $4 million in costs.
   Gian Carlo Menotti, the Pulitzer Prize-winning composer and
founder of the festival, chose the ancient setting of Spoleto in
1957 with the aim of merging the cultural worlds of Europe and
America. In 1977 he took the festival to Charleston, S.C., and in
1986 he expanded the project to Melbourne, Australia.
   Menotti retains a dominant role in all of the festival's
artistic and organizational aspects.
   This year's festival runs through July 10.
</TEXT>
