<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Drought-Birds     06-23 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Birds,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drought Takes Toll on Abandoned Baby Sparrow Hawks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Heat-Drought, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORWALK, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A family is feeding worms to a nestful of
baby sparrow hawks after the birds' parents apparently abandoned
them to search for water and food amid the lingering drought.
   Five baby American kestrels, a type of small falcon commonly
known as a sparrow hawk, plopped down at the picnic table of June
Shawver's home in this community Monday.
   Family members have been giving worms to the brown-speckled
birds, which are members of a federally protected species.
   ``Sunday, I saw a bird out my window that I thought was an
owl,'' said Ms. Shawver. She now believes the bird was probably the
adult bird just as it was abandoning the nest.
   The next day, she found the babies, who are about 6 inches long
and will grow to up to 12 inches. The birds happily dined on worms
that the family had gathered to feed a pet turtle, she said.
   ``They were gobbling them up like crazy,'' Ms. Shawver said.
   Because the kestrels, like all birds of prey, are protected by
federal law, Ms. Shawver notified State Game Protector Jerry
Duckworth. Duckworth said it was not normal for parent birds to
leave a nest like that.
   ``More than likely it was the lack of water and insects that
prompted the birds to abandon the nest,'' Duckworth said. ``There
was not enough food for the parents to survive, so they left.''
   While it is illegal to possess the kestrels, dead or alive, the
Shawvers will be allowed to feed the baby birds so long as they are
not confined in any way, Duckworth said.
   The birds are gradually getting adult feathers, Ms. Shawver said.
   ``You can see them changing every day,'' she said. ``The female
is the most aggressive. She is bigger than the rest. She seems to
stand up by herself a lot.''
</TEXT>
