<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ToxicMail     06-23 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Toxic Mail,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Toxic Shipments Target Of Criticism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of Congress and spokesmen for postal
workers expressed alarm Thursday over the shipment of biological
toxins and other deadly agents through the U.S. mail system, saying
the items are not properly packaged at times.
   But officials from the Defense Department and the Centers for
Disease Control, both shippers of such items, defended their
procedures and said elaborate packaging precautions are taken.
   The Postal Service said it is considering tighter regulations
that would ban the shipment of some disease-causing agents and
microorganisms from its mail service.
   The action is being considered because an expected increase in
such shipments through the Postal Service could cause a possible
hazard to postal workers, Frank Henselton, assistant postmaster
general, said at a congressional hearing.
   The proposed regulation was to be issued Thursday followed by a
45-day comment period before a final rule is taken under
consideration, he said. Many of the shipments of disease-related
agents already are shipped by private overnight carriers.
   The Postal Service's assurances did not ease some of the concern
expressed by members of a subcommittee of the Post Office and Civil
Service Committee.
   ``These viruses are intended for warfare, they're intended to
kill people,'' declared Rep. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., adding that
they should not go through the regular mail system.
   Moe Biller, president of the American Postal Workers Union,
called plans by the U.S. Army to expand its shipment of toxic
materials through the postal system ``bizarre'' and a ``devious
scheme'' that should be rejected.
   He said that at the very least the Postal Service should require
a permit to ship toxic specimens ``and should require advance
notice before it is presented for acceptance into the mailstream.''
   Eighteen members of Congress sent a letter to Defense Secretary
Frank Carlucci earlier this month expressing their concerns about
the Army's plan to expand the shipment of toxins by registered mail
from research centers around the country to a proposed testing
center at the Dugway Proving Grounds in Utah.
   Such shipments, said Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., ``will expose
postal workers and the general public to an unacceptable health
risk.'' She said the Army has gone ``to great lengths'' to describe
the safety precautions being taken at the proposed laboratory but
shows a lack of concern with shipping safeguards.
   Thousands of toxins and disease agents are shipped through the
postal service by private laboratories as well as the Defense
Department and the CDC, witnesses said. While the shipments require
strict packaging, in some cases up to five layers of packing, there
still are spills, witnesses said.
   Gerald Miss, a Postal Service mail handler from Frederick, Md.,
said he and his colleagues frequently have observed shipments that
are not properly packaged.
   Miss said that last November he came across a dripping styrofoam
parcel containing flu vaccine, which dripped over his hands and
onto his apron.
   ``Though the spill did not result in an illness it points to a
potential threat,'' he told the subcommittee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
