<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Keillor-NPR     06-23 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Keillor-NPR,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Keillor Settles Suit With NPR Over Tape of Speech</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Garrison Keillor and National Public Radio
said Thursday they had settled a lawsuit that the star of ``A
Prairie Home Companion'' brought alleging copyright infringement.
   The terms of the settlement call for NPR, through Keillor, to
make available free to people who request them 400 cassettes of a
disputed speech Keillor made in October 1987 at the National Press
Club in Washington.
   The speech covered various topics and promoted his book,
``Leaving Home.'' NPR, which long has transmitted National Press
Club luncheon appearances to member stations, included the speech
in its catalog of cassettes for sale.
   In his lawsuit, filed in Minneapolis, Minn., Keillor said he
never gave the radio network permission to use the speech.
   ``It was an expensive suit and they tried to punish me as much
as possible and make it cost as much as possible by going through
days of tortuous depositions, and after they put us all through the
grinder as far as they could, they agreed to stop doing what I was
suing them to stop doing,'' he said in an interview Thursday.
   ``I never wanted any money from them, and there was never any
money asked for,'' he said. ``I just wanted them to leave my work
alone.''
   Keillor had sought in the suit to have all unsold tapes
destroyed and a list of people who had bought the tapes. He also
had asked for unspecified damages and attorneys fees.
   NPR defended its sale of the cassette, saying it handled
Keillor's appearance before the press club no differently than it
handled talks by others.
   The nonprofit radio network said it has distributed tapes of
those events to the public through its cassette catalog since 1979
and has more than 130 titles.
   Spoken Arts Inc. of New York, which produces and distributes
some cassettes for NPR, was included in the settlement. Officials
at Spoken Arts were out of the office and not available for comment.
   NPR said it believes Keillor's book publicist was aware when he
arranged the appearance that cassettes would be distributed and
that Keillor also was aware of the arrangements.
   ``NPR thinks it is important to preserve its right to distribute
programs and cassettes of press club appearances as part of its
service to the listening public,'' the radio network said.
   Keiller's nationally broadcast variety show, ``A Prairie Home
Companion,'' which was produced by Minnesota Public Radio and
distributed by American Public Radio, was discontinued a year ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
