<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis-Cuomo     06-23 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Cuomo,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuomo Expects No Quick Decision on Dukakis Veep Choice</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Gov. Mario Cuomo said Thursday
that, after a long discussion with a top aide to Michael Dukakis,
he thinks there'll be no quick decision on a Democratic vice
presidential candidate.
   Meanwhile, a political adviser to both Cuomo and Dukakis said
the New York governor had agreed to stump the nation in support of
Dukakis' presidential campaign.
   Cuomo said he had talked Wednesday with Paul Brountas, who is
leading the effort to find a running mate for Dukakis, about the
vice presidential selection process and came away with the
impression that it would take awhile.
   ``They do not seem to me the kind of people who would make
precipitous judgments or very early judgments,'' said Cuomo. ``I
don't expect a quick decision.''
   Cuomo said he and Brountas talked about Jesse Jackson and the
New York governor's role, but he did not provide details. He noted
that a Dukakis-Cuomo ticket was not discussed.
   ``That's not even a question,'' said Cuomo.
   Brountas didn't return telephone messages left at his office.
   Meanwhile, former Cuomo aide Michael Del Giudice said the
governor would soon be helping the Dukakis campaign in other ways.
   ``The Dukakis people want him to talk in other parts of the
country, getting out the Democratic agenda and talking about
Dukakis,'' said Del Giudice, a Wall Street investment banker who
served as chief of staff to Cuomo during the governor's first term.
Del Giudice helped put together Dukakis' successful New York
primary campaign.
   The former Cuomo aide said the New York governor would ``take a
very active role'' in the Dukakis campaign and had already
scheduled speaking engagements in California and Florida.
   Cuomo, once considered a possible 1988 Democratic presidential
candidate himself, remained neutral through the New York primary
and didn't endorse Dukakis until the primary season ended June 7.
By then Dukakis already had the nomination sewed up.
</TEXT>
