<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 2118EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Afghan-Soviets     06-23 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghan-Soviets,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Official Says Soviet Withdrawal `Well Under Way'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The withdrawal of Soviet forces from
Afghanistan is ``well under way'' with the Russians pulling out
their troops on schedule, a senior State Department official
testified Thursday.
   ``So far we see no evidence that the Soviets do not intend to
meet their troop withdrawal deadlines on Aug. 15 and Feb. 15,
1989,'' Undersecretary of State Michael H. Armacost told the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee.
   But Armacost resisted demands by Sen. Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H.,
that the United States immediately appoint an ambassador at large
to deal with the Afghan resistance movement.
   He indicated that the Reagan administration prefers to wait
until a full-fledged government emerges that has widespread support
of the Afghan people before extending any sort of official or
informal recognition.
   Humphrey, who testified before the committee, also asked that
U.S. aid to Afghan refugees be doubled.
   Richard S. Williamson, assistant secretary of state for
international organizations, said emphasis is being put on
organizing a United Nations relief and resettlement program for the
Afghan people, some 5.5 million of whom are refugees in either
Pakistan or Iran.
   Williamson said that in the fiscal year ending Sept. 30 the
United States will have made about $142 million in relief funds
available for Afghan refugees.
   The State Department does not intend to seek a supplemental
appropriation to provide additional funds for the period because of
budget constraints, he said, adding: ``Our continuing programs are
consistent with, supportive of and will be closely coordinated with
the U.N. effort.''
   He said the United States is encouraging other nations to make
substantial contributions to the Afghan relief effort administered
by the U.N.
   ``In our appeals we point out that we are by far the largest
donor of humanitarian assistance to Afghans and that others should
now assume a major share of the new burden as the refugees begin
their return home,'' he said.
   Williamson also made clear that the Soviet Union is being asked
to bear a large share of the costs.
   ``It destroyed the country of Afghanistan. It is obligated to
pay a major part of the bill to rebuild it,'' he said. ``But its
contribution to the U.N. must come without strings or any
requirements that the funds be used to bolster the illegitimate
Kabul regime.''
   He said the Soviets also should help in eliminating the danger
posed by the thousands of landmines thay have planted on Afghan
territory.
</TEXT>
