<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0739 06-23 0981</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0739,990</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Backs Tax Hike At Home; Jackson Says He's Made Up Mind On
Veep</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Tops with 15 grafs to update with Dukakis backing new taxes
and fresh comments on land probe; picks up 9th graf pvs, Jackson
added</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis announced his backing
Thursday for $115 million in new taxes to ``make sure the state's
fiscal base is solid and strong'' and also faced questions about
his administration's acquisition of land for a new prison _ a deal
now under scrutiny by the FBI.
   On the Republican side, George Bush had breakfast with former
U.N. Ambassador Jeane Kirkpatrick while an independent group called
``Americans for Bush'' announced plans to spend $10 million
supporting him in the presidential campaign.
   Jesse Jackson said he's made up his mind about the Democratic
vice presidential nomination but won't reveal his decision unless
asked by Dukakis.
   Making two long-awaited fiscal decisions certain to provide
campaign ammunition to the Republicans, the Democratic governor
announced he had signed a $40 million cigarette tax and favored
raising another $75 million by bringing the Massachusetts tax code
in line with federal tax law changes.
   Dukakis said he had balanced nine state budgets, a record he
characterized as in ``sharp contrast'' to that of the Reagan
administration.
   ``I think the people of this state and the people of this
country can recognize when someone is talking about fiscal
responsibility and someone who is doing it,'' Dukakis told a
Statehouse news conference. The Massachusetts Constitution requires
the governor to balance the budget although Dukakis has twice
inherited deficits.
   In statements issued in Washington and Boston, the FBI
acknowledged it has opened a preliminary inquiry to determine if
federal laws were violated in connection with a proposal to place a
new state prison in New Braintree, Mass.
   ``Gov. Michael Dukakis is not the subject of an investigation,''
FBI spokeswoman Kathy Bradford said in Washington.
   Residents of the rural community of 800 people waged a bitter
fight against placement of the medium-security prison in their area
and some opponents have contended that the current owners of the
700-acre parcel had inside information that the property would be
chosen as the site of the new prison.
   A development firm owned by Gary Striar and Gary Jacobson bought
the land from the Seventh Day Adventist Church in 1985 for $3
million. They have offered to sell it to the state for $9.5 million.
   Jacobson and his wife contributed $1,000 each to Dukakis'
presidential campaign, the maximum allowed by law.
   Asked about the deal, Dukakis told reporters in Fall River,
Mass., ``The process was as open as it could possibly be. ... We
have very tough procedures for the acquisition of property.''
   Jacobson and Dukakis grew up near each other in the Boston
suburb of Brookline.
   The governor told a statehouse news conference upon his return
from Fall River that he was unaware who owned the land when he
chose it as a prison site.
   ``One of them grew up around the corner from me and I remember
shoverling his parents' driveway,'' he said. ``Any suggestions that
the secretary of human services and his staff proceeded other than
in accordance with the law and strict standards of integrity are
unfortunate and regrettable.''
   Jackson added a new element to speculation over whether he is
interested in the vice presidential nomination when he was asked in
Washington whether he had privately made an decision on whether
he'd accept second place on the ticket if it were offered by
Dukakis.
   ``Privately, yes,'' he replied.
   Had he informed Dukakis?
   ``No,'' he said. ``That would be public.''
   Jackson met with his state campaign chairmen for pre-convention
planning and then flew to Puerto Rico. Although Jackson won Puerto
Rico's beauty contest primary, Dukakis ended up with all of the
territory's 57 delegates.
   ``No doubt there will be some adjustments made in Puerto Rico,''
he said.
   Meanwhile, the Democratic Party made what chairman Paul G. Kirk
Jr. claimed was history by settling all delegate challenges before
the July convention in Atlanta.
   After the last four disputes, involving delegates in Indiana,
Kansas, Maine and Virginia, were settled, Kirk said it was the
first time the Democrats would open their convention without a
single delegate challenge.
   But disputes over platform issues were far from over.
   One of those was highlighted Thursday when Dukakis was asked if
he could support Jackson's call for an independent Palestinian
state.
   ``No, of course not,'' he said.
   ``I support direct negotiations between Israel and its neighbors
and responsible Palestinians who ... recognize Israel's right to
exist within its borders,'' Dukakis said. ``I'm going to do
everything I can as president to create an environment in which
these discussions can take place.''
   Republican Party chairmen from 13 Southern states met in
Charleston, S.C., and were told by Bush campaign manager Lee
Atwater that the vice president would be emphasizing the
differences between himself and Dukakis in the fall campaign.
   ``It's obvious to me the Democratic Party and the Dukakis
campaign has made a very conscious decision to try to make the case
there's not a lot of difference between the candidates,'' said
Atwater, a native South Carolinian.
   ``Americans for Bush,'' unveiled the first of what it said would
be a series of television commercials supporting Bush.
   The commercial describes Bush's career as a Navy pilot,
businessman, member of Congress, U.N. ambassador, U.S.
representative in China and as vice president. Floyd Brown, a
spokesman for the group, said $330,000 was being spent to air the
commercial on several cable networks.
   Bush had no public appearances, but he began the day with a
breakfast with Mrs. Kirkpatrick, who is often mentioned as a
possible vice presidential candidate. The former United Nations
ambassador is a favorite of GOP conservatives who like her tough
anti-communist positions on foreign policy.
</TEXT>
