<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Reagan-Drought     06-23 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Drought,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lyng Tells Reagan It's Too Early for Relief Measures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Drought-Heat Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture Secretary Richard Lyng told
President Reagan on Thursday that it is too early for emergency
relief measures to deal with effects of the drought, a White House
spokesman reported.
   ``Despite the serious potential effects of the drought, the
secretary said rainfall in the next two weeks would alleviate much
of the potential damage,'' Deputy Press Secretary B. Jay Cooper
said.
   Vice President George Bush, however, said in a separate
statement, ``If conditions continue to deteriorate, money that has
been saved in this year's farm programs will be redirected to farm
families as disaster relief for the rural economy.''
   Rising crop prices are expected to reduce the direct subsidies
that would have to be paid to farmers this year, saving an
unspecified amount of federal money.
   Cooper said Lyng also reported that the Presidential Interagency
Drought Policy Committee is establishing a toll-free telephone
number to answer questions about federal services available to
citizens in drought-stricken areas.
   The hotline begins operation Friday and will operated from 8
a.m. to 6 p.m. EDT on weekdays and from 9 a.m. to 1 p.m. EDT on
Saturdays. The number is 1-800-541-3375.
   Cooper said Lyng briefed the president and vice president and
then the Cabinet in separate meetings. He said Lyng showed Reagan a
map that demonstrated the worsening condition of the drought in
many areas of the United States.
   ``The secretary said that in discussions he has had with
congressmen and senators, farm groups and governors, there was
agreement that it is too early for emergency relief measures,'' the
White House spokesman said.
   Cooper said Lyng also reported that the Agriculture Department
and other agencies have taken some steps to help, such as allowing
haying and grazing on conservation reserves.
   The spokesman quoted Reagan as saying after the meeting, ``Our
No. 1 worry right now is the effects of the drought on the farmers
and their families and making certain they receive any help we can
provide.''
</TEXT>
