<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Yankees-Martin-Newspage     06-23 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yankees-Martin-Newspage,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Billy Martin's Fifth Term as Yankee Manager Ends</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Billy Martin was fired as manager of the New
York Yankees for the fifth time Thursday and was replaced by his
predecessor, Lou Piniella.
   Principal owner George Steinbrenner made his 15th managerial
change in as many years just a day after the Yankees' third
straight loss to the Detroit Tigers and three days after the team
fell out of first place in the American League's Eastern Division.
   Martin, a second baseman the great Yankee teams of the 1950s,
was suspended once and fined twice this season for throwing dirt on
umpires. Earlier, his face was battered in a fight in a Texas bar.
   Piniella, who managed the Yankees in 1986 and 1987, was
appointed general manager at the end of last season but resigned on
May 29.
   He joins Martin, Bob Lemon and Gene Michael, who was named
third-base coach on Thursday, on the list of those Steinbrenner has
fired and re-hired as manager.
   Martin was hired as Yankee manager in 1975, led the team to a
World Series title in 1977 and was fired in 1978. He was rehired
and fired during the 1979 season, brought back in 1983, fired the
next year and replaced by Yogi Berra. Berra was fired during the
1985 season, Martin returned, then was fired at the end of the
season.
</TEXT>
