<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Pope 1stLd-Writethru a0690 06-23 0815</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0690,0835</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Begins Visit to Austria Recalling `Cruel Tyranny' of Nazism</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads throughout to UPDATE with private meeting of Waldheim
and pope; pope retires for night; CLARIFIES that pope addressed
Waldheim along with government and church leaders in ceremonial
hall. EDITS to TRIM. No pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto VIE3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II recalled the evils of
Nazism during a meeting Thursday with President Kurt Waldheim, who
has been accused of being involved in war crimes while serving in
Adolf Hitler's army.
   Foreign diplomats did not attend a speech by the pope to church
and government officials including Waldheim, who has been virtually
ostracized internationally because of his wartime past. But
diplomats warmly greeted the pope at a reception afterwards.
   ``In this year of 1988, I should like to particularly recall the
great trials and cruel tyranny which Austria, along with other
nations, had to suffer in the not too distant past,'' John Paul
said in his speech, at the beginning of a five-day visit to
Austria, his second since becoming pope in 1978.
   ``Amongst the many who were persecuted for religious, racial and
political reasons were large numbers of Catholics _ priests,
members of religious orders and lay people,'' the pope said in an
ornate ceremonial hall of the Hofburg Palace.
   About 80 people, including government officials and church
leaders, attended the gathering. The pope delivered his address in
German.
   This year is the 50th anniversary of the ``Anschluss,'' when
Hitler annexed his native country in 1938. The event, coupled with
a war record that continues to dog Waldheim, has inspired
controversy and soul-searching. Waldheim has repeatedly denied
involvement in war crimes.
   In his own greeting, Waldheim thanked the pontiff for receiving
him at the Vatican in June 1987 _ a meeting that drew a bitter
response from Jewish leaders because of questions about the
president's war service.
   The Vatican said at the time that John Paul was receiving the
office, not the man. Vatican spokesman Joaquin Navarro has said of
the pope's trip to Austria: ``This is not a political visit, it is
a pastoral visit. He was invited by the bishops.''
   Waldheim and his family later posed for pictures with the
pontiff at the Hofburg Palace. Then the pope met privately with
Waldheim for about five minutes, but Navarro declined to say what
the two men talked about.
   Waldheim did not attend a reception afterwards where the envoys
greeted the pope, according to a pool report distributed to
journalists. The pope then retired for the night at the Vienna
archbishop's residence.
   Protests coincided with the pope's arrival.
   Earlier Thursday, John Paul said an evening Mass at St.
Stephen's Cathedral. As he was about to start, American Jews
displayed banners at the windows of a hotel across the square from
the cathedral. The banners said ``Nazi Waldheim'' and ``Don't Meet
Waldheim.''
   Police ordered the banners removed.
   Several hours before John Paul arrived, Rabbi Avi Weiss of
Riverdale, N.Y., and five other American Jews demonstrated outside
Waldheim's office.
   ``Do not embrace Waldheim, no!'' Weiss told a small crowd
attracted to the demonstration. The other five members of the group
were dressed in black-and-white striped uniforms similar to those
of concentration camp inmates.
   In New York, Elan Steinberg, executive director of the World
Jewish Congress, issued a statement saying: ``The pope's meeting
with his flock in Austria is not what troubles the Jewish
community. It is the deliberate inclusion of meetings with Kurt
Waldheim on his itinerary.''
   John Paul will make about 20 appearances in Austria, 85 percent
of whose 7.5 million people are Roman Catholic. He visited the
country for three days in 1983.
   Waldheim, smiling and wearing a blue suit, was the first person
to greet the white-robed pontiff as he stepped off the special
Alitalia jetliner at Schwechat Airport.
   The pope mentioned several places he will visit, including
Mauthausen, the Nazi concentration camp where 110,000 prisoners
died.
   ``Let us, when we meet, bring before God not only the great and
burdensome legacy of the past but also the joys and sorrows of the
present,'' the pope said, speaking in German.
   Waldheim also denounced ``intolerance, intransigence and hate
among nations, religions and classes,'' but made no direct
reference to the dispute over his past.
   Most Western leaders shun Waldheim, who was U.N.
secretary-general for 10 years, because of allegations of
complicity in Nazi atrocities. The charges arose during the
election campaign two years ago.
   Waldheim denies wrongdoing but the United States has barred him
from the country, saying it has evidence he was involved in
deporting civilians while serving as a German army officer in the
Balkans during World War II.
   John Paul, on the 38th foreign pilgrimage of his papacy, also
will meet with representatives of Austria's small Jewish community
and address Roman Catholics from neighboring communist countries.
</TEXT>
