<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 2036EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DefenseProbe-BDM     06-23 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Probe-BDM,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Contractor BDM International Says Ford Still Plans
Takeover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Aerospace & Communications Corp. intends
to proceed with plans to take over BDM International Inc.,
according to BDM, the defense contractor whose name has surfaced in
the Pentagon contracting investigation.
   ``Based upon what Ford now knows concerning the government
investigation of defense contractors, Ford plans to proceed with
its tender offer,'' BDM said in a statement Thursday from its
headquarters in McLean, Va., just outside Washington.
   Susan Pearce, a spokeswoman for Ford, would not elaborate on the
BDM statement. BDM spokesman James Hughes did not return a
telephone call.
   The boards of directors of both BDM and Ford Aerospace, a
division of Ford Motor Co., approved the $425 million takeover last
month. Under the tender offer, which expires at midnight Friday,
Ford Aerospace will pay $34.75 per share.
   BDM's name has come up in the Pentagon investigation because
Melvyn Paisley, a former Pentagon official who is under federal
scrutiny, served as a consultant to the company after he left the
Navy in 1987. Paisley's wife, Vicki, also worked at BDM, first as
an employee and then as a consultant.
   The Wall Street Journal reported in Thursday's editions that
government officials are reviewing work performed by Mrs. Paisley
for BDM.
   The Los Angeles Times, quoting sources it did not name, reported
Thursday that Paisley allegedly arranged an elaborate scheme under
which high-level Pentagon officials smuggled classified documents
out of the Pentagon and allowed him to copy them with the aid of
his wife.
   Federal investigators are looking into allegations that defense
contractors and consultants, many of them former members of the
military, bribed Pentagon officials for contracting details that
could be vital in winning contracts worth billions of dollars.
   No one has been charged in the case.
</TEXT>
