<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush-Ads 2ndLd-Writethru a0667 06-23 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Ads, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0667,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Americans for Bush' To Raise $10 Million for Presidential
Campaign</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: LEADS with 4 grafs, Bush campaign says committee
misrepresented self; picks up 2nd graf pvs, bgng: The first</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group calling itself ``Americans for Bush''
said Thursday it will spend $10 million in an effort to elect
George Bush as the next president, including a series of television
commercials.
   But the Bush campaign says organizers of the effort have been
asked to stop using Bush's name in their fundraising.
   ``We feel that this committee has misrepresented itself,'' said
spokeswoman Alixe Glen. ``They're misrepresenting that their group
is an authorized campaign committee, and they're not.''
   She said the Bush campaign was not opposed to independent
efforts to help elect Bush, as long as those groups make it clear
they are not part of the authorized campaign committee.
   The first commercial, shown at preview for reporters, highlights
Bush's career as a Navy pilot, businessman, member of Congress,
ambassador to the United Nations and China and ``as Ronald Reagan's
trusted vice president.''
   ``George Bush will make a great president, but first we have the
tough job of getting him elected,'' retired Adm. Mark H. Hill says
in the commercial which solicits contributions to pay for more
advertising.
   The effort, which is independent of Bush's presidential campaign
and not subject to federal spending limits that apply to the
campaign itself, is being underwritten by the National Security
Political Action Committee.
   Hill told reporters the committee ``supports the initiatives of
the active-duty military'' and that the advertising effort would
seek to portray Bush as the candidate with the best record on
supporting the military.
   Floyd Brown, a spokesman for the organization, said $330,000 was
being spent to buy time for the first commercial on several cable
networks, including Cable News Network, and on stations in regional
markets. It will be shown starting next week, he said.
   Elizabeth Fediay, chairman of Americans for Bush, said the
commercial ``is only the beginning of the very active role that
National Security PAC hopes to have through the election, not only
to have an impact in helping to elect George Bush but also on a
number of senatorial races and some targeted congressional races.''
</TEXT>
