<DOCNO> AP880623-0192 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 2036EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DefenseProbe-McDonnell     06-23 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Probe-McDonnell,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>McDonnell Douglas Wins $960 Million Pentagon Contract for F-A-18
Jets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The McDonnell Douglas Corp., one of several
contractors under scrutiny in a defense fraud investigation,
received a $963.2 million contract Thursday for F-A-18 jet fighters.
   The contract, awarded by the Navy, calls for construction of 84
of the sophisticated jets _ the full number authorized for purchase
in fiscal 1988 by Congress.
   The Navy wants to buy another 72 of the twin-engine jets in
fiscal 1989.
   McDonnell Douglas is the prime contractor for the plane, which
is nicknamed the Hornet. The Northrop Corp., another defense
contractor under scrutiny, is a major subcontractor.
   Both McDonnell Douglas and Northrop were named in search
warrants executed last week by FBI agents investigating what has
been described as a massive fraud and bribery scheme. McDonnell
Douglas has been identified as a client of Melvyn R. Paisley, a
former assistant Navy secretary and now a defense consultant
believed to be one target of the investigation.
   The F-A-18 is the Navy's newest carrier-based fighter. It is
capable of being used either as an air-to-air fighter or as an
air-to-ground attack jet. FBI agents made a point of searching
McDonnell Douglas offices for documents involving potential sales
of the plane to U.S. allies.
