<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FederalAbortions     06-23 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Federal Abortions,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Approves Federally Funded Abortions for Rape, Incest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Appropriations Committee voted
Thursday to give victims of rape or incest the right to federally
funded abortions.
   The panel voted 15-14 to defeat a motion to delete the
provision, which had been added earlier this week by a subcommittee
to the fiscal 1989 spending bill for the departments of health and
human services, labor and education.
   The Office of Management and Budget, in a letter to committee
members, said presidential advisers would recommend a veto of the
$139 billion bill if it includes the abortion provision.
   The sponsor of the motion, Sen. Lowell Weicker, R-Conn., argued
before the committee that ``denying Medicaid funds to poor women
for what is legal in this country makes no sense.''
   The annual spending bill usually contains a provision saying
abortions can only be paid for under the federal-state Medicaid
program when the woman's life would be endangered by carrying the
fetus to term.
   The version approved by the committee would return the law to
its status before 1980. The same provision was added in 1986 in
committee, but removed on the Senate floor.
   The 1989 spending bill is expected to reach the Senate floor
next month.
   OMB called the new abortion provision a Medicaid expansion that
``diverges from longstanding policy on this issue.''
   Weicker called the OMB letter ``a waste of power'' that diverts
attention from the needs of the nation into ``narrow philosophical
issues.''
</TEXT>
