<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Canada-Soviets 1stLd-Writethru a0712 06-23 0578</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Soviets, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0712,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Canada Expels Two More Soviet Envoys In Spy Squabble</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf `The government...' with 2 grafs to ADD that
Roublev given until Monday to leave. PICKS up 5th graf pvs bgng,
`The government also ....' ADDS 5 grafs with detail, background.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two more Soviet envoys were expelled or barred
from Canada on Thursday in a spy squabble, and a Soviet Embassy
spokesman said his side would take further retaliation.
   The latest action by Canada brings to 19 the number of Soviets
expelled or barred from returning to the country since Tuesday. The
Soviets have expelled or barred five Canadians.
   The Soviets were accused of seeking military and industrial
secrets and trying to infiltrate Canada's intelligence agencies.
   Canada's External Affairs Department said Col. Grigori
Stepanovich Roublev, a top-ranking military attache at the Soviet
Embassy in Ottawa, was expelled Thursday and given until Monday to
leave.
   A former second secretary at the embassy, Sergei Mikhailovich
Kashtanov, was told he can never return to Canada.
   The government also announced it will cut by three the total
number of Soviet diplomats assigned to Canada.
   The reduction in accredited Soviet diplomats brings to 60 the
official Soviet diplomatic complement in Canada.
   Within minutes of the orders issued Thursday, spokesman
Vyacheslav Bogdanov at the Soviet Embassy said, ``There is no doubt
whatsoever that there will be retaliation'' by Moscow.
   The most serious rift in Canadian-Soviet relations in a decade
began Tuesday when Prime Minister Brian Mulroney's government said
eight Soviet diplomats and officials had been expelled and nine
others formerly posted in Canada would not be allowed to return.
   Moscow retaliated Wednesday by expelling two Canadian diplomats
and barring re-entry for three others, alleging espionage.
   A statement Thursday from Canadian Foreign Minister Joe Clark
said the espionage allegations against the Canadian diplomats in
Moscow are ``totally without justification.'' It said the latest
expulsions follow ``Soviet espionage activities in Canada which
have obliged the Canadian government to expel the Soviet
officials.''
   The statement gave no details of the alleged spying by Roublev
and Kashtanov, but Clark's press secretary Paul Frazer told The
Associated Press they were involved in ``unacceptable activities,''
the usual euphemism for spying.
   Frazer said Roublev has been in Canada since May 1985, while
Kashtanov served in Canada from February 1981 to August 1985.
   Asked why they had not been expelled earlier, Frazer said: ``We
think our response is appropriate in the circumstances.''
   He said the Soviet ambassador was called in Thursday and
informed of the latest action. He was also told that Canada was
willing to ``put the matter behind us'' if Moscow did likewise,
Frazer said.
   The last wave of mass expulsions was in 1978 when 13 Soviet
diplomats were expelled for trying to recruit a Royal Canadian
Mounted Police intelligence officer as a double agent.
   The Canadian Broadcasting Corp. said the latest Soviet spy ring
tried to infiltrate a U.S.-owned military contractor in Montreal,
Paramax Electronics, which has access to highly classified American
naval technology.
   Paramax, a subsidiary of Detroit-based Unisys Corp., is building
the combat systems for six new Canadian frigates and the radar,
sonar and communications systems for six other frigates.
   A Soviet translator at the International Civil Aviation
Organization in Montreal, Yuri Smurov, provided ``useful
information'' leading to the breakup of the spy ring, Clark said
Wednesday.
   Smurov has now defected and asked for asylum for himself, his
wife and daughter Christina, a fifth grade pupil.
</TEXT>
