<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Brezhnev     06-23 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Brezhnev,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Another Blow to Brezhnev: Mansion Turned into Wedding Palace</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The late Leonid I. Brezhnev's once-might image
fell a little farther Thursday. A white marble mansion built for
brief visit he paid to Baku will be turned into a wedding palace.
   Azerbaijan's Communist party built the mansion, which overlooks
the Caspian Sea, for the Soviet leader so he would have an
appropriate place to stay during a visit to the southern republic's
capital in 1982.
   He stayed only two days and the building has been unoccupied
since, according to reports by state television and the official
news agency Tass.
   ``This beautiful white marble building is well known to all Baku
residents, but hardly any one of them can boast of being in it even
once,'' a television correspondent said on Vremya, the evening news
program.
   He said the Azerbaijan party Central Committee acted under the
principle of ``social fairness'' in deciding to convert the mansion.
   ``Soon, Mendelssohn's march will ring out here for thousands of
newlyweds,'' the correspondent said as images of crystal
chandeliers flashed across the screen in shots of the mansion's
interior.
   In January, Soviet authorities stripped a city, town squares and
a Moscow neighborhood of Brezhnev's name.
   The two-story mansion, surrounded by a high concrete wall, was
built in the days when Geidar A. Aliev, a close Brezhnev associate,
was party chief in Azerbaijan. Aliev was retired from the ruling
Politburo at the age of 64 on Oct. 21, 1987, ostensibly for health
reasons but under a cloud of poor performances of industries he was
responsible for.
   The man who replaced Aliev as Azerbaijani party chief, Kyamran
Bagirov, was fired May 21, apparently for mishandling a territorial
and ethnic dispute with the neighboring republic of Armenia.
   Bagirov's leadership also received an implied blow on Thursday.
The television report said a complex of buildings where Azerbaijani
leaders had lived will be turned into a children's health center.
The report did not specifically mention Bagirov.
   The appropriation of lavish private mansions has a long
tradition here. When the Bolsheviks seized power in 1917, they
converted many mansions of Russia's aristocrats and palaces of the
Czars for public use.
   Under Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, Brezhnev's name has
become synonymous with what Soviet officials call the ``period of
stagnation,'' a time when the economy fell into a slump. Brezhnev,
who ruled from 1964 until his death in 1982, has been blamed for
fostering complacency and cronyism.
</TEXT>
