<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua-Peace     06-23 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Peace,0449</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mining Town Dreads Renewed Fighting As End of Truce Nears</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of this small mining
town dread the end of a truce that gave them nearly three months of
relative peace from fighting between U.S.-backed rebels and leftist
Sandinista government troops.
   Both sides have sympathizers here, but everyone ``fears the
return of the fighters,'' said Maria Toledo, owner of a small food
shop.
   Santo Domingo nestles between two hills in the central Chontales
province, a region which has seen intense fighting during the
6{-year-old war between the rebels, known as Contras, and the
Sandinistas.
   Military sources say the violence has steadily diminished since
a cease-fire began March 23.
   The town's only ambulance, once busy transporting war wounded,
now ferries sick children to the local health center. Residents
like Eudoro Castro, 43, are now left more or less in peace.
   Castro explained how he's gotten by in a war that has killed
26,500 people, wounded another 25,000 and nearly destroyed the
Nicaraguan economy.
   ``The Contras come along and demand a cow. I give it to them,''
Castro said. ``The Sandinistas come by, I give them one too. I'm
happy they are leaving me in peace now to work.''
   Military sources admit there have been some abuses by Sandinista
soldiers, abuses that have helped the Contras build a strong base
of popular support in the region.
   The fatigue-clad soldiers are still here, but now they doze on
the shaded sidewalks instead of preparing for another round of
combat.
   This region is also headquarters for a Contra force of about
2,000 rebels.
   Military sources who asked not to be identified said the army
has been in contact with various rebel factions during the
cease-fire, attempting to persuade them to lay down their arms. The
army has had little success, the sources said.
   The truce is due to expire at the end of June.
   The last round of talks between the Contras and Sandinistas fell
apart in Managua on June 9 and no new talks have been scheduled.
The government has proposed another round in the capital starting
June 26, but the rebels have not responded to the offer.
   Meanwhile, the people of Santo Domingo wait, dreading renewed
hostilities.
   ``We want to live in peace,'' said Felix Perez Garay, a
53-year-old food vendor who lost a son and three grandchildren, all
Sandinista soldiers, in the war.
   ``We want to forget our hatred and have a new life,'' Garay
said. Pointing to the bullet-shattered windows of the church, he
said: ``The war leaves only this.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
