<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Drought-RainDance     06-23 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Rain Dance,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>After Ceremony, Rainfall Arrives 40 Minutes Ahead of Schedule</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Drought-Heat, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLYDE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The rain came _ not much, but it came _ 40
minutes ahead of schedule after a Sioux Indian medicine man gave
prayers and offerings for rain in a traditional ceremony.
   Florist Cliff Doebel said he brought Leonard Crow Dog here from
South Dakota, at a cost of $2,000, last weekend to make people
aware of the drought and warn them that they may not be able to
rely on Ohio's agriculture this year.
   After performing his ceremony, Crow Dog said the rain should
arrive Thursday. It began falling at 11:20 p.m. Wednesday.
   The National Weather Service does not have an official rainfall
monitor in Clyde, but precipitation in nearby northwest Ohio
communities late Wednesday and early Thursday ranged from 0.22 inch
in Fremont to 0.08 inch in Milan, forecaster Matthew Peroutka said.
   ``It's not enough, and the situation is still here and still
severe,'' said Doebel. ``But I think it was enough to help some of
the corn out.''
   ``I'm not one to know those answers (of why it rained),'' he
said. ``All I know is you flip a coin and sometimes it comes up
heads.''
   Crow Dog, 45, arrived by plane Saturday and spent the night in a
tepee erected in a field near the Doebel greenhouse. He performed a
traditional ceremony, using prayers and offerings to summon the
``four winds of the earth'' to bring rain.
   Crow Dog left Ohio early in the week, saying his work was done,
Doebel said.
</TEXT>
