<DOCNO> AP880623-0205 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 2203EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FCC-Renewals     06-23 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FCC-Renewals,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FCC Will Consider Measures to Curb Abuses in License Renewal
Process</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission agreed
Thursday to consider measures designed to curb abuses in a
broadcast license renewal process that allows ``extortion and sham
applications'' by license challengers seeking profitable
settlements.
   The FCC commissioners voted 3-0 to consider changes in the
system by which radio and television station owners renew their
licenses and defend themselves against charges by competing
companies that apply for the license to run the station.
   The license-challenge process is aimed at bringing to the
commission legitimate issues related to a station owner's
qualifications.
   But commissioners said they were concerned that some license
challengers may have no interest in running a broadcast station and
may file competing applications or petition the agency to deny an
incumbent's license only so they can profit from a financial
settlement.
   FCC Chairman Dennis R. Patrick said the commission will ``not
... tolerate extortion or sham applications.''
   The FCC said it would consider whether to limit the amount of
money an incumbent licensee could pay a challenger to withdraw a
competing application or to prohibit such payments altogether.
   The agency also will consider requiring competing applicants to
identify financial contributions from those backing the application.
   The FCC also will consider changes in its policy of granting
stations ``renewal expectancy'' to give the industry more
stability. Such status is currently awarded based on a station's
past service to its community.
   Patrick said he wanted to develop a policy with the least amount
of second-guessing of a station's programming decisions.
</TEXT>
