<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Heat; Scattered Storms in Upper Mississippi Valley, Northeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A cool front brought some relief from the heat Thursday in parts
of the Northeast and mid-Atlantic states, but most of the nation's
midsection continued to swelter and suffer.
   Afternoon readings were already in the mid-90s to around 100
degrees from the central high Plains through the lower Missouri
Valley into the Tennessee Valley and mid-Atlantic states.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered Thursday afternoon
across the upper Mississippi Valley, the strongest one moving
across parts of southeastern South Dakota and northeastern Nebraska.
   Thunderstorms were also scattered along a Canadian cold front
that was sagging south across the northern mid-Atlantic region.
   Showers and thunderstorms, accompanied by gusty winds and heavy
rain, were widespread along the Gulf of Mexico coast into Florida.
There were also isolated storms across the deserts of Southern
California.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 53
degrees at Nashua, N.H., to 109 at Phoenix and Glendale, Ariz. The
early morning low for the nation was 40 at Truckee, Calif.
   The national forecast for Friday called for continued sunny and
hot weather across much of the nation. Scattered showers and
thunderstorms were predicted across the Great Lakes into parts of
Iowa; from southern Texas across the Gulf Coast into the southern
Atlantic Coast and much of Florida; and in parts of the desert
Southwest and Great Basin.
   Highs will be in the 70s along the California coast and from
Upper Michigan through much of New England; 80s across the Pacific
Northwest and from the Great Lakes into the mid-Atlantic states;
between 100 and 105 across the central Plains; above 105 in the
Southern California valleys and the desert Southwest; and in the
90s across most of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
