<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PuertoRico-Cocaine     06-23 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Puerto Rico-Cocaine,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Biggest Cocaine Shipment In Island History Found On Plane, Police
Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY HELEN J. SIMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A twin-engine plane that skidded to
a stop on its nose in an abandoned airfield Thursday was carrying
half a ton of cocaine, the largest shipment ever seized on the
island, police said.
   Six people were in custody for questioning and helicopters were
still combing the area late Thursday for another who escaped,
police spokesman Tony Santiago said. No charges have been filed.
   Police said the cocaine shipment was the largest ever
intercepted on its way to Puerto Rico. They estimated its street
value at $720 million.
   ``Direct to Puerto Rico, this is the largest to date,'' Santiago
said. Last August more than 2,000 pounds of cocaine were found in
the steel beams of more than 20 shipping containers bound for
Florida.
   The plane arrived in San Sebastian, 80 miles west of San Juan,
around 2 a.m. and scraped to a stop on its nose as it tried to land
on a runway formerly operated by the government, police said.
   Occupants of a pickup truck waiting nearby raced over, unloaded
seven dufflebags with about 400 pounds of the drug and took off in
a hail of gunfire when federal and local drug agents arrived at the
scene.
   After a chase though the darkness the truck fell into a ditch
and its occupants escaped, police said.
   About 675 pounds of cocaine was found in the plane, wrapped in
individual packages of about 2 pounds each, police said. They
described the plane as an ``expensive'' Fairchild with a six- or
seven-seat capacity.
   Five men and a woman were later picked up nearby. At least four
of them were believed to be local residents, Santiago said.
   Several weapons, including an Uzi machine gun with loaded
magazines, a Magnum 357 pistol with extra shells and an AR-15 rifle
were also seized, along with several portable radios.
   Officials said they did not know where the plane came from, but
that most aircraft intercepted in the area with drugs aboard come
from Colombia.
</TEXT>
