<2ND_LINE>AM-Letterman Return,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Letterman Back on Air Tuesday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Letterman will go back on the air next
Tuesday, with or without his writers but with their blessing in any
event, head writer Steve O'Donnell said Thursday.
   O'Donnell said the writers were hoping that the striking Writers
Guild of America would grant a waiver for the ``Late Night'' show
to resume next week with its writers, but were still awaiting word.
   ``That means we will be by his side, but if not, he'll go back
on the air just the same, no hard feelings,'' said O'Donnell.
``We've been having meetings all week and we've decided the best
thing is to get the show on the air.''
   As of Thursday night, NBC would not confirm that Letterman was
going back on the air.
   Johnny Carson went back on the air last month without his
writers. He is writing his own monologues.
   ``The Tonight Show Starring Johnny Carson'' and ``Late Night''
went into reruns when the writers went on strike four months ago.
   Letterman, a member of the guild, would not be violating the
strike by going on the air in his capacity as a performer.
O'Donnell said if the writers do not get a waiver and Letterman is
on his own, he will make ``casual remarks'' at the beginning of the
show, then interview guests.
   O'Donnell said Letterman attended Wednesday night's meeting of
the Writers Guild of America East, where a vote was taken on the
latest contract offer by the producers.
   The vote was not yet final Thursday night, but supporters of the
contract conceded they did not have enough votes to end the strike.
   Letterman's show had previously sought an independent contract
with the guild, but that plan was scrapped because the show is a
production of NBC.
</TEXT>
