<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Burma Bjt   06-23 0688</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma, Bjt,0707</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Surround Students at Buddhist Shrine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police formed a tight ring Thursday around
the gold-encrusted Shwedagon Pagoda, this Buddhist nation's holiest
shrine, where student protesters set up a ``strike center.''
   Students in green sarongs, the uniform of high school students,
tried unsuccessfully to enlist residents of Rangoon in a march to
the hilltop pagoda. The march did not take place.
   Demostrations also were reported in Pegu, about 50 miles north
on the Rangoon-Mandalay railroad. Classes were suspended at the
main schools in Mandalay, the nation's second-largest city, but no
disturbances were reported.
   Rangoon spent its third night under a 6 p.m.-6 a.m. curfew and a
ban on public meetings, which were imposed after street violence in
which nine people were killed by official count.
   University students have led three major rounds of protest since
October, the first since 1974 against the 26-year-old regime of
Gen. Ne Win, whose economic policies and wars on ethnic minorities
have impoverished this Southeast Asian country.
   Hundreds of people have been arrested and Western diplomats say
100 may have died in street violence, most in rioting March 18 and
since.
   Witnesses said police closed the pagoda to the public at 5 a.m.
and surrounded the grounds, on which protesters established their
``strike center'' Wednesday.
   Students began arriving at the shrine Wednesday morning after
authorities shut down the Rangoon Institute of Technology. Some of
the last worshipers to leave said about 500 students were there,
but the figure could not be confirmed.
   No information was available on the student demands or what was
happening inside.
   Shwedagon Pagoda sits on a hill in Rangoon's northern suburbs.
Its gilded central stupa, or tower, soars 325 feet above a temple
base adorned with more than five tons of gold.
   Burmese are almost fanatically devoted to the shrine, which
legend says was founded 2,500 years ago. It has survived wars,
earthquakes and the British occupation, during which it was a
center for anti-colonial nationalists.
   Residents reached by telephone in Mandalay, about 380 miles
north of Rangoon, said classes were suspended at Mandalay
University, the Medical College and the Government Technical
Institute. The action appeared to be precautionary, since no
trouble was reported.
   Similar reports from Pegu said an overnight curfew was imposed
Wednesday after students and other rioters destroyed or heavily
damaged government buildings, vehicles and cooperative stores. Pegu
was the seat of several ancient kingdoms.
   Western analysts say restrictions on individual freedoms and
poor economic conditions are spurring the protest.
   Although Burma is rich in resources and has an educated
populace, its per capita annual income of less than $200 puts it
among the poorest nations. Ne Win's ``Burmese Way to Socialism''
mixes military control, socialism and few dealings with the outside
world.
   Most merchants in Rangoon's sprawling market districts closed
their shops at noon Thursday for fear of looting if violence
resumed. Some government employees went home before normal closing
hours.
   Attendance was minimal at high schools and the Education
Institute, the only center of higher learning still open in
Rangoon. Teachers were told to continue classes regardless of the
attendance level.
   No major incidents have been reported since the curfew took
effect Tuesday. A few street vendors and drivers of taxis and
rickshaws have been arrested for going out before 6 a.m., but were
reported freed after warnings.
   The latest trouble began Tuesday when 5,000 students and other
protesters in Rangoon fought police with stones.
   Students at several institutions demonstrated peacefully last
week for legalization of student unions and release of detained
comradesd. The government closed the school and the government
responded with violence.
   Trouble began last October when the government declared much of
the currency in circulation to be invalid and did not offer
compensation. On March 18, after several days of unrest, police and
soldiers quickly crushed a rampage in downtown Rangoon by students
and other protesters.
   A government panel announced only two deaths and said 625 people
were arrested, but diplomatic sources told reporters in Bangkok,
Thailand, as many as 100 people have been killed since October.
Many of those arrested have been released.
</TEXT>
