<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ChemicalFire     06-23 0583</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chemical Fire,0599</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Georgia Officials On Way to Look into Massachusetts Chemical Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal agency is investigating an
arson fire at a Georgia warehouse owned by the same company whose
Massachusetts plant was ravaged by fire over the weekend, routing
25,000 people from their homes.
   While the federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms was
looking into the Georgia warehouse fire Thursday, Georgia
investigators were on their way to Springfield to take a look at
the burned-out plant, Springfield fire department spokesman Giorgio
Placanico said.
   ``We'll probably go down there, too,'' Placanico said.
   Firefighters in protective suits continued carting barrels of
chloride out of the remains of the 18th-century mill Thursday as
ambulances stood by in case pockets of fumes overwhelmed the
workers.
   The Springfield plant burned for four days, spewing a
three-mile-long gas cloud across the city of 170,000 and forced
thousands out of the neighborhood before firefighters controlled
the last of several fires Monday.
   The first fire apparently was sparked by rainwater that fell
through a window of the Advanced Laboratories Inc. plant and mixed
with chloride tablets that the plant makes for swimming pools,
causing a violent reaction. The later fires are under investigation.
   A June 10 fire at a Weatherking South Inc. warehouse in
Doraville, Ga., owned by the same company, also appears to be
accidental, said Chuck Johnson, a spokesman for the DeKalb County
public safety department.
   But the second fire Tuesday in Georgia was clearly the work of
an arsonist, he said. ``There was no other way that fire could have
started,'' he said in a telephone interview.
   The arson fire destroyed the 30,000-foot swimming pool supply
warehouse, which also housed offices, Johnson said.
   ``The unusual number of fires here and up there have forced us
to make the connection,'' Johnson told the Union-News of
Springfield. ``We think they are associated and so we've called in
the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms to help us.''
   An agent with the bureau said investigators are working only on
the Georgia fires and have not been called in to help with the
Springfield investigation, which is being handled by the city arson
squad.
   But he added that the federal investigators are keeping watch on
what the Springfield fire officials turn up.
   ``Nobody can say yet whether these fires were arson or
accidental,'' said agent Terence McArdle. ``But we are keeping an
eye on it. When two company plants have chemical fires, we are
interested.''
   No one was hurt in the Georgia fires, which released a small
amount of chlorine gas but forced no evacuations.
   An estimated 275 people have gone to Springfield-area hospitals
for treatment since the first fire ignited Friday, but none of the
injuries has been reported to be serious.
   Advanced Laboratories and Weatherking South are both wholly
owned subsidiaries of Aquafab Industries Inc. of New York, a pool
supply firm owned by John P. Perreira of East Greenwich, R.I., and
Boca Raton, Fla., and Robert M. Petrin of Coventry, R.I., according
to records filed with secretaries of state in Massachusetts and
Georgia.
   The Massachusetts Department of Environmental Quality
Engineering has released records showing that since April 1986,
state officials have investigated a series of incidents at the
plant, including charges that the firm was illegally dumping
chlorine chemicals in a nearby pond.
   An attorney for the company has said the owners will have no
comment until the damage from the fire has been assessed.
</TEXT>
