<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 2027EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Drought-Governors     06-23 0628</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Governors,0649</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governors Of Parched States Hear Agriculture Secretary</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Drought-Heat, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Agriculture Secretary Richard Lyng said
Thursday federal programs will provide relief for drought-stricken
farmers, but governors meeting in emergency session questioned
whether those methods were adequate.
   During a brief appearance before the 10 governors who gathered
for the day-long conference, Lyng promised the federal government
``will do what is needed to minimize the severity of the damage.''
   But the agriculture secretary also reminded the gathering that
there were several existing aid programs already in place, and he
stressed repeatedly that the extent of the damage from the drought
was yet to be determined.
   But Gov. George Sinner of North Dakota, speaking at a closing
news conference, said farmers in several states already had lost
much of their cash crops and others have sold off entire livestock
herds for lack of feed grain.
   ``Where I think he (Lyng) is wrong is in the wheat area,'' said
Sinner. ``That damage is done and it is very, very severe. In the
livestock feed area, that damage is done and it's going to grow.''
   Sinner also said government programs must be made flexible
enough to ensure that farmers hurt by the current drought aren't
disqualified from participating in crop-insurance and disaster-loan
program because of ``technicalities.''
   ``I'm afraid we're going to lose some farmers,'' he said, ``and
we've lost enough already in my state.''
   That message echoed throughout the day.
   ``Welcome to the heart of the droughtland,'' Illinois Gov. James
Thompson said in opening the conference. ``We used to be known as
the heart of the heartland. Now we are both.''
   In his speech, Lyng noted that 1,200 counties in 30 states
already have been granted permission for grazing livestock or
making hay on government-rented land normally set aside for
conservation or crop-reduction plans.
   He also pointed out that task forces already have been set up
within the administration and Congress to study the consequences of
the drought. The federal government's crop-insurance and
disaster-loan programs could serve large number of farmers once the
extent of the damage from the drought becomes clear, he said.
   ``The situation is still fluid. ... We'll need a little bit of
time to learn what the losses are,'' he said.
   Before he left the conference, Lyng said he would meet with
Reagan on Friday morning to update him on the drought situation.
   But several governors suggested the situation in their states
already demands a more-specific response from the federal goverment
_ even if they had different ideas on what the response should be.
   Illinois' Thompson said the barge traffic along the Mississippi
River so crucial to agricultural states like Illinois was paralyzed
because of low water levels, and proposed he U.S. Army Corps of
Engineers seek permission to divert water from Lake Michigan to
solve the problem.
   That proposal, however, was disputed by Wisconsin Gov. Tommy
Thompson.
   ``It might turn out to be more disastrous over the long term
than the immediate salvation it provides,'' said the Wisconsin
governor.
   ``It's an idea we should explore. I'm just saying we should not
go quickly, though.''
   Tommy Thompson said restoring last year's 50-cent price cut on
federal dairy support programs and blocking a second cut next
January ``would do more for Wisconsin farmers than anything but
rain.''
   Given the differing needs of the states represented, Thompson
was asked how they would reach agreement on priorities.
   ``That's difficult,'' he said, ``any time you deal with
agricultural issues, everybody has a different agenda. ... But this
issue is crucial enough for us to find a common ground.''
   Attending the day-long meeting, besides Sinner and both
Thompsons, were the governors of Minnesota, Montana, South Dakota,
Mississippi, Ohio, Kansas and Nebaska.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880623-0212 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 2038EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a TwoCaliforniaCompaniesPushingSeedlessProducontheSenatefloor.
    06-23 0495</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>Two California Companies Pushing Seedless Product</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By JOE BIGHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRESNO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some watermelons no longer rate as seedy
characters.
   Two California companies, Sun World and Petoseed Co., are
marketing seedless watermelons, which are showing up in
supermarkets across the nation for the first time.
   Sun World has launched a national marketing effort for its
seedless watermelons, while Petoseed has provided several growers
with seeds and is promoting hybrid seedless varieties the company
developed.
   The need to spit out the seeds to the juicy fruit has long been
the pits, but the idea of ending such expectorating has been around
a while, too.
   ``The process by which it is produced was developed in the late
1930s,'' said David Marguleas, Sun World's merchandising manager.
   Seedless watermelons didn't catch on then because they were
``very difficult to grow, very expensive to farm, and production of
seed for seedless watermelons was produced on a very limited
basis,'' he added.
   Dr. O.J. Eigsti continued work on developing seedless
watermelons in Oklahoma. He had no commercial success until recent
years when his American Seedless Corp. formed a joint venture to
have Sun World promote and distribute them.
   Petoseed began a breeding program in 1976 to develop seedless
watermelons for sale in Japan, said Jim McConnell, the company's
product marketing coordinator. The Japanese have eaten seedless
watermelons produced by their own farmers for more than two
decades, he noted.
   Petoseed has developed three seedless varieties, which have been
planted on about 600 acres this year.
   Sun World, which markets about 75 California-grown fruits and
vegetables, test-marketed seedless watermelons grown on 180 acres
last year, then expanded production to 2,000 acres this season,
Marguleas said.
   Regular watermelons with seeds were grown on more than 15,000
acres of California farm land in 1986, the last year for which
state statistics have been compiled. The crop that year totaled
186,000 tons valued at $27.7 million.
   Sun World seedless watermelons will be available in most major
markets during the summer, said Marguleas, who was in New York City
last week promoting the product to food editors.
   ``Not only gone are those annoying black seeds, consumers also
found the flavor sweeter and crunchier than the average
watermelon,'' Marguleas said.
   Barbara Buck of the Western Growers Association said Sun World
seedless watermelons will carry ``a sticker on the side that says
they are seedless with a disclaimer that says they may contain an
occasional seed.''
   Consumers will find a couple of other things different in
comparing seedless varieties with regular watermelons.
   Both Marguleas and McConnell said seedless watermelons could
cost two or three times as much as seeded watermelons, which now
range from 9 to 19 cents a pound.
   McConnell said the difficulty in growing seedless watermelons
and the extra cost will limit their popularity to about 15 percent
of the market.
   ``I don't see it as taking over the watermelon market,'' he
said. ``I see it as a specialty item.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880623-0213 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 2041EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Rabin     06-23 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Rabin,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rabin Leaves For Week-Long Visit To United States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin left
Thursday for a week-long visit to the United States during which he
said he would present American officials with plans for the future
of the Israeli-occupied lands.
   Rabin said he would meet with President Reagan and other top
U.S. officials but described his trip as a ``regular visit.''
Israeli officials did not disclose Rabin's itinerary for security
reasons.
   ``I will take an opportunity before the U.S. elections to thank
a sympathetic, supportive administration, and particularly
President Reagan who has done so much for Israel's security,''
Rabin said before departing from Tel Aviv's Ben Gurion airport.
   The defense minister said he planned to discuss with U.S.
officials the Middle East situation and the Arab uprising in the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, which has claimed the lives of
211 Palestinians and four Israelis since it began last Dec. 8.
   ``I'm bringing them some plans for the future,'' Rabin said
without elaborating.
   Rabin's visit comes amidst U.S. criticism of Israeli policies in
the occupied territories. The latest criticism came Thursday, when
U.S. Ambassador Thomas Pickering accused Israel of violating
Palestinian human rights.
   Speaking at Bar Ilan University near Tel Aviv, Pickering called
on Israel to stop deportations, administrative detentions, house
demolitions and other measures of what he termed collective
punishment.
   Israel has deported 21 Palestinians since the uprising began. As
of June 9, at least 2,500 Palestinians have been served with
administrative detention orders, a measure allowing the army to
hold a suspect in jail for a period of up to six months without
trial.
   In apparent response to Pickering's criticism, Rabin revealed
plans to release some Palestinian detainees. He said between 50 and
80 prisoners are beingh released every day.
   ``If a village or a family have shown good behavior, we are
going to release some detainees from the area,'' Rabin said. ``We
want to use the carrot as well, not only the stick.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
