<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SouthAfrica-Blast     06-23 0202</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa-Blast,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pregnant Woman Hurt By Bomb Loses One Twin In Emergency Delivery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman pregnant with twins
underwent an emergency Caesarian section Thursday after being
injured in a bomb blast. One of the babies died and the other was
in critical condition, officials said.
   The 20-year-old mother, Michelle Ebrahim, was reported in
serious condition at Johannesburg Hospital. The babies were
delivered seven weeks prematurely.
   Mrs. Ebrahim, her husband, and their 2-year-old daughter were
among 10 people injured Wednesday when a limpet mine exploded at a
video game arcade in downtown Johannesburg.
   There have been more than 20 bombings in South Africa this year,
killing eight people and injuring 59.
   The government has blamed the attacks on the outlawed African
National Congress guerrilla movement. The ANC, which is fighting
the government because of its policy of apartheid, has not claimed
responsibility for specific attacks in recent months but has said
it seeks to intensify its guerrilla operations.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which South Africa's 26 million blacks have no vote in
national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and
maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
