<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GorillaDies     06-23 0156</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gorilla Dies,0160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Popular Lincoln Park Zoo Gorilla Dies at 24</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Otto the gorilla, a top attraction at Lincoln
Park Zoo, died Thursday of an unknown cause. He was 24.
   Most gorillas in captivity live well into their 30s, said Carol
Leifer, a zoo spokeswoman. ``He could have lived longer,'' she
said, ``and we had certainly hoped that he would. He was in no way
an elderly creature.''
   His body was found by a zookeeper in an area out of public view.
   Lester Fisher, director of the zoo, said the cause of death
would not be certain until an autopsy, but a heart attack or stroke
were possible.
   ``His many thousands of friends will be as saddened as I am by
Otto's death,'' Fisher said.
   More than 100,000 people saw Otto since he first came to the zoo
in the mid-1960s, Ms. Leifer said. He sired 11 offspring and had
three grandchildren.
</TEXT>
