<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Politics     06-23 0169</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Politics,0175</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rocard Renamed Prime Minister</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Francois Mitterrand reappointed Socialist
Premier Michel Rocard on Thursday and asked him to form a new
Cabinet.
   Mitterrand put off renaming Rocard, who resigned earlier this
month, so Rocard could vote Thursday for the Socialist candidate
for president of the National Assembly, Laurent Fabius.
   Fabius defeated the incumbent, Jacques Chaban-Delmas of the
neo-Gaullist Rally for the Republic party, by 301-268. Eight
members of the 577-seat body either were absent or abstained.
   Rocard, 57, said Wednesday he would name a new government ``as
soon as possible'' but ``without haste,'' and political sources
said it could take place early next week.
   Rocard and the other members of the Cabinet formally resigned
two days after assembly elections June 12 in which neither the
Socialists nor the conservative coalition won a majority.
   Some centrist politicians have asked Mitterrand to form a
coalition government, but political analysts expected the new
Cabinet to resemble the previous one, largely made up of well-known
Socialist figures.
</TEXT>
