<DOCNO> AP880623-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 2305EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Cambodia     06-23 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Cambodia,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Denies Reports of Asylum for Pol Pot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Foreign Ministry on Thursday denied reports
out of Washington that China agreed to help solve the Cambodian
conflict by offering asylum to Khmer Rouge leader Pol Pot.
   Ministry spokesman Li Zhaoxing, at a weekly briefing, said a
Washington Post article last week saying China would give refuge to
Pol Pot was ``highly irresponsible. ... Such a report is absolutely
groundless.''
   Li also denied China is ready to accept a Cambodian government
without the Khmer Rouge, the communist faction it backs with arms
and supplies.
   ``We favor a four-party coalition of Kampuchea (Cambodia) under
the leadership of Prince (Norodom) Sihanouk. We are not in favor of
any single party taking power nor are we in favor of exclusion of
any other party,'' Li said.
   U.S. State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said Monday
that China signaled in private its backing for a Cambodian
government without the Khmer Rouge, which launched a reign of
terror during its 1975-78 rule, during which more than a million
people died.
   China and members of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
support a three-party resistance coalition led by Sihanouk and
including the Khmer Rouge.
   The resistance is calling for the withdrawal of Vietnamese
troops that have occupied Cambodia since late 1978 and the forming
of a four-party government including the Vietnam-backed faction
holding the capital of Phnom Penh.
   Little is known of the current activities of Pol Pot, the Khmer
Rouge leader during the 1975-78 bloodbath, but both ASEAN and
Vietnam have expressed concern that the Khmer Rouge might regain
power after Vietnam withdraws and Pol Pot and other fanatic
leftists might re-emerge.
   Asked if China supports Indonesia's plans to host informal
``cocktail party'' talks in Jakarta next month that will for the
first time bring together the rival factions in Cambodia, Li said,
``it is worth giving it a try.''
   He said China supports all efforts by ASEAN countries for a
``fair and reasonable settlement'' to the Cambodian question,
adding that China believes the rapid withdrawal of all Vietnamese
troops is the key to any settlement.
   He criticized Vietnam's statements that it will pull out 50,000
of its 120,000 troops this year and leave Cambodia by 1990 or 1991,
saying the timetable was too slow.
   ``This only shows that up to now, Vietnam has no sincerity to
settle the question of Kampuchea,'' he said.
   Li said that in the past, Vietnam's proclaimed withdrawals
turned out to be mere troop rotations. ``People are entitled to
call for strict international supervision and on-the-spot
verification of the withdrawal of Vietnamese troops from
Kampuchea.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
