<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Matlovich     06-23 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Matlovich,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Who Fought Air Force Discharge for Homosexuality Dies From
AIDS</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY18</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leonard Matlovich, who died from AIDS at
age 44, was remembered Thursday for his 13-year battle against gay
stereotypes, beginning with his discharge from the Air Force for
declaring his homosexuality.
   ``He saw the gay rights struggles of the 1980s as the equivalent
of black civil rights struggles of the '50s and '60s,'' said Mike
Erickson, former owner of a California radio station where
Matlovich conducted a weekly talk show.
   Matlovich, who waged a public battle against the Air Force after
he was discharged for homosexuality in 1975, died Wednesday night
friend in Hollywood, where he had moved in April from San
Francisco, said friend Michael Bedwell.
   Matlovich died peacefully in the presence of relatives and
friends. The former technical sergeant was diagnosed with AIDS in
1986.
   ``Leonard Matlovich, more than anyone I have ever met, was
someone who was so admired that wherever he was people would come
up to him and say how he had changed their lives with his courage
to admit that he was gay,'' said Ken McPherson, a gay rights
activist in San Francisco.
   Matlovich won the Bronze Star and Purple Heart during the
Vietnam war. Erickson said Matlovich told him one of the medals was
awarded after he killed two Viet Cong soldiers while on sentry duty.
   Matlovich's declaration of homosexuality spurred the then
fledgling gay rights movement, which made his fight a cause
celebre. Matlovich was pictured on the cover of Time magazine in
1975, next to the words, ``I am a homosexual.''
   The Air Force responded by giving him a general discharge, but
Matlovich filed suit and in 1980 received an honorable discharge
and a $160,000 settlement.
</TEXT>
