<1ST_LINE>r a AM-IndelicatoIndicted     06-23 0549</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Indelicato Indicted,0564</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indelicato Indicted on New State Charges of Theft and Forgery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gerard T. Indelicato, a former education adviser
to Gov. Michael S. Dukakis facing sentencing on federal fraud and
conspiracy charges, was named Thursday in state indictments
accusing him of larceny and forgery.
   Indelicato, 42, is due for sentencing July 8 after pleading
guilty to separate federal charges of fraud and conspiracy.
   The newest charges that date from his term as Dukakis' special
assistant for educational affairs from 1983-86 and his term as
president of Bridgewater State College from 1986 until his
resignation in December.
   In a prepared statement, Dukakis said the charges were the
result of a probe by the State Office of Investigation that Dukakis
himself requested last November.
   ``The criminal charges against Gerard Indelicato are very
serious _ more so because they allege a violation of the public
trust. I expect every public official who works for the
commonwealth to meet the highest standards of integrity,'' Dukakis
said.
   The new state charges against Indelicato were included in
indictments returned by separate grand juries sitting in Suffolk
and Plymouth counties.
   The five indictments released in Boston charge Indelicato of
Norwood with seven counts of violating the state
conflict-of-interest law, seven counts of larceny, 13 counts of
forgery, two counts of submitting false documents to a state
agency, three counts of filing false state income tax returns and
violations of Massachusetts fraud law.
   The Plymouth County indictments, covering Indelicato's actions
as Bridgewater president, include three counts of larceny, five
counts of forgery and one conflict charge.
   He is to be arraigned in Suffolk County on July 5 and in
Plymouth County on July 6.
   Indelicato's attorney, Morris Goldings, did not immediately
return a reporter's telephone call.
   The Suffolk County charges allege that Indelicato, while a
public official, had a financial interest in state contracts
awarded by the state, by Southeastern Massachusetts University and
the University of Lowell.
   In the Plymouth County indictments, Indelicato is charged with
forging the deed and other documents on land owned by the
Bridgewater State College Foundation, where Indelicato was building
a house.
   The other larceny counts relate to Indelicato's alleged misuse
of the foundation's funds, and the conflict charge relates to a
$7,500 payment from the foundation to Administrative Associates, in
which Indelicato had a financial interest.
   If convicted, Indelicato faces maximum penalties of 10 years in
state prison on each of the 13 forgery counts, five years in prison
and a fine of $25,000 on the larceny charges, five years in prison
and a fine of $10,000 on the fraud counts, two years in prison and
a $3,000 fine on the conflict counts and three years and a $100,000
fine on the tax charges.
   Indelicato pleaded guilty in federal court in April on charges
of mail fraud, conspiracy to commit mail fraud, perjury and making
false statements on tax returns between 1979 and 1983, before he
became a top Dukakis aide.
   The prosecution plans to recommend Indelicato serve 5 years in
prison and pay restitution of up to $80,000 for money siphoned out
of an adult education program through fraudulent billing, phony
employees and embezzled checks.
   Three co-codefendants in the federal case pleaded guilty to a
variety of charges.
</TEXT>
