<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     06-23 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRDS LANDING, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The post office in this sleepy
delta town is one of the three smallest in the nation, but it still
gets the postmaster's stamp of approval for being an interesting
place to work.
   Birds Landing tied with Salvo, N.C., and Ocholpee, Fla., in a
contest to determine the smallest post office. The winners beat out
such places as Cut and Shoot, Texas; Smile, Ky.; and Remote, Alaska.
   Using a point system, the post offices were compared in such
categories as square footage, local population, number of post
office boxes and number of delivery route stops. The contest began
with officials at the Postal Service's Oakland division, which
includes Birds Landing.
   Handling mail for the 24 people of Birds Landing, about 4 miles
from the Sacramento River, and about 100 families in the
surrounding countryside doesn't sound like a high-pressure job, but
Shirley Paolini, who has been postmaster for 20 years, said:
   ``For me, it's never boring. It can be anything else, but it's
never boring. You never know what the day is going to bring.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BARTLESVILLE, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Someone with a sense of fowl play
keeps stealing the city's duck crossing signs, so street officials
have decided to sell the yello caution signs to pay the bills.
   The duck silhouette on a diamond-shaped sign is supposed to warn
motorists to watch for ducks crossing the street near a
neighborhood park pond.
   Since first installing the caution signs about two years ago,
the city has put up about 20 of the signs. All have disappeared.
   At $75 apiece, the street department is out $1,500 for the
signs, said Garold Young of the town's streets department. He said
officials figure the missing signs have become wall hangings in
dormitories and bedrooms.
   Officials decided last week they would bow to market demand and
offer the signs for sale at $28 to $35 apiece.
   ``I don't know if it will do any good but we thought we would
try to sell them,'' Young said. ``We are not here to make a profit.
The people in the area want the ducks protected.''
</TEXT>
