<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 0807EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APonTV-Costas Adv24   06-23 0828</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP on TV-Costas, Adv 24,0845</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv24</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs, June 24, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Bob Costas Gets Early Morning Practice for Late-Night Show</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Viewers who don't want to stay up half the night
this fall can get a glimpse of NBC's new late-night talk show host,
sports announcer Bob Costas, when he takes a turn as guest co-host
on ``Today,'' beginning Monday.
   On Aug. 22, Costas' show, ``Later with Bob Costas,'' premieres.
It will follow ``Late Night with David Letterman'' Monday through
Friday at 1:30 a.m. EDT.
   Costas hopes a homey set and varied guest list will quickly
disabuse viewers of the notion that Costas is a sports guy and must
be doing a sports show.
   Some of the guests already booked include David Eisenhower,
activist Abbie Hoffman, comedians Steven Wright and Martin Mull,
talk-show host Larry King, journalists Tom Shales and Linda
Ellerbee, film critics Gene Siskel and Roger Ebert, sex therapist
Dr. Ruth Westheimer, actor Chuck Norris, singers Meatloaf and
Johnny Cash and Jerry Mathers as ``the Beaver.''
   Sports figures won't be ignored. John Madden and Bob Uecker have
been booked, and Costas hopes to get Sugar Ray Leonard and Bobby
Knight on the show, too.
   ``If we do get sports figures, it would be because the interest
in them transcends sports fans,'' Costas said.
   ``We're going to get a really good cross-section of people that
I think will appeal to viewers that have watched the Letterman
show. We hope we can keep some of the people that are watching
Letterman at 1:30 and pick up some strays. You know, milkmen who
are getting ready to go to work, precocious paper boys.''
   Meanwhile, Costas is one in a series of fill-ins for ``Today''
co-host Bryant Gumbel, who is off getting ready for his duties as
anchor of the network's coverage of the Summer Olympics. Costas
will go to the Olympics, too, and appear on a wrap-up that will
pre-empt the NBC late-night schedule, including his own show.
   It has been widely speculated that Gumbel won't want to return
to the early-morning grind after his high-profile stint in prime
time. So Costas, along with other guest hosts, has been presumed
under consideration to replace him.
   Costas' predecessors in the recent host-of-the-week series have
included Phil Donahue, Tom Snyder and Jim Lehrer. All three are
consummate professionals in their element, but only Snyder seemed
comfortable with the ``Today'' format.
   Costas dismisses speculation about the ``Today'' slot but avoids
issuing an unequivocal rejection of the idea.
   ``I think the thing that no reasonably intelligent person would
say _ `No I'll never do that.' Stupid thing to say. But is it
something I'm thinking about doing, something that concerns me,
something I'm pointing toward doing? Absolutely not.''
   How well he does next week notwithstanding, Costas is considered
to have star potential by NBC, whose talk-show king, Johnny Carson,
is approaching retirement age.
   And the cushy schedule of ``Later'' would be hard for Costas to
give up. The show is taped one day a week, then he's free to
continue his first love, covering baseball. And if the show is
successful and is picked up beyond the current 26-show commitment,
Costas will move it for the summer to St. Louis, his hometown. A
``Today'' job would require him to be in New York almost all the
time.
   ``I'm well aware that some very substantial people in this
business have done that (``Today'') job, and even to be mentioned
in connection with it is flattering and an honor, et cetera, et
cetera,'' Costas said.
   ``However, I think the most important thing that someone should
do is do what makes them happy, not fulfill somebody else's idea of
what the next highest-ranking job is and what the next step up the
ladder is and what your next ambition should be.
   ``My ambition is to do a good job at what I do and to be happy.
And I'm very, very, very happy anytime I'm at a baseball game.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   `SATURDAY NIGHT' REVIVE _ The entire cast of NBC's ``Saturday
Night Live,'' the first to win major kudos since the originals,
will be back for a third year when the show begins its new season
Oct. 8, says NBC. ...
   WHEW! `FAMILY FEUD' IS BACK _ Everybody who's been getting along
so well out there, get set to take up fussin' and a-fightin' again.
``Family Feud'' is coming back on the air, appropriately enough on
the Fourth of July, after a three-year absence _ but this time
without host Richard Dawson and without network ABC. The new host
is standup comic Ray Combs. The new network is CBS. Dawson,
meanwhile, is supposed to become the host of a new version of ``You
Bet Your Life'' on NBC. Whose shoes would you rather try to fill?
Richard Dawson's or Groucho Marx's?
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri PMs, June 24</NOTE>
