<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0572</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks surged on news of a strengthened dollar, positive
economic reports and eased pressure on interest rates, boosting the
Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks to the highest level
since the crash eight months ago.
   The catalyst for Wednesday's rally appeared to be a surprising
surge in the dollar, which rose to nearly 129 Japanese yen. The Dow
Jones industrial average rose 43.03 points to 2,152.20.
   Bonds, meanwhile, rose as much as $18 for every $1,000 of face
value, with interest rates on the bellwether 30-year Treasury bond
dropping to 8.91 percent from 9.08 percent late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The rise in grain and soybean futures prices slowed on forecasts
for rain in the eastern Corn Belt despite predictions that the
rainfall would be sparse.
   On other markets Wednesday, precious metals futures plummeted
while Treasury bond and stock-index futures posted sharp gains;
livestock and meat futures fell sharply; and energy futures
advanced.
   On the Chicago Board of Trade, oat futures soared on reports
that as much as 50 percent of the U.S. oat crop had been lost to
the drought. Corn for July delivery closed up the permissable limit
for the seventh straight day. But the forecasts for rain left
soybeans prices mixed, and wheat was mostly lower as harvesting of
the winter crop accelerated.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders for durable goods fell 2.2 percent in
May, the steepest drop in nine months, the Commerce Department
reported.
   Slower aircraft sales was largely responsible for the drop in
orders to a seasonally adjusted $114.8 billion, down from $117.4
billion in April, according to Wednesday's report.
   Analysts said the manufacturing sector remains strong despite
the figures, while financial markets and the White House read the
report as good news for inflation.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pepsico Inc. has agreed to buy the soft drink
bottling operations of Grand Metropolitan Inc. for $705 million in
cash.
   The deal was announced Wednesday.
   Grand Metropolitan acquired the operations in 1980 and is the
third largest independent bottlers of Pepsi-Cola products in the
United States, accounting for about 3.6 percent of Pepsi-Cola's
domestic soft drink volume.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government cannot force ailing LTV Corp. to
take back more than $2 billion in pension obligations simply
because a new labor contract restored previously cut benefits, a
Manhattan federal judge ruled.
   U.S. District Judge Robert W. Sweet said Wednesday he couldn't
uphold a decision by the Pension Benefit Guaranty Corp. to restore
the pension plan obligations of LTV's steel unit, Cleveland-based
LTV Steel Co.
   Sweet said that although the pension agency didn't provide
enough documentation that LTV could afford to take back its pension
obligations, the agency might be able to do so at a trial.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two ailing Texas thrifts have been taken over by
an Arizona savings bank after Federal Home Loan Bank Board
officials guaranteed $83.9 million in assistance to complete the
transaction.
   MeraBank Federal Savings and Loan, with $6.4 billion in assets,
on Wednesday took over First Financial _ A Savings Association,
based in El Paso; and Brownfield Federal Savings and Loan
Association in Brownfield. MeraBank, based in Phoenix, is the
largest thrift institution in Arizona.
</TEXT>
