<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 0144EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     06-23 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Higher On Gasoline Rally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gasoline futures have rallied for a second
straight session, lending strength to oil prices.
   The July contract for unleaded gasoline rose 0.41 cent to close
at 50.40 cents a gallon Wednesday on the New York Mercantile
Exchange. The July contract for home heating oil gained 0.34 cent
to close at 43.62 cents a gallon.
   The August contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
U.S. crude, picked up 8 cents to close at $16.44 per barrel.
   The market opened lower because of abundant supplies of crude
oil on world markets, said Peter Beutel, assistant director of the
energy group at Elders Futures Inc.
   But gasoline prices, which also had rallied on Tuesday, moved
higher and supported oil prices, he said.
   Gas futures rose on fears that supplies would be tight, Beutel
said. Traders were concerned about the backup of gasoline barges on
the Mississippi River, especially with the summer driving season at
hand.
   The drought in the Midwest has shrunk water levels on rivers and
many barges have either run aground or become snagged in traffic
bottlenecks. The Army Corps of Engineers is running dredging
operations to allow the barges to move, but progress has been slow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
