<HEAD>Yields on Two-Year Treasury Notes Lowest Since April</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yields on two-year Treasury notes fell in the
government's latest auction to the lowest level since April.
   The average yield was 8.05 percent on Wednesday, down from 8.18
percent at the last comparable auction on May 25.
   It was the lowest rate since two-year notes averaged 7.64
percent on April 27. The notes will carry a coupon interest rate of
8 percent, with each $10,000 in face value selling for $9,990.90.
   A total of $8.54 billion in notes were sold out of bids totaling
$29.18 billion.
