<1ST_LINE>r f PM-PepsiBottling Bjt   06-23 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pepsi Bottling, Bjt,0517</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pepsico Agrees to Buy Grand Met Bottling Operations for $705
Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pepsico Inc. has agreed to pay $705 million in
cash for the soft drink bottling operations of Grand Metropolitan
Inc., the nation's third-largest independent bottler of Pepsi-Cola
products.
   The deal, disclosed Wednesday, is expected to be completed by
late July and involves territories in the Carolinas, Georgia,
Kentucky, Tennessee and Calfornia.
   Grand Metropolitan acquired the operations in 1980. They account
for about 3.6 percent of Pepsi-Cola's domestic soft drink volume.
   But the Montvale, N.J.-based concern said the bottling
operations did not fit its strategic business plan for developing
its core businesses, which include hotels, retailing, foods and
alcoholic beverages.
   ``Although Pepsi is a leader in the soft drinks industry, we do
not own the brand and therefore cannot direct its position in the
marketplace as we do our other brands like Smirnoff,
Inter-Continental and Alpo,'' said Ian A. Martin, chairman of Grand
Metropolitan.
   The operations being sold are Atlantic Soft Drink Co., based in
Columbia, S.C., that holds Pepsi Cola franchises in the Carolinas,
Georgia, Kentucky and Tennessee, and Pepsi Cola San Joaquin, which
has franchises in central California.
   Grand Met said the companies had combined annual sales of $355
million in the year ended Sept. 30, 1987.
   D. Wayne Calloway, Pepsico chairman and chief executive, said
the Grand Met franchises will ``significantly strengthen our soft
drink volumes and improve operating profits, both this year and
well into the future.''
   He said the acquisition will dilute Pepsico's earnings for 1988
by about 4 cents a share. In 1987, Pepsico reported net income of
$595 million, or $2.26 a share, on revenue of $11.5 billion.
   The sale would mean Pepsico, which is based in Purchase, N.Y.,
will own bottling operations that account for about 36 percent of
its domestic soft drink volume, up from about 32.4 percent.
   James M. Griffith, a spokesman for Pepsico, said Pepsico was not
looking to acquire independent bottling operations but became
interested once the bottlers became available because they are
located in ``two very important areas where we are determined to
strengthen Pepsi's presence'' and in some cases border territories
Pepsico already owns.
   He said such acquisitions offer ``some economies of scale.''
   A spokeswoman for Grand Met, Mary Carroll, said her company was
approached about three months ago by someone who suggested he may
be prepared to offer a certain price for the bottling operations.
She refused to identify the suitor.
   She said the inquiry prompted the company to consider whether it
wanted to sell the operations, and it subsequently notifified a
limited number of potential bidders that the operations were for
sale.
   Martin said Pepsico offered ``a very fair price.''
   Grand Metropolitan is the U.S. subsidiary of Grand Metropolitan
PLC, a multinational company based in the United Kingdom. Sales in
the United States exceed $10 billion, the company said.
   Pepsico has operations in soft drinks, snack foods and
restaurants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
