<DOCNO> AP880623-0253 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 0151EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Brazil-Debt     06-23 0583</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brazil-Debt,0601</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brazil Gets $5.8 Billion Debt Refinancing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The debt restructuring Brazil reached
with its creditor banks after eight months of tense negotiations
includes $5.2 billion in new loans, lower interest rates and
payments aimed at bringing the nation current on its obligations.
   Brazil on Wednesday said it had closed a $5.8 billion accord
with its creditor banks to refinance some $64 billion of the
country's massive foreign debt.
   The agreement ends Brazil's negotiations with the committee of
14 banks representing the nation's 700 creditor banks, which now
must sign the accord.
   ``Brazil has concluded one of the best refinancing accords ever
reached by a debtor nation,'' Finance Minister Mailson da Nobrega
told reporters at a news conference.
   ``The accord is not a solution to the country's foreign debt
problems but it will bring Brazil closer to the international
financial community and remove the obstacles to economic and social
development of the country,'' he said.
   The accord came a year and a half after Brazil stopped interest
payments on the $64 billion in bank debt in order to conserve
shrinking foreign reserves. The nation's total foreign debt of $121
billion is the largest in the developing world.
   While interest payments were a crippling $1 billion monthly,
inflation soared to 1,000 percent annual levels, money reserves and
the trade surplus dropped dramatically and unemployment skyrocketed
to about 25 percent.
   Under the agreement, Brazil will make a $345 million payment to
creditors for March interest on Friday and by the end of next month
will meet a $1 billion to cover April and May interest, bringing it
current on its obligations.
   But da Nobrega said the agreement did not ``formally revoke''
the moratorium. Da Nobrega said that might happen in October, when
all creditors are expected to have signed the accord and Brazil
receives more than $4 billion.
   Under the agreement, which covers interest due in 1987, 1988 and
the first half of 1989, Brazil will receive $5.2 billion in new
money to meet interest payemtns and debt falling due over the
period will be spread out over 20 years, with an eight-year grace
period.
   Brazil also will receive $600 million in short-term credit lines
toward financing exports and imports.
   In addition, the banks agreed to sharply reduce the interest
rate they had been charging on the $64 billion in loans. Brazil's
spread, or the extra interest charged high-risk clients above the
London Interbank Offered Rate, was to be cut to 0.8125 percent from
the 1.75 percent set under previous agreements. Among developing
nations, only Mexico has obtained such a low spread from creditors.
   One of the sticking points between Brazil and its creditors was
linkage between new money and approval of the country's economic
policies from the International Monetary Fund. Brazil has argued
the fund's policies are recessionary and impinge upon the country's
sovereignty.
   According to the accord, only the $600 million in credit lines
will be linked to meeting economic goals in an IMF-approved plan
and even that decision could be appealed at a later date.
   ``Brazil is the first country to sign a medium-term accord
without having to have any rigid links with the fund,'' da Nobrega
said.
   According to da Nobrega, a Brazil also is allowed to pull out of
the agreement if there are any ``external economic shocks that
impair Brazil's ability to meet interest payments.'' This could
apply to even a drop in Brazil's trade surplus, this year expected
to reach over $13 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880623-0254 </DOCNO>
