<DOCNO> AP880623-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 0828EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-LTVPensions     06-23 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-LTV Pensions,0579</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge: Government Can't Force Pension Plans Back on LTV</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While the federal Pension Benefit Guaranty Corp.
is entitled to make employers take back terminated pension plans,
it hasn't proven it's case yet against LTV Corp., a judge has ruled.
   The judge on Wednesday refused to uphold the PBGC's decision to
force the financially ailing LTV to reassume $2 billion in pension
obligations because a new labor contract restored previously cut
benefits.
   U.S. District Judge Robert Sweet of Manhattan said the agency,
which insures the pensions of 30 million American workers, had not
explored ``all the relevant facts'' before handing three
underfunded pension plans back to LTV's Cleveland-based steel unit,
LTV Steel Co.
   ``Since the agency's decision is not sustainable on the
administrative record, the appropriate remedy is to vacate the
restoration decision'' that gave back responsibility for the
pensions to LTV, said Sweet.
   ``We're very pleased,'' said Lewis B. Kaden, an attorney for LTV
Corp., who called the ruling ``a complete victory.''
   But Sweet concluded in his 126-page opinion that the PBGC might
be able to make its case with additional data. The judge sent the
issue back to the PBGC ``for further consideration'' and told both
sides to arrange a conference with him on further proceedings.
   ``While the court recognized PBGC's authority to restore
terminated plans, it did not immediately enforce restoration of the
LTV plans,'' said PBGC spokeswoman Jane Hoden. ``Instead, the court
required additional fact finding by the PBGC on LTV's ability to
fund the plans. The PBGC is pleased that the court recognized our
authority to restore plans, but we are disappointed that the court
required additional proceedings.''
   Reading from a statement, she said the PBGC ``is now considering
other legal steps to resolve the issues of this case and relieve
the uncertainty faced by retirees.''
   The Dallas-based LTV, a giant steel, aerospace and energy
concern, filed for protection from its creditors under Chapter 11
of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code in July 1986.
   The PBGC, which insures pension benefits much like the Federal
Deposit Insurance Corp. insures bank deposits, took over LTV's
steel industry pension plans last January after the company
terminated them. The plans were $2 billion in debt, making the PBGC
LTV's largest creditor.
   But when a new LTV labor contract with the United Steelworkers
of America restored some benefits previously cut, the agency
claimed that the company was taking unfair advantage of federal
funds to cut costs and gain labor peace.
   LTV, the nation's No. 2 steelmaker, claims that restoring the
plans and their deficit will seriously hamper its ability to
reorganize and emerge from bankruptcy proceedings.
   LTV Corp.'s first quarter net income rose 26 percent, according
to the company, because of higher steel prices and the continuing
benefits of federal bankruptcy law protection.
   Last September the PBGC shifted responsibility for the
underfunded pension plans back to LTV, claiming the corporation was
abusing the pension insurance program and its actions could
jeopardize the agency's already strapped nationwide pension
insurance fund.
   But LTV claimed the move violated the automatic stay provision
of the Bankruptcy Code, which bars legal action against companies
in reorganization.
   Sweet ruled, however, that the restoration of pension plans was
allowed under the law that created the PBGC and the action was not
subject to the automatic stay provision.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880623-0258 </DOCNO>
