<HEAD>London Shares Up</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be led with closing figures</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were higher at midday Thursday on the
London Stock Exchange, boosted by a strong showing on Wall Street
in the previous session.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was up 8.9
points, or 0.5 percent, at 1,882.2 at about 12:30 p.m. local time.
   Trading volume was 360.2 million shares at midday, compared with
262.9 million shares at the same time a day earlier.
   Dealers said the market was heartened by gains in New York on
Wednesday, when the Dow Jones industrial average closed 43.03
points higher at 2,152.20.
   Market observers said business would have been more brisk in
London had it not been for computer problems with SEAQ, the Stock
Exchange Automatic Quotation system.
   Analysts said the market appears to be consolidating advances
reached over the past two sessions, when the 100-share index
climbed 35 points.
   ``People are starting to question whether the rise can
continue,'' said one equity salesman, adding that ``as we get
towards 1,900, people seem to doubt whether we can surpass it.''
