<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Norway-Oil     06-23 0163</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Norway-Oil,0170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Norway Continues Oil Production Restraint</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Norway will restrain by 7.5 percent its
North Sea oil production during the second half of 1988, the Oil
and Energy Ministry announced Thursday.
   Ministry spokesman Egil Helle said the restrained level will
mean a daily production of 90,000 barrels below full capacity. But
new wells and fields will be opened during the next six months,
raising Norway's overall production, Helle said.
   The cut will apply to all offshore fields.
   The energy ministry said that Norway's average daily production
during the first half of 1988 was about 1.035 billion barrels.
During the second half it is projected to reach 1.125 billion
barrels.
   Norway is not a member of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries, but it has held back on production since
February 1986 in line with OPEC's efforts to stabilize prices.
   ``The government's decision to reduce the production growth is a
contribution to stabilization of oil prices,'' the ministry said.
</TEXT>
