<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 3rd Ld-Writethru, f0048,0734</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises; `Big Ticket' Orders Fall; Stock Market Leaps</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS New grafs 2-4, Meanwhile, the ... 4.3 percent, to
UPDATE with government revising 1988 economic growth estimate.
Picks up 2nd graf pvs, The Commerce</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's economy, fueled by an export-driven manufacturing
boom, expanded at a robust 3.6 percent in the first quarter,
slightly less than previously thought, the government said today.
   Meanwhile, the government revised upwards its estimate of
economic growth in 1988, predicting an expansion of 3.5 percent.
The original predictions was that the economy would grow by 2.9
percent this year.
   Beryl Sprinkel, chairman of the presidential Council of Economic
Advisers, said, ``The economy is doing better than even we
expected. Our rosy forecast wasn't rosy enough.''
   He said that contrary to some fears, the economy is not
overheating, with inflation holding at 4.3 percent.
   The Commerce Department said the gross national product, the
broadest measure of economic health, grew to a seasonally adjusted
annual level of $3.915 trillion in the January-March period, a
$34.6 billion increase from three months earlier.
   It was a modest downward revision of a previous estimate of GNP
growth in the first quarter. Last month, the government put GNP
growth at 3.9 percent, up from an initial estimate of 2.3 percent
in April.
   Analysts were expecting the slight retreat.
   Government economists said the first quarter growth occurred
with little pickup in inflation. A price index tied to the GNP rose
at an annual rate of 1.4 percent, slightly lower than the
previously estimated 1.7 percent and well below the 2.7 percent
pace of the fourth quarter.
   In a separate report today, the Commerce Department said
after-tax corporate profits fell 1.0 percent in the first quarter
to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $144.2 billion.
   That was down $1.4 billion from the last three months of 1987
and the worst performance since the first quarter of 1987, when
profits fell 3.7 percent.
   Today's report represents a downward revision from an estimate
last month, when the department said profits after taxes eased up
0.5 percent.
   On Wednesday, a strong rally by the dollar and indications that
inflation may not be heating up as badly as earlier feared helped
spark a stock market rally that pushed Wall Street to its highest
levels since the October crash.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks rose 43.03 points
to 2,152.20, eclipsing the previous post-crash high of 2,131.40 set
a week earlier.
   Aiding the market was the Commerce Department's report of a 2.2
percent decline in May of orders to U.S. factories for ``big
ticket'' durable goods, the biggest drop in nine months.
   Economists said the decline in orders was healthy because it
indicated the economy was not being overheated by too much pressure
on production capacity.
   Stocks also were helped by a big rise by the dollar in foreign
exchange, a rally that caught many traders by surprise.
   The dollar reached almost 129 Japanese yen in New York, up more
than 2 yen from Tuesday's close.
   Analysts said the dollar's jump may have stemmed partly from the
outcome of the economic summit meeting of the seven major
industrialized countries in Toronto, and a summit communique
hinting there was room for the dollar to strengthen further.
   ``That statement gave the market a signal to buy dollars,'' said
Earl Johnson, a vice president at Harris Trust and Savings Bank in
Chicago.
   The decline in durable goods orders surprised economists, who
had expected more than a 2 percent rise in orders. But they noted
the government's survey apparently did not include several
multibillion-dollar orders placed to Seattle-based Boeing Co.
   Even though the overall May decline was the largest since
August's 2.3 percent fall, analysts saw little cause to worry that
the report was forecasting a significant decline in manufacturing,
which has been booming as the cheaper dollar bolsters export sales
of U.S. goods.
   Excluding defense goods, orders fell only 0.9 percent. Excluding
airplanes, they rose 0.6 percent.
   The financial markets read the report as good news for
inflation. Many traders and some analysts have been concerned that
the export boom, coupled with steady consumer demand in the United
States, would strain manufacturers' capacity and cause shortages
and price increases.
</TEXT>
