<HEAD>GAF Confirms It Is Under Investigation; Denies Wrongdoing</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES throughout with GAF statement, confirmation; no
pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   GAF Corp. confirmed Thursday that it is under
investigation for possible securities law violations, but a
spokesman for the company denied any wrongdoing.
   According to the spokesman, the focus of the investigation
appears to relate to the disposition of a portion of GAF's stock
position in Union Carbide Corp. during late 1986.
   GAF made a hostile bid for Carbide in 1985 but reached a
standstill agreement with the company the following year.
   According to unidentified sources quoted in Thursday's editions
of the Wall Street Journal, the federal government is looking into
GAF's accumulation of Carbide stock through Jefferies & Co., a Los
Angeles securities firm once headed by Boyd L. Jefferies.
   Jefferies pleaded guilty to two felonies after being implicated
in a stock parking scheme by convicted arbitrager Ivan F. Boesky,
who is now serving time in prison.
   James Sherwin, GAF's vice chairman and chief administrative
officer, has been named as having had an agreement with Boyd
Jefferies regarding alleged stock parking and manipulation, the
newspaper said.
   Under their alleged agreement, GAF agreed to reimburse the
Jefferies firm for losses incurred in trading in Carbide stock.
   The Journal's sources noted that Sherwin did not make any money
from the scheme. The U.S. attorney's office in New York appears
undecided as to whether it will seek criminal charges in the case,
the paper said.
   ``Both the company and its officials are innocent of any
wrongdoing,'' a spokesman for GAF said.
   In early trading on the New York Stock Exchange, GAF had fallen
$1.62{ a share to $46{.
   According to the Journal, GAF is the first industrial company to
be targeted for investigation in the government's widespread probe
of abuses within the securities industry.
   The paper noted that the investigation could hamper GAF Chairman
Samuel Heyman's planned $1.27 billion leveraged buyout of the
Wayne, N.J.-based chemicals and building materials company.
   But the GAF spokesman said, ``the outcome of this matter will
not have any material financial consequences to the company, and
plans for management's proposed leveraged buyout of GAF remain
unaffected.''
  
</TEXT>
