<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Soar At Opening</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans opened
sharply higher today on the Chicago Board of Trade amid fears that
crop damage from the scorching drought was bound to deepen.
   Soybeans for July delivery blasted to a 15-year high in early
trading after topping $10.76{ a bushel, the 1977 top price for a
near-month contract.
   Scattered rain fell in parts of the eastern Farm Belt Wednesday
but analysts said only a return to normal rainfall patterns could
ward off further wreckage in the country's corn, oat, spring wheat
and soybean fields.
   Experts estimate the drought has already devastated at least 50
percent of the oat and spring wheat crops, 30 percent of corn and
will begin to take a significant toll on soybeans in July.
   Corn for July delivery opened up the 10-cents-a bushel limit;
July soybeans quickly traded up their 45-cent limit, putting the
contract within { cent of $11 a bushel; and oat futures opened
limit-up.
   Weekend weather forecasts for more light, scattered showers in
the Midwest may have a slight slowing effect on the rally, said
Cathy Leow, an analyst with Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc. in New
York.
   ``I would say the market is going to remain strong, although
some profit-taking may come in today and tomorrow,'' she said.
   In early trading, wheat was 7 cents to 11 cents higher with July
at $3.92{ a bushel; corn was 4 cents to 10 cents higher with July
at $3.54{ a bushel; oats were 14} cents to 15 cents higher with
July at a record $3.48 a bushel; soybeans were 21 cents to 45 cents
higher with July at $10.99{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were sharply lower to limit-down in
early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .42 cent to 1.20 cents lower with August at
62.12 a pound; feeder cattle were 1.15 cents to the limit 1.50
cents lower with August at 69.15 cents a pound; hogs were the limit
1.50 cents lower to .05 cent higher with July at 44.40 cents a
pound; frozen pork bellies were .10 cent to the limit 2 cents lower
with July at 40 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures closed sharply lower Wednesday.
</TEXT>
