<1ST_LINE>u f PM-FCC-Indecency 2ndLd-Writethru f0078 06-23 0634</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-FCC-Indecency, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0078,0649</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 3rd graf pvs, The Kansas, with comment
from station's attorney; Also moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission today
voted to levy the first fine for violation of its new decency
standards on a Missouri television station that aired a sexy movie
during prime time.
   Commissioners voted 2-1 to impose the maximum $2,000 fine
against KZKC-TV for its May 1987 broadcast of ``Private Lessons,''
which included scenes of a bare-breasted woman seducing a teen-ager.
   The Kansas City station aired the movie at 8 p.m., a time the
FCC has determined children are likely to be in the audience. The
FCC's guidelines allow ``indecent'' material to be aired after
midnight to lessen the risk that such programs could be viewed by
children.
   Attorney Thomas Davidson, who represents the station, said he
was ``shocked and surprised and outraged by the imposition of the
maximum fine in light of the circumstances.'' He said the sanction
is unfair because ``we don't know what is indecent because the
statute doesn't provide any guidance.''
   All three commissioners said that the movie fit the FCC's
definition of indecency, but Commissioner Patricia Dennis disagreed
with the fine. She said ``parents, not the commission, should bear
the primary responsibility of deciding what their children should
watch at night.''
   FCC Chairman Dennis R. Patrick disagreed, saying the government
must help parents in deciding what their children watch on
television. He said it is reasonable to assume that there are
unsupervised children in the audience during prime-time hours.
   Patrick said Wednesday that the FCC's record on indecency has
been clear.
   ``While respecting the First Amendment rights of all citizens,
we have taken clear and decisive action to enforce the statutory
ban on broadcast obscenity and to further restrict the broadcast of
indecent material so as to put parents in a better position to
control their children's access to this type of material,'' he said.
   Media Central Inc., which owns KZKC, has said the film had been
cut by an inexperienced editor and violated company standards, but
a fine would be inappropriate because the FCC's indecency
guidelines are ambiguous and are being applied to TV for the first
time.
   The movie, the owners said, was aired little more than a month
after the new standards were adopted. The FCC guidelines are being
challenged in court by broadcasting groups, news organizations and
public interest advocates as being unconstitutionally vague and
overbroad.
   Media Central acknowledged that the airing of the 1980 sex
comedy violated KZKC's ``broadcast standards and sense of good
taste,'' but the company said station officials took immediate
corrective action after the broadcast, including a clarification of
the station's policy on frontal nudity.
   Attorney Thomas Davidson, representing Media Central, said it
would be premature to comment before the commission acted.
   Media Central, based in Chattanooga, Tenn., is awaiting court
action on a reorganization plan it filed under Chapter 11 of the
Federal Bankruptcy Act.
   ``Private Lessons'' is about a wealthy 15-year-old boy who is
seduced by his housekeeper. The film includes several scenes in
which the housekeeper is shown bare-breasted.
   The FCC decided in April 1987 to apply the wording of a 1978
Supreme Court decision that said indecent material is ``language or
material that depicts or describes, in terms patently offensive as
measured by contemporary community standards for the broadcast
medium, sexual or excretory activities or organs.''
   The commission said indecent material may be aired only when
there is a reasonable risk that children are not in the audience.
In a subsequent ruling in November 1987, the FCC said it would
consider that children were not likely to be in the audience after
midnight. Previously the FCC had considered 10 p.m. the cutoff time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
