<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0347</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market retreated slightly today in
moderate trading after a strong runup in the previous session that
had pushed the Dow Jones industrial average to its highest level
since the October crash.
   The widely watched index of 30 industrials, which surged 43.03
points Wednesday to 2,152.20, was down 5.51 to 2,146.69 by 3 p.m.
EDT.
   Among broader market indicators, the New York Stock Exchange
composite index of all listed issues fell 0.36 to 154.99. The
American Stock Exchange market-value index fell 0.43 to 308.16.
   Losing stocks outnumbered gains by more than an 8-to-7 ratio on
the NYSE, with 790 down, 665 up and 493 unchanged. Volume on the
Big Board totaled 159.63 million shares with an hour of trading
left.
   Brokers differed on their assessment of the market today. Some
said they weren't surprised at the price weakness, attributing it
to investors who sold stocks to capture profits from the Wednesday
surge. A few said that reaction reflected lack of confidence in the
market's ability to sustain a longer rally. Others said the
dollar's strength and eased pressure on interest rates provided
underlying support to prices and probably would lure more people
into the market.
   They were encouraged by a government report today that predicted
the economy will grow at a larger than expected 3.5 percent this
year without a significant rise in inflation.
   IBM was among the most prominent issues, gaining 1| to 124|.
Hewlett Packard, another big-name computer stock, rose 1] to 53\.
   Other blue-chips were narrowly mixed. Boeing fell \ to 57|,
Sears fell \ to 37[, and McDonalds rose | to 46[.
   Commonwealth Edison was the Big Board's most active issue, up \
to 28| on volume exceeding 21.4 million shares. The heavy trading
was linked to dividend-capture strategies surrounding the stock.
   GAF fell 1~ to 46\ after reports surfaced that the company was
under investigation for possibly manipulating the stock of former
takeover target Union Carbide Corp.
