<2ND_LINE>BC-Bank Bid,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Irving Fails To Act By Bank Of NY Deadline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irving Bank Corp. failed to respond by a
Thursday deadline set by Bank of New York Co. for accepting a
sweetened $1.4 billion takeover bid.
   Bank of New York spokesman Owen Brady said the company was
disappointed that no action had been taken, and as a result, the
friendly offer had expired. In a one-page letter sent Thursday to
Bank of New York Chairman J. Carter Bacot, Irving outside director
David L. Luke III said the bank would be ``derelict in its duty if
we tried to respond'' by the noon Thursday deadline set by Bank of
New York on Wednesday.
   Luke said several serious concerns remained, among them, whether
Bank of New York could proceed with its latest offer under the
conditional approval the Federal Reserve Board granted to its
previous $1.2 billion offer. That approval is scheduled to run out
July 9.
   Irving's board of directors, which favors a merger with the
state-run Banca Commerciale Italiana SpA, failed to reach a
decision after meeting for several hours on Tuesday. Company
representatives also held a 1{-hour meeting with Bacot.
   Brady said Irving had plenty of time to respond. ``The offer was
out there for 10 days,'' he said.
   Bank of New York had warned that unless Irving's board of
directors went along with its latest proposal it would push for a
quick court decision on related lawsuits and proceed with a hostile
$1.1 billion tender offer. The company is seeking, among other
things, to remove Irving's anti-takeover ``poison pill.''
   Bank of New York improved its offer last week by slightly
raising the stock portion of the bid and adding other shareholder
incentives, including a special cash dividend.
   It valued the revised bid for all of Irving's 18.5 million
shares outstanding at around $76 a share, or $1.4 billion. That is
about 25 percent higher than the existing hostile $1.1 billion
tender offer.
   Banca Commerciale, Italy's second-largest bank, is offering $80
a share for 51 percent of Irving, or about $760 million. The
proposal is part of a complex defensive restructuring plan that
includes, among other things, sale of Irving assets, cost-cutting
measures and a special cash dividend.
