<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Close Mixed In Wild Session</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans closed mixed
in a wildly erratic session Thursday that saw soybeans hit a
15-year high near $11 a bushel, then plummet 70 cents as the market
developed a feverish case of the jitters.
   ``We're trading hysteria right now,'' said Cathy Leow, an
analyst with Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc. in New York.
   ``We're seeing an unprecedented type of weather,'' she said.
``However, it's also a very well-known fact that there is
significant downside risk if the weather situation were to change.''
   The markets opened sharply higher on fears of deepening drought
damage but only oat futures sustained the bullish momentum on
reports estimating oat yield losses of at least 50 percent. Most
oat contracts advanced the limit for daily trading for the fourth
consecutive session.
   Soybean futures began falling sharply at around noon CDT after
the price for July delivery reached $10.99{ a bushel. Corn and
wheat followed suit.
   ``The quote machines could not keep up,'' Ms. Leow said. ``I was
seeing quotes on my machine 10 cents behind what the market was
trading. I would not be compeletely shocked if we saw a record
volume day today.''
   At the close, wheat was 6{ cents lower to 5 cents higher with
July at $3.80 a bushel; corn was 7 cents lower to 3{ cents higher
with July at $3.48 a bushel; oats were 3 cents to 15 cents higher
with July at $3.48 a bushel; soybeans were 24{ cents lower to 20
cents higher with July at $10.30 a bushel.
</TEXT>
