<1ST_LINE>u f BC-EECSummit     06-23 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC Summit,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEC Executive Says Britain Is Obstacle To European Central Bank</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community may be
unable to create a European central bank until Britain changes its
stance on monetary cooperation, says Jacques Delors, the EEC's
chief executive.
   Delors, president of the EEC's commission, said Thursday it was
difficult to imagine creating such an institution as long as
Britain refuses to join the exchange-rate mechanism of the
eight-nation European Monetary System.
   The EMS was established in 1979 to minimize fluctuations in the
exchange values of its members' currencies. Britain has said it
might be willing to join the system in the future, but it has been
cool to the idea of a central bank.
   Delors told a news conference that a meeting of EEC government
leaders next Monday and Tuesday in Hanover, West Germany, would
discuss prospects for establishing a true European monetary and
currency union, including a European central bank.
   EEC officials have indicated they do not expect the meeting to
produce any decision on creating such a bank.
   West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, who will chair the Hanover
summit, would propose that a group of ``wise men'' be set up to
study the central bank issue and to draw up specific plans, Delors
said.
   The EEC has set a goal of eliminating all barriers to free
movement of goods, money and people among its 12 member nations by
Dec. 31, 1992.
</TEXT>
