<1ST_LINE>u f AM-ConsumerElectronics Bjt   06-23 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Consumer Electronics, Bjt,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Homes Are Filled With Consumer Electronics, Survey Shows</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer electronics aren't just for yuppies, an
industry group said Thursday in releasing a Gallup survey that
found nearly two-thirds of American homes owned a videocassette
recorder.
   Ownership of VCRs has mushroomed to 65 percent of U.S.
households, said the Electronic Industries Association, which
sponsored the nationwide telephone survey of 1,008 adults this
spring.
   Televisions, which topped the popularity list, were owned by 99
percent of the households surveyed.
   Among other items included in the survey, telephone answering
machines were in 24 percent of the homes, personal computers in 18
percent and compact disk players in 14 percent.
   Some people even claimed to have facsimile machines at home _
about 1 percent, the Gallup Organization survey found.
   ``Our products are not luxuries owned by a privileged, select
few,'' Thomas P. Friel, vice president of the trade organization's
Consumer Electronics Group, said in a news conference.
   Not surprisingly, the survey found the households with the
highest incomes had the most consumer electronics products. But it
wasn't just rich singles. Ownership was higher among families with
children. For example, about 78 percent of families with children
had VCRs, while only 40 percent of single-member households did.
   In general, ownership of consumer electronics products was
higher in the East and West than in the Midwest or South.
   For example, telephone answering machines were in 36 percent of
households in the West and 27 percent in the East. They were in 19
percent of the households in the South and 17 percent of those in
the Midwest, the survey found.
   On televisions, the survey found that 31 percent of households
owned one, 33 percent owned two and 35 percent owned three or more.
Forty-three percent of households with children own three or more
televisions.
   Questions asked of the whole group have a margin of error of 4
percentage points, while questions asked of subgroups have higher
error margins, a Gallup spokesman said.
   Since it was a survey done by phone, the results are valid only
for homes with telephones _ people without phones would tend to own
less consumer electronics equipment.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
