<HEAD>Money Funds Rose $909 Million in Latest Week</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund
Report are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the
week ended Wednesday.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 439 money market mutual
funds rose $908.7 million in the latest week, the Investment
Company Institute said Thursday.
   The rise to $266.28 billion in the seven-day period ended
Wednesday, followed a revised $1.88 billion decline in the funds'
assets the previous week, according to the Washington-based mutual
fund trade group.
   The previous week's decline had initially been reported as $2.45
billion.
   The funds' assets hit a record high $280.02 billion in the week
ended Feb. 24.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 220 general purpose funds increased $281 million to
$81.83 billion, assets of 97 broker-dealer funds increased $169
million to $113.5 billion, and assets of 122 institutional funds
rose $458.7 million to $70.95 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds rose in
the week ended Tuesday to 6.56 percent from 6.50 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield rose to 6.46 percent from 6.39 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was
36 days, down from 37 days, Donoghue's said.
   Separately, the newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of
100 leading commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and
savings banks in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the
effective annual yield available on money market accounts was 5.73
percent as of Wednesday, unchanged from a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super
NOW accounts, was also unchanged at 5.13 percent.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 7.11
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, unchanged from the
previous week. Yields were 7.45 percent on 1-year CDs, up from 7.44
percent; 7.83 percent on 2{-year CDs, up from 7.82 percent; and
8.26 percent on 5-year CDs, up from 8.25 percent.
