<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Europe-Aviation     06-23 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Europe-Aviation,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Experts Discuss Future Of European Airlines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND DE LIGNY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KERKRADE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Common Market leaders should remove
obstacles to airline mergers by carriers based in different member
nations, Western European aviation experts said Thursday at a
seminar here.
   ``Far-reaching liberalization of the airline industry is
essential to ensure a free flow of goods and services within the
EEC,'' Hans Raben, head of the Dutch civil aviation agency, told a
news conference. ``And it is crystal-clear that obstacles against
international mergers must be removed.''
   He spoke at the end of the day-long seminar in this southern
Dutch town on the future of the airline industry in the
deregulated, liberalized Common Market envisioned after 1992.
   The conference, convened by Dutch Transport Minister Neelie
Smit-Kroes, drew 40 representatives from Common Market airlines,
civil aviation authorities and governments.
   The European Economic Community has a 1992 goal of removing all
trade barriers among its members, including Western Europe's
patchwork of bilateral aviation agreements.
   Although some nations, notably Britain and the Netherlands,
already have liberalized aviation agreements, most European
countries severely limit the freedom of operation for foreign
airlines.
   After 1992, European airlines would be free to choose their
destinations and flight frequencies. Experts at the seminar
predicted that only a few very large carriers will be able to
survive.
   Seminar participants heard a report by the International
Foundation of Airline Passenger Associations on possible effects of
European airline mergers on the flying public. The Dutch Transport
Ministry commissioned the report by the private, Geneva-based
organization.
   In the report, IFAPA's executive director Geoffrey Lipman said
EEC members should maintain some regulations to safeguard airline
passengers. He said that after the 1978 deregulation of civil
aviation in the United States, passenger complaints on congestion,
delays and bad service mushroomed.
   Raben said that while the U.S. government abolished many of the
regulations affecting the airline industry in one move, ``we're
planning a gradual change in Europe.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880623-0288 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 1733EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Analysis Bjt   06-23 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Analysis, Bjt,0684</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar's Latest Jump Is Another Quirk In Unpredictable Market</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world's sudden enthusiasm for the dollar is
built on the vicissitudes of guesswork and opinion, and it may not
last.
   After months of stability, the dollar has jumped about 3 percent
against the Japanese yen and 4 percent against the West German mark
since June 10.
   Investors who used to treat the U.S. currency as a sick patient
are speculating about how high it might rise.
   Many analysts are happy to explain why they believe the dollar's
rise is long overdue and well-justified, but watertight
explanations have proven notoriously leaky in the past.
   Certainly there have been some reasonable theories for the
increase in the dollar's value.
   For example:
   _A sharp improvement in the U.S. merchandise trade deficit for
the month of April raised hopes that the nation was on a steady
path to balanced trade.
   _Japan reported extremely strong economic growth in early 1988,
raising the possibility that Japanese inflation would increase and
undermine the value of the yen. In another potential inflation
signal, the Japanese and West German money supplies have been
growing rapidly.
   _The finance leaders of the Group of Seven industrialized
nations left open the possibility that they would tolerate a
further increase in the dollar's value.
   But those explanations (and others) notwithstanding, the latest
dollar rise is more of a quirk than a response to fundamentals.
   The truth is that no one is certain what the dollar's
``natural'' value is _ if there is even such a thing. After all,
history shows the dollar can swing a long way from equilibrium.
   In early 1985 the dollar was worth twice what it is worth now in
terms of yen and marks. In light of that experience, who can say
for sure it is properly valued now?
   Although the latest pressure on the dollar has been upward, one
group of economists says it should fall another 15 or 20 percent.
   Psychology _ the mass psychology of the markets _ is the real
reason for the dollar's latest move.
   Traders who make a living by trading currencies were bored and
frustrated by the months of stability in the dollar. Some of them
undoubtedly made profits by engineering a rally in the dollar.
   The dollar's strength is new and it could be short-lived.
   As recently as the first quarter of this year, private investors
were so chary of the dollar that foreign central banks were forced
to finance more than 60 percent of the U.S. current account deficit.
   Foreign official assets in the United States rose $25 billion in
the three-month period, more than in any quarter of 1987, notes
Carol Stone, senior economist of Nomura Securities International
Inc.
   Sometime around April, Ms. Stone said, ``There was a massive
change in psychology.'' Suddenly, she said, private foreign
investors decided they weren't afraid to hold dollars.
   ``It's one of the virtuous-circle kind of things. The dollar has
remained stable, so people think the dollar will continue to remain
stable. It just keeps feeding on itself.''
   Virtuous circles can quickly change to vicious circles.
   ``As long as you are dependent on foreign capital inflows, the
dollar is extremely vulnerable,'' noted Jai P. Bajaj, chief
economist of New York Life Insurance Co.
   Yes, he said, it is possible that the United States will move
surely and steadily from trade deficit to trade surplus by sometime
in 1990. Congress and the next administration may make steady
progress on reducing the federal budget deficit.
   But then again, ill-timed moves in Washington or a sudden
deterioration in the trade account could inspire a run on the
dollar, Bajaj said.
   ``You can very easily fracture foreign confidence in U.S.
economic management,'' he said. ``I see lots of slippages. Lots of
danger.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Peter Coy covers trade and technology for The
Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880623-0289 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 1745EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   06-23 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0579</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market retreated slightly Thursday in
moderate trading, weakened by investors cashing profits from the
strong gains of the previous two sessions.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks, which had risen
nearly 70 points over Tuesday and Wednesday to the highest level
since the October crash, lost 3.91 points to close at 2,148.29.
Broader indexes were largely lower.
   Some traders were disheartened by what they called the market's
failure to sustain the momentum of a rally that began two days
earlier. They said it reflected a reluctance by a broad range of
investors to commit significant money to the market for a prolonged
period.
   ``When a market or a stock breaks out and it's in good shape,
what you normally do is at for least several days put some legs
under it,'' said Paul Campbell, a vice president and market
technician at Nikko Securities Co. International Inc. in New York.
``So I would have to argue that at least so far, the fact we're
unable to follow through is a negative, not a positive.''
   Others were more optimistic and said the slight retreat should
be regarded as a sign of underlying strength.
   ``The back-to-back days of the magnitude we had are probably
some cause for some profit-taking,'' said John J. Muldowney, head
of equity and over-the-counter trading at Scott & Stringfellow Inc.
in Richmond, Va. ``I'm not at all discouraged by this.''
   Others said they expected large institutional investors and
money managers to put cash into stocks over the next several
sessions to bolster portfolios before the quarter ends June 30.
That development likely would raise prices.
   In addition, they said foreigners likely will be increasingly
attracted to U.S. stocks if the dollar's strength is sustained.
That would be another positive for the stock market.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about an 8-to-7 ratio
in nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks,
with 803 issues down, 708 up and 473 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the NYSE totaled 185.77 million shares,
down from 217.51 million in the previous session. More than 21
million shares of the volume Thursday was due to dividend-capture
trading strategies in Commonwealth Edison, which rose \ to 28|.
   IBM was the most prominent blue-chip issue, surging 2} to 125}
after having gained nearly 6 in the previous two sessions.
   GAF fell 1} to 46] after reports emerged that the company was
under investigation for possibly manipulating the stock of former
takeover target Union Carbide Corp. GAF denied any wrongdoing.
   UAL jumped 3~ to 94| after Merrill Lynch reportedly upgraded its
investment rating on the airline company.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trading at regional exchanges and on the over-the-counter market,
totaled 213.88 million shares.
   The NYSE index composite index of all listed issues fell 0.32 to
155.03.
   Standard & Poor's index of 400 industrials fell 0.92 to 317.58,
and S&P's 500-stock composite index fell 0.84 to 274.82.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index rose 0.23
to 308.82. The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter
market closed at 391.03, up 0.50.
   The Wilshire Associates Equity Index, the market value of NYSE,
American and OTC issues, fell $4.44 billion or 0.16 percent from
Wednesday.
