<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MoneySupply     06-23 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Money Supply,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Money Supply Measures Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All three measures of the nation's money supply
tumbled in mid-June, the Federal Reserve Board reported Thursday.
   The Fed said its narrowest measure of the money supply, M1, fell
$2.1 billion in the week ended June 13 to a seasonally adjusted
$771.8 billion from $773.9 billion the previous week.
   It said the measure known as M2 fell $4.8 billion to a
seasonally adjusted $3,013 billion from $3,018 billion.
   An even broader measure, M3, fell $1.8 billion to a seasonally
adjusted $3,794 billion from $3,796 billion.
   M1 includes cash in circulation, deposits in checking accounts
and non-bank travelers checks. M2 is M1 plus accounts like savings
deposits and money-market mutual funds. M3 is M2 plus less-liquid
accounts, such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations
of $100,000.
   The central bank considers the two broader measures of the money
supply as well as the value of the dollar, commodity prices and the
difference between short- and long-term interest rates in setting
its monetary policy.
   But most economists say that recent movements in the money
supply do not appear to have played a very significant role in
those deliberations.
   In other reports Thursday:
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of New York reported commercial and
industrial loans at major New York City banks rose $952 million in
the week ended June 15, compared with a gain of $133 million the
previous week.
   _The Federal Reserve said discount window borrowings, excluding
extended credit, averaged $498 million a day in the week ended
Wednesday, down from $562 million the previous week.
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis reported that the
monetary base, the seasonally adjusted total of member bank
reserves held at Federal Reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and
in circulation, was $278.2 billion in the two-week period ended
Wednesday, up from $276.1 billion two weeks earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
