<1ST_LINE>u f AM-SuperfundSuits     06-23 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Superfund Suits,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EPA Files Suits Against Chrysler, Other Companies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency
filed lawsuits Thursday against Chrysler Corp. and 11 other
companies or individuals to recover more than $4 million in cleanup
costs for two hazardous waste sites in Delaware and Pennsylvania.
   James M. Seif, regional administrator of EPA's Region III office
in Philadelphia, said cleanup had begun at both sites and some
companies had already settled with EPA for cleanup costs.
   ``We're sending a message to those who have not settled,'' he
said at a news conference. ``We go to court to ensure others to
settle.''
   In Pennsylvania, the EPA is suing 10 companies for $982,000 plus
25 percent of future cleanup costs of the McAdoo site in Schuylkill
County, Seif said. The site, located in Kline Township, covers
about eight acres and was used for deep and strip mining of coal.
   The Harvey and Knott Drum site in Kirkwood, Del., was used as an
open dump and burning ground, Seif said. The EPA suit, filed in
federal court in Delaware against Chrysler Corp. and Knotts Inc.,
seeks $3.3 million and one-third of EPA's future oversight costs
for cleanup of the two-acre site, he said.
   Seif said General Motors Corp. previously agreed to perform
cleanup at the Harvey and Knott site and will be reimbursed for
one-third of the cleanup costs.
   The Pennsylvania suit was filed in U.S. District Court for the
Eastern District of Pennsylvania in Philadelphia.
</TEXT>
