<1ST_LINE>r f AM-USAir     06-23 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-USAir,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Finds No Evidence Union Staged Boycott</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TARA BRADLEY-STECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge said Thursday he found no
evidence the Association of Flight Attendants instigated a massive
overtime boycott at USAir, which was forced to cancel 179 flights
over the Memorial Day holiday.
   Although U.S. District Judge Robert Standish said the refusal of
many flight attendants to work overtime during the three-day
weekend was ``part of a concerted refusal to fly,'' he said
evidence was insufficient to prove the union ordered or encouraged
such a job action.
   The judge stopped short, however, of denying USAir's request for
a preliminary injunction barring future overtime boycotts. He said
he would issue a ruling on the airline's request Friday.
   Although neither side would claim victory or defeat, flight
attendants union attorney Deborah Greenfield said, ``Clearly he
(Standish) hasn't found any proof of union involvement so far.''
   USAir spokesman David Shipley declined to comment on the judge's
actions until a ruling is issued. He said the airline has no plans
to change its long-standing tradition of scheduling overtime for
its flight attendants.
   About 11,000 passengers were affected when hundreds of flight
attendants refused to work overtime during Memorial Day. The
airline said it lost an estimated $1.1 million.
   USAir officials testified during the two-day hearing that about
one-third of the airline's flight attendants routinely work more
than the 85 hours a month mandated by their contract.
   Under their two-year pact, which expires in August, USAir's
3,000 flight attendants can choose to work up to, but no more than,
95 hours a month.
   USAir sued the union last week amid stalled contract
negotiations with the 1,000 flight attendants of Pacific Southwest
Airlines, which merged with USAir in April.
   Flight attendants union spokeswoman Dee Maki said major
unresolved issues in the negotiations, which began in July and
currently are being mediated, include an airline proposal to pay
Pacific Southwest Airlines' former attendants at a different rate
than USAir's.
   USAir has a two-tiered pay system for its flight attendants, and
the proposal for Pacific Southwest Airlines workers would create
two additional tiers until parity is attained in three years, she
said.
   If USAir could have proved union involvement in the Memorial Day
job action, the flight attendants union could have been in
violation of the federal Railway Labor Act, which prohibits
organized work slowdowns, strikes, sickouts and other such actions
during contract negotiations.
   On Thursday, Ms. Maki testified she told attendants at union
meetings and in written memos in May that extra flying time was
voluntary but did not try to discourage members from working
overtime.
   ``We told them we will not sponsor anything like that,'' she
said.
   But USAir attorney Thomas Reinert said impromptu notices posted
in crew lounges encouraging an overtime boycott and statements Ms.
Maki made to the press expressing her delight over the job action
were evidence of union involvement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
