<1ST_LINE>u f AM-India-Carbide     06-23 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Carbide,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indian Government Files Contempt Petition Against Union Carbide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government lawyers on Thursday filed a
contempt of court petition against Union Carbide Corp. for
demanding that a judge in the district court be removed from his
position, the United News of India reported.
   A.M. Mathur, the advocate general of Madhya Pradesh state, filed
the petition in the state High Court in Jabalpur, the news agency
said. Jabalpur is 347 miles southeast of New Delhi.
   The petition said a Union Carbide request that Bhopal District
Judge M.W. Deo excuse himself from hearing the lawsuit against the
giant U.S. chemical company amounted to contempt of court.
   The Indian government has filed a $3 billion suit against Union
Carbide for a toxic gas leak from one of its subsidiary pesticide
plants in Bhopal, India. The gas leak in December 1984 killed
nearly 3,000 people and injured more than 20,000 others, in the
world's worst industrial disaster.
   Judge Deo ruled last December that Union Carbide must pay $192
million to the gas victims as ``interim relief.''
   The ruling, upheld by the state high court, was termed unfair by
Union Carbide because, the company said, Deo had not ruled on the
merits of the case. Union Carbide lawyers then filed an application
asking Deo to excuse himself.
   Deo in a ruling last week refused to dissociate himself from the
case, saying there were no legal grounds for the request.
   The contempt of court application Thursday said that Union
Carbide's request was a direct attack on Deo and an attempt to
intimidate him. It was designed to obstruct the course of justice,
the petition said.
</TEXT>
